<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Secrets Agent</TITLE></HEAD>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (e-mail:jgang@jamesgang.com) -->

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/index.html">
<IMG width=378 height=27  SRC="/docs/images/tisbanner.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=115 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/cprofile.gif" border=0 ALT="cprofile">
</center>
<HR  size=2 >
<!-- Main Body -->

<center>
<IMG width=303 height=193  SRC="/docs/images/walker.gif" border=0 ALT="Stephen Walker, CEO; Photo: Doug Kapustin Montage: F.James"></center>

<center><H1>SECRETS AGENT</H1></center>
<P>
<b>Stephen Walker holds the key to Internet security</b>
<P>
<I>Howard Community Times, March 28, 1996; Story by Darren M. Allen</I>

<P><blockquote>
	<h3>For a man whose life's work is keeping other people's secrets, Stephen Walker has been doing a lot of talking.</H3>
<P>
	The 56-year-old high-tech entrepreneur has been talking to Congress, talking to researchers, talking to America's spy agencies - talking to just about anyone willing to consider his solutions to a problem as old as the Internet.
<P>
	Left unresolved, it's a problem that will pose obstacles to computer-based banking, commerce and communication, Walker insists.
<P>
	Walker and his Trusted Information Systems, Inc. are at the forefront of a nationwide effort to give businesses and individual computer users a way to keep private communications out of government hands.
<P>
	Until now, the 12-year-old Glenwood firm hasn't gone out of it's way to attract attention, plugging away in relative obscurity to help make cyberspace safe from government intrusion. In fact, the nondescript red-brick headquarters on Route 97 might as well be a collection agency or an insurance office. Its undistinguished appearance masks what Walker hopes is the secret to turning the Internet into a powerful business tool, instead of a playground for on-line hackers.
<P>
	Even Richard Story, director of the Howard County Economic Development Authority, only became aware of TIS's presence here after the company asked county planning officials to approve its expansion plans.
<P>
"They are clearly outside of the envelope where we'd expect a high-tech company to be," Story said.
<P>
	Indeed, even though Story noted that Howard County lacks a high-tech corridor similar to Montgomery County's Interstate 270, most technology firms are found in Columbia  business parks, not in the county's rural west.
</blockquote>

<P>
