<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>TIS Security Consulting</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=61 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/projects.gif" border=0 ALT="Projects">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 6>TIS Advanced Research and Engineering</font>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<IMG width=375 height=253 SRC="/docs/images/flag2.gif" border=0 ALT="Flag">
</CENTER>
<Blockquote>

TIS is internationally renowned for the research in information systems
security.
We are actively participating in government research contracts and internal
research and development projects that require trust engineering analysis,
expertise on general computer and communication security, and development of
prototype systems that advance the state of the art in trusted systems
technology. Under DARPA and National Laboratory sponsorship, TIS staff are
performing leading research in the areas of access control, cryptography,
security services for Internet mail, trusted distributed file systems, secure
distributed operating systems, trusted operating systems, and integrated
Fortezza support. In addition to our innovative research efforts, TIS provides
trusted systems engineering and consulting to a number of major Government
organizations and acquisition programs.
The projects described below are representative of TIS' research and
engineering activities.
<UL>
<H3>Domain Type Enforcement (DTE) </H3>
For Distributed Object Control
Under DARPA funding, TIS demonstrated how innovative access control
software can provide significant, practical improvements in the security
of DoD
and civil-sector computer systems, particularly those based on the widely
used
UNIX operating system.  The demonstration prototype provides strong, flexible
administrative control over existing programs and data on both autonomous and
networked systems. The prototype attaches type attributes to system objects,
such as network messages, and mediates the ability of processes in different
domains to access objects of different types.

<H3>DTE Firewalls</H3>
DARPA-sponsored research is developing three successive research prototypes
to demonstrate the ability to safely use emerging network applications.
The first
prototype employs DTE within firewalls and selected hosts to encapsulate
network applications and proxies, thereby confining the damage they can
inflict
as a result of bugs, flaws, or intentional attack. Next, new generation
firewalls will
provide cryptographically protected coordinated DTE protection across the
Internet. Finally, globally accessible Domain and Type Authority (DTA) servers
will provide directory-like services so that firewalls can dynamically
identify the
types of information that can be safely exchanged with other firewalls.

<H3>TIS/MOSS (Mime Object Security Services)</h3>
MIME Object Security Services (MOSS), a Privacy Enhanced Mail (PEM)
derivative that is a Proposed Internet Standard for adding security
services to
Multi-Purpose Internet Mail Extensions (MIME), uses digital signatures and
encryption to provide origin authentication, integrity, and
confidentiality to MIME
objects.  TIS/MOSS is a security toolkit that provides digital signature and
encryption services for MIME objects.   It includes an integration with
the Rand
MH Message Handling System, a free mail user agent.  It also includes both a
generic application interface and a linkable library interface that
facilitates its
integration with other email user agents.


<H3>User-Level Truffles</H3>
TIS is extending the security functionality of the Ficus distributed file
system to
allow two or more individuals to securely share files across the Internet.
This
research aims to provide an efficient mechanism for joining selected segments
of file systems on selected machines across the Internet in a highly automated
manner consistent with those machines' access control policies.

<H3>Secure Distributed Processing</H3>
Under DARPA and Rome Laboratory sponsorship, TIS is developing an
infrastructure for the rapid deployment of distributed applications that can
interoperate among high-assurance trusted systems and conventional untrusted
systems.  This effort is based on an approach that incorporates secured CORBA
mechanisms into security architectures that control distributed client/server
interactions. Access control uses Domain Type Enforcement (DTE) technology
integrated with object-oriented techniques for distributed object-management
architectures.  This effort will result in distributed application
security for remote
clients and servers in trusted and untrusted enclaves.  Several prototype ORB
Servers are being developed along with new object-oriented DTE mechanisms to
achieve these objectives.  The trusted system base for this work is the
Trusted
Mach system with distributed O/S extensions developed by the Triad project.
These extensions include: distributed inter-process communication using the x-
kernel network protocol framework, distributed thread migration, scheduling
coherence, and passive servers; replication of servers and objects; and a
scheduling framework that supports an adaptable real-time scheduling policy.

<H3>Internet Infrastructure Protection (IIP)</H3>
Under a DARPA contract, TIS investigating ways of enhancing the Internet
infrastructure protocols using public key cryptography and other techniques to
provide protection against accidental or malicious failures by participants or
outsiders.  In particular, we are designing and implementing a digital
signature
toolkit to support data origin authentication and data integrity security
services.
These services are the cornerstone of protecting the Internet
infrastructure from
disruption.  Two vital infrastructure protocol areas are targeted for
integration
with this toolkit -- the Domain Name System, which provides a translation
of host
names to Internet addresses, and routing protocols, which provide the
mechanism by which messages are transmitted from source to destination
through the Internet.  The DNS security portion is now available.

<H3>International Cryptography Experiment (ICE)</H3>
This DARPA-funded project promotes cryptography in the international use of
computer software applications (e.g., word processors, electronic mail
programs,
electronic commerce and funds transfers). Cryptographic Application Program
Interfaces (CAPIs) provide the technical "glue" to combine applications and
cryptographic services.  The current approach is to provide mass-market
software vendors with a security architecture and components that will
allow their
products to use cryptography without including cryptographic implementations
within their code.  Applications can call cryptographic functions in a generic
manner, and users can provide "approved" cryptographic modules at the time of
use. International approval would be sought for products to meet international
requirements.


<H3>FORTEZZA</H3>
TIS is involved in several projects related to the integration of NSA's
FORTEZZA encryption technology.
<P>
<UL> <B>MOSS/Fortezza</B><BR> TIS is investigating the integration of the NSA-developed Fortezza PCMCIA crypto card into the Internet MIME Object Security Services (MOSS) protocols.  As illustrated in the UNIX-based prototype,  the integrated TIS/MOSS/Fortezza software employs the MOSS protocols and security services, including message integrity, originator authenticity, non-repudiation of origin (with asymmetric key management), and (optional) data confidentiality.  <P> <B>Gauntlet Internet Firewall/Fortezza</B><BR>

TIS has incorporated a Fortezza-based unilateral I&A capability into the
Telnet
and FTP protocols and the HyperText Transfer Protocol (HTTP), which is used
for World Wide Web (WWW) access into the TIS GauntletTM Internet Firewall
software for the Defense Information Systems Network - Near Term (DISN-NT).
The Telnet and FTP implementations employ the public-key entity authentication
techniques specified in NIST Proposed Standard for Public Key Cryptographic
Entity Authentication Mechanisms.
<P>
<B>TMACH/Fortezza</B><BR>

TIS explored the use of the Fortezza card with various scenarios involving the
TMach system.  The TMach system was configured to provide a Fortezza-based
Core Cryptographic Service in the trusted computing base (TCB) in order to
demonstrate how this TCB-assured cryptography could be used to regrade mail
for transmission over an untrusted network.
TIS also demonstrated a prototype of the Gauntlet Internet firewall running on
the TMach system.  In addition to the standard firewall proxies, this
prototype
included mail guard functionality.  The mail filter verified that every
message had
been encrypted and signed before it left the enclave. Mail guards were used to
protect enclaves that included untrusted systems.  A high-assurance mail guard
was required to verify that the message had been properly protected before
it left
the enclave.
</UL>
</UL>
<P>

