<!-- Main Body -->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<center>
<Font size= 6>Principles for Use of Encryption and Key Recovery</FONT>
<P>
<b>Stephen T. Walker<br>
Joan Winston<P>

Trusted Information Systems, Inc.<br>
August 28, 1996<P></b>
</center>


<H3>Introduction</H3>

For the past several years, TIS has been pursuing a "middle ground"
solution to the costly and divisive struggle between the public's
interests in unrestricted use of cryptography and governments' (the
U.S. and others) interests in ensuring access to the encrypted
communications of terrorists and criminals.  Until recently,
governments have very effectively used export controls on products
containing cryptography to control the use of cryptography by law
abiding individuals and organizations in the U.S. and throughout the
world. <P>

The focus of this debate is becoming more intense as terrorist
bombings in the U.S. heighten the calls of hard liners in law
enforcement for prohibitions on cryptography, while hard liners in the
private sector demand unrestricted export of cryptographic products.
Unfortunately, if either side were to prevail unilaterally, we all
will lose.  There are valid issues on both sides of this debate that
we had all best try to understand. <P> 

In seeking a middle ground on this incredibly contentious issue, we
started with what many believe is an essential component of any sound
cryptography policy:  make sure there is a way for the owner of the
original information to recover it in an emergency or unusual
circumstance.  The corporation that widely uses cryptography without
such a recovery mechanism faces difficult times when one of its
employees becomes ill or quits.  Some form of user-owned and
user-controlled, emergency key-recovery system is essential if
cryptography is to provide the security utopia that everyone is
seeking.  And, to the extent that such key-recovery capabilities
become widely used by law abiding industries, law enforcement, using
conventional search warrants and wiretaps, can be assured of access to
illegal activity within those industries.  [Sadly, until this happens,
the only real losers in this struggle are these law abiding
individuals and organizations.] <P> 




<H3>The TIS Principles</H3>

	Trusted Information System's  RecoverKey<font size=1>TM</font>   technology family
(patents pending) provide means for emergency recovery of encryption
keys.  In developing our RecoverKey technology concepts, we evolved a
set of principles to guide our efforts.  These principles build upon
each preceding principle (e.g., #3 depends upon #1 and #2).  Taken
together, we believe that these principles define a sound basis for
evolving an acceptable and workable solution to the national dilemma
on cryptography export policy. <P>

<DL>
<DT><B> <DD>1.
 No domestic controls on cryptography.  Anytime, anywhere. </B> <P>
	
There are now no domestic controls on use of encryption in the United
States or most other countries.  That is as it should be.  It would be
unacceptable to establish U.S. government controls on domestic use of
encryption, and TIS would strongly oppose any such initiative.   TIS
also would resist any attempts to deploy encryption technology in such
a way as to create de facto domestic controls in the United States or
anywhere else.   <P> 

<DT><B>
<DD>2.	Unconstrained user key recovery must not be controlled and
should be encouraged. </B> <P>

Users of strong encryption need user-controlled emergency key
recovery.<SUP><A HREF="#note1">1</A></SUP> Emergency key recovery
should be simple, affordable, and easy to use.  Its use should be
encouraged as part of sensible key management and sound information
management. <P>

If important messages, files, or databases are stored in encrypted
form, the user (or his/her organization , family, or heirs) will
eventually want to decrypt them.  If the decryption key is intact and
readily available, no problem.    <P>

But suppose the right key isn't readily available.  The person who
normally has access to the key may be on vacation or have met with a
mishap.  The key may have been corrupted, lost, or destroyed
(maliciously or by mistake).  Even assuming away these eventualities,
consider that stored, encrypted files may need to be retained for
years or decades.  The plaintext, however, must be recoverable so that
the file or data can be used, or updated, or backed up.  If archives
are encrypted, keeping track of  "editions" or versions of files and
the corresponding generations of keys is complex.  Given the value of
the encrypted information, as well as the value of being able to get
access in a timely fashion, it makes sense to have a backup means for
emergency key recovery. <P>

Since there are no domestic controls on encryption, domestic users
should have an entirely unconstrained choice as to whether and how
they provide emergency key recovery.  If user controlled key recovery
is left unfettered by governmental constraints, users will have a wide
variety of alternatives and prices to choose from, including the
(perhaps costly) choice not to use recovery at all. <P>

<DT><B>
<DD>3. Specific constraints on user key-recovery techniques may be useful
and acceptable to some for relaxation of export controls on
encryption. </B> <P>

Historically, with cryptography considered a military technology and
encryption products with keys longer than 40 bits treated as munitions
under State Department export controls, national security concerns
have always outweighed commercial and economic concerns.  That has
been difficult for U.S. companies who have been unable to freely
export products containing DES encryption, let alone very strong,
triple-DES encryption.  Tight controls on exports have affected the
domestic supply of encryption products and, therefore, have also been
bad for U.S. consumers.  <P> 

<b>The Administration's new export policy offers easier export of good
encryption, strong encryption,  -- even <EM>very strong</EM> encryption -- in
exchange for use of  key-recovery techniques that meet government
export criteria.</B>    <P>

The "exportable " version of TIS's encryption-key recovery system
(i.e., RecoverKey-InternationalTM) is constrained to meet the export
criteria set by the U.S. government.  It can still be used as an
emergency access system when an individual user or corporation needs
to recover an encryption key that has been lost, damaged, or is
otherwise unavailable.  However, the government interest in the system
is so that it can be used  for authorized law enforcement or national
security purposes, according to legal process.   <P>

The tradeoff means that product developers can use
RecoverKey-International technology in their products to qualify for
transfer of an encryption product's export Commodity Jurisdiction to
the Commerce Department.  Commerce Department CJ recognizes that an
encryption product is a "dual use" commodity that can be exported
under the more flexible and market-oriented Commerce Department
controls.  Having Commerce Department CJ can allow products to be
readily exported and used throughout the global information
infrastructure. <P>

<B>Importantly, the Administration's new encryption policy does not
change the unconstrained domestic production and use of encryption in
the United States. </B>  <P>

Users that are not concerned with exportability or international
communications and commerce can continue to use whatever encryption
they chose, with or without government-constrained key recovery.  <P>

When exportability is not a concern, the "unconstrained" version of
our emergency encryption-key recovery system offers full user choice
and control.  Unconstrained RecoverKey is not restricted by the
U.S. government's export criteria.  Since there are no restrictions on
domestic use of encryption in the United States, the RecoverKey
configuration can be used when desired to provide emergency recovery
of the plaintext of encrypted data.  This is accomplished via recovery
of the encryption key from a special RecoverKey "lockbox" (called a
Key Recovery Field, or KRF) associated with the encrypted data. The
user or his/her organization can choose whether or not to generate the
Key Recovery Field.  The RecoverKey variant of our technology allows
any choice of algorithm and key length (including triple-DES), and
does not constrain interoperability. <P>

The encryption key is recovered from the lockbox using through use of
a private-sector "lockbox service center" entity called a Key Recovery
Center, or KRC.  With the (domestic) RecoverKey system, users' choice
of KRCs is not constrained according to any government requirements.
For RecoverKey-enabled encryption, users can choose any Key Recovery
Center (KRC) they wish, even own their own KRC. <P>

<DT> <B>
<DD>3a) If this tradeoff is not useful or acceptable, then back to
Principle 2: no controls on unconstrained user recovery.   This would
include the unconstrained choice not to employ key recovery.
Technologies deployed to obtain relaxation of export controls should
not become <I>de facto</I> domestic controls on use of encryption. </B> <P>

TIS's emergency encryption-key recovery system is designed to avoid de
facto government regulation of domestic cryptography.  The TIS
technology does not inherently constrain user choice or control.  The
RecoverKey-International variant is constrained to provide an
international emergency key- recovery system that satisfies the
U.S. government's export criteria for Commerce Department CJ.  In the
RecoverKey-International configuration, the U.S. government's export
criteria impose constraints on KRF generation, interoperability, and
choice of  Key Recovery Centers, in exchange for easy exportability.
The government's export criteria may also impose constraints on key
length, at least for the near term (see below). <P>

The TIS RecoverKey technology family affords users more privacy and
control  than other techniques to facilitate export.  With both the
unconstrained and export-enabling  versions of RecoverKey, all
emergency recovery is on a session by session, message by message, or
file by file basis.  What is "recovered" is the key used to encrypt
that session, message, or file.  With the RecoverKey family of
technologies, there is never a central database of  encrypted
sessions, messages, or files.  There is no central database of  KRFs,
users' secret keys, or users' private keys.   <P> 
 
Unlike the Government "Clipper" key escrow proposal, Government
agencies would not hold any users' keys.  Government access to
encryption keys could only be obtained through private sector Lockbox
Service Center operators upon presentation of suitable legal
documentation.   <P>

 Unlike "workfactor reduction" schemes that deposit part of an
emergency access key for  the "export version" of a product directly
with the U.S. government, the RecoverKey-International system affords
overseas users the same protection--under rule of law--that domestic
users have.  <P> 

And, unlike "private-key escrow systems" where users' private keys are
stored with a third party for purposes of emergency access or export,
the RecoverKey family has been specifically designed so that users
need never relinquish their private keys to anyone.  <P>

<DT><B><DD>4.
Key length restrictions should not be imposed on exportable key
recovery techniques. </B> <P>

Sound technologies that satisfy governmental criteria for exportable
encryption need not be additionally constrained by artificial
restrictions on key length.   Key length restrictions for encryption
products that meet government export requirements should be dropped.
The Administration has indicated a possible first move toward such an
objective.  Vice President Gore's July 12, 1996 policy statement
included a statement that "permitting products using longer [than
64-bit] key lengths to be exported to specific industry sections"  was
under consideration as an initial step in export
liberalization.<SUP><A HREF="#note2">2</A></SUP>   <P>

Allowing strong encryption products with key recovery, including those
that implement triple-DES, to be easily exportable if the products
meet the export criteria, may actually benefit law enforcement and
national security -- as well as users -- by encouraging  the use of
key recovery internationally.  Such exportable, strong encryption
products may be preferred in the marketplace, serving to curb the
proliferation of  "domestic-only," strong encryption products with no
recovery capability at all.  <P> 


<DT><B><DD>5.
At least some key recovery techniques are independent of any
public-key infrastructure (PKI) or key-management infrastructure
(KMI).  Key recovery need not be linked to any particular PKI or KMI
for purposes of export. </B> <P>

Requiring exportable key-recovery systems to be linked to a particular
form of key management or to a particular public-key certificate
hierarchy is unnecessary.  Measures to do so, particularly if the
resulting "export" infrastructures would distort normal market forces
and "crowd out" alternatives in a still-fragile and rapidly changing
marketplace, would constitute an attempt at de facto domestic control
via technology deployment.  This is especially the case if the KMI/PKI
in question would require "escrow" or deposit of users' private keys. <P>

<DT><B>
<DD>5a) Users should never be required to turn over their private keys as
a condition for obtaining a public-key certificate.  </B> <P>
 
<DT><B>
<DD>5b) Users need not turn over their private keys to be able to use good
encryption internationally. </B><P>

The RecoverKey and RecoverKey-International systems do not depend on
any particular key management infrastructure (KMI), but will support
any KMI or public-key infrastructure (PKI).  Therefore, products
enabled with variants of  our technology can fit easily into the
Trusted Third Party framework for encryption that is the focus of
international cryptography principles now being formulated by the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD). <P>

Unlike other, longer term  proposals for a "bundled" public key
infrastructure and escrow system, the TIS emergency encryption-key
recovery system is available now.  Our RecoverKey systems are enabling
technologies that will support the development of a variety of key
management infrastructures, and will in turn be supported by them. In
the meanwhile, RecoverKey-International makes  easier exportability of
good cryptography possible in a way that meets users' privacy and
security concerns, as well as government access requirements for
export.  Users who don't need or want the tradeoff between key
recovery constraints and exportability , or who simply prefer to use
unconstrained encryption technology domestically, can use
unconstrained RecoverKey and enjoy user-controlled key recovery as
they see fit.  <P>

The TIS RecoverKey technology is application independent, as well as
platform independent.  Hardware and software developers - and their
customers - can choose the implementation and algorithms they prefer,
yet have a scaleable and cost-effective form of key recovery.  With
exportable configurations, these products can potentially be sold and
used worldwide.  With the unconstrained RecoverKey configuration,
users have total choice over whether and how the recovery system is
used.   <P>

</DL>



<H3>Status Of Our RecoverKey Efforts</H3>

TIS has combined its RecoverKey-International technology with our
GauntletTM  Internet Firewall. The combination allows customers to
operate cost-effective Global Virtual Private Networks over the
Internet through use of  DES IP encryption.  During 1996, we have made
significant progress in exporting Gauntlets enabled with
RecoverKey-International: <P> 

<UL>
<LI> In January 1996, TIS received the first-ever export approval for
56-bit DES encryption, enabled with RecoverKey-International (formerly
known as the "CKE" version of our Key Recovery Technology).  The
customer, a foreign-owned multinational corporation, agreed to operate
at least one Key Recovery Center (KRC) in the United States.   <P>
 
<LI> In June 1996, TIS received export approval for export to a
foreign-owned, multinational corporation operating entirely outside
the United States.  In this case, a Key Recovery Center will be
operated at the corporation's European headquarters, with no direct
U.S. connection.   <P>
 
<LI> In August 1996,  we began receiving export approvals for export
to U.S.-owned and foreign customers that wish to use a commercial Key
Recovery Center located in the United States. <P>
</UL>

Soon, TIS expects to receive a Commodity Jurisdiction (CJ)
determination that will allow general export of our firewall product
with 56-bit encryption to most locations worldwide.  In order to
obtain Commerce Department CJ, these firewalls will be enabled with
RecoverKey-International and be registered with a commercially
operated Key Recovery Center in the United States.  Future CJ export
determinations allowing general exportability of products using other
KRCs, both inside and outside the United States, are anticipated. <P>

TIS is actively licensing its RecoverKey Toolkit to other vendors of
products using cryptography, so that these vendors can provide their
customers with user-controlled emergency key recovery and product
exportability. <P>

<OL>

<LI> <A NAME="note1"></A> For purposes of this document, we categorize
"weak" encryption as having a symmetric key shorter than 56 bits,
"good" encryption as having a key with 56 bits (e.g., the Data
Encryption Standard, or DES), "strong" encryption as having a key
longer than 56 bits, and "very strong" encryption as having a key size
of 112 bits or more.

<LI> <A NAME="note2">Office of  the Vice President, "U.S. Cryptography
Policy: Why We Are Taking the Current Approach," July 12, 1996. 
</OL>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

