<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Internet Infrastructure Protection</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=112 height=15 SRC="/docs/images/nsecurity.gif" border=0 ALT="OS Security">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 6>Internet Infrastructure Protection</font>
<BR>
<Blockquote>

This Web page contains information on the Internet Infrastructure Protection 
task of INFOSEC for Networked Systems project funded by DARPA/ITO.<P>
View the <a href="/docs/images/arpa/iip-quad2.gif">quad chart</a> graphic for the IIP task.

<HR>

<H2>PROJECT SUMMARY</H2>

<H3>ARPA Order Number:</H3>

A941

<H3>CONTRACTOR:</H3>

Trusted Information Systems, Inc.
<BR>
3060 Washington Road
<BR>
Glenwood, Maryland  21738
<BR>
Phone: (301) 854-6889
<BR>
FAX:   (301) 854-5363

<H3>PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATORS:</H3>

George R (Russ) Mundy
<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:mundy@tis.com"><I>mundy@tis.com</I></A>
<BR><BR>
Sandra Murphy
<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:murphy@tis.com"><I>murphy@tis.com</I></A>

<H3>TITLE OF EFFORT:</H3>
Internet Infrastructure Protection


<!--<RELATED_INFORMATION>
http://www.tis.com/docs/Research/iip.html
</RELATED_INFORMATION>-->

<H3>OBJECTIVE:</H3>

The Internet infrastructure protocols, which provide the support for
the operation of the Internet, are designed with an implicit trust in
the integrity and authenticity of information contained in these
protocols.  The implicit trust is not reasonable in the present day
Internet environment and is very detrimental to survivability and
availability.  Accidental failure or malicious attack by outsiders
could result in widespread disruption of the Internet.  TIS efforts in
this task will prevent such disruptions by employing digital signature
and other techniques to support data origin authentication and data
integrity security services for certain chosen infrastructure
protocols.  TIS is also investigating the use of existing work to
improve the robustness of protocols in the face of Byzantine attacks,
i.e., arbitrary behavior from the protocol participants themselves.


<H3>APPROACH:</H3>

TIS is investigating methods of enhancing the Internet infrastructure
protocols using public key cryptography and other techniques.  These
methods provide protection against accidental or malicious failures by
participants or outsiders.  In particular, we will design and
implement a digital signature mechanisms to support data origin
authentication and data integrity security services.  These services
are the cornerstone of protecting the Internet infrastructure from
disruption.  Two vital infrastructure protocol areas will initially be
targeted for integration with these mechanisms -- the Domain Name
System, which provides a translation of host names to Internet
addresses, and routing protocols, which provide the mechanism by which
messages are transmitted from source to destination through the
Internet.
<P>

TIS has worked with the Internet community to specify architecture and
protocol enhancements to support the inclusion of data integrity and
data origin authentication security services in the Domain Name System
protocol.  These services will provide protection from the propagation
of inaccurate data and prevent domain name system servers from
masquerading as other servers.  The design will ensure that servers
with the enhanced security services can interoperate with non-enhanced
servers and clients. This will allow for the phased deployment of the
secure domain name system throughout the global Internet.
<P>


TIS has designed protocol enhancements to support these same security
services in routing protocols.  The security services will provide
protection from the introduction and propagation of invalid routing
data from hosts masquerading as valid routers.  Backward compatibility
with routers using non-enhanced versions of the software is a goal and
will provide for phased deployment.
<P>

TIS is also investigating ways of enhancing an existing routing protocol
with cryptographic and other techniques that provide Byzantine
robustness.  Such techniques have been known for some time, but have not
been incorporated into routing protocol products.  The enhanced protocol
will be designed and implemented to minimize performance degradation due
to the enhancements, and to ensure that enhanced and non-enhanced
protocols will coexist peacefully and cooperate.  There are several routing
protocols currently in wide use in the Internet.  TIS is presently
implementing enhancements to the OSPF intra-autonomous system routing
protocol.  TIS is also investigating enhancements to the BGP
inter-autonomous system routing protocol and to routing registries.

<H3>RECENT 1996 ACCOMPLISHMENTS:</H3>

<UL>
<LI>

Alpha testing of the TIS implementation of a security enhanced DNS was
completed.  The initial beta version incorporating the results of this
testing was completed and was made available via anonymous FTP for US
and Canadian testing.

<LI>
A prototype of the TIS design for a security enhanced OSPF was
completed.  Porting of this prototype to GateDaemon, a publically
available package of routing protocols, has begun.  The TIS design was
reported to the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) OSPF Working
Group for comment by the OSPF community; those comments have been
incorporated into the design.  The OSPF Working Group has proposed
publishing the TIS design as an Experimental RFC.


<LI>
TIS applied to the Department of State for export approval for the
security enhanced DNS.  The Department of State has informed us that our
product falls under the Department of Commerce's jurisdiction.  We have
therefore applied for a Commodity Jurisdiction from the Department of
Commerce.  Approval for world wide distribution will motivate the
adoption of these enhancements by commercial DNS vendors and providers
of publically available DNS products.

<LI>
TIS has worked with the DNSSEC Working Group of the IETF to keep them
apprised of TIS implementation experience and related design changes.
Based on this interaction, the DNSSEC Working Group has passed the
DNSSEC specification to the Internet Engineering Steering Group (IESG)
of the IETF for publication as a Proposed Standard.  Approval as an
Internet standard will be another motivation for adoption of these
enhancements by commercial DNS vendors and providers of publically
available DNS products.</UL>

<H3>FISCAL YEAR 97 PLANS:</H3>

<UL>
<LI>
Release of the final version of the TIS implementation of DNS security
enhancements for full, worldwide Internet deployment is planned for
1997.  TIS will develop tools to facilitate deployment of the secure
DNS capability.  The initial toolset will be available in 1997.  TIS
will also identify methods to extend the use of secure DNS.  TIS will
work with the Internet community to plan a phased deployment of the
security enhanced DNS.

<LI>
Completion and release of an implementation of a security enhanced
OSPF, integrated with the GateDaemon package of routing protocols,
will take place by March 1997.

<LI>
TIS will investigate extending the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) with
techniques similar to those used in OSPF to provide security for the
BGP routing protocol.  The initial research to extend OSPF provides a
secure routing protocol for intra-autonomous system routing while the
extensions to BGP are needed for inter-autonomous system routing.

<LI>
TIS will investigate the possibilities for providing similar data
origin authentication and data integrity security enhancements to
standard multicast routing protocols. </UL>


<H3>TECHNOLOGY TRANSITION:</H3>

Prototypes of any code we have developed or will develop are being
made available to the Internet community.  To ensure that this
technology is transferred to the community, we are working with the
standards groups responsible for the specifications of these
protocols, particularly the IETF, to see that the enhancements are
incorporated in the standards.  TIS will work with other researchers
and the vendor community to facilitate incorporation of techniques
and, as appropriate, software developed under this research into
commercial implementations of infrastructure protocols.  TIS is also
working with those providing publicly available software products that
implement infrastructure protocols (e.g., BIND, the public domain DNS
package, and the GateDaemon routing software from the GateDaemon
Consortium of Merit Network Systems, Inc.) to facilitate incorporation
of this technology.
<P>
TIS is working with the Department of State and the Department of
Commerce to receive approval for the widest possible approval for
distribution of software developed under this research.  The
Department of State has determined that the TIS implementation of the
DNS security extensions does not need their licensing approval for
export from the US and Canada.  TIS is currently waiting for a
determination by the Department of Commerce on the request for a
general export license.  Approval for distribution outside the US will
facilitate the incorporation of this technology into both commercial
and publically available implementations.
<P>
Beta versions of TIS implementation of the DNS security extensions and
the TIS digital signature toolkit are currently available from TIS.
Both implementations are written for Unix platforms.  Additional
implementations will be made available as this research progresses.
<P>
<hr>
The <a href="iip95.html">1995 DARPA/ITO Project Summary</a> contains more information about the IIP task.<P>

<ADDRESS>
Last modified: 3 July 1996
</ADDRESS>




</BLOCKQUOTE>
