<html>
<head>
<title>User-Level Truffles (ULT)</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</head>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#191970" vlink="#B22222" alink="#B22222">

<center><a href="/docs/research/index.html"><img src="/docs/images/tisr.gif" alt="TIS Research" border=0 height=28 width=216></a>
<hr size=2 >
<a href="/docs/research/network/index.html"><img src="/docs/images/nsecurity.gif" alt="Network Security" border=0 height=15 width=112></a>
</center>
<hr size=2 >
<!-- Main Body -->
<font SIZE=+3>User-Level Truffles (ULT)</font>
</p>
<center>
<p><img src="/docs/images/ult.gif" border=0 height=262 width=476></p></center>
<h3>User-Level Truffles: Secure and Distributed Sharing of Files Across
the Internet</h3>

<blockquote>
<p>User-Level Truffles is an <a href="http://www.ito.arpa.mil">DARPA/ITO</a>-sponsored
joint project between Trusted Information Systems, Incorporated
and the Computer Science Department of the <a href="http://www.cs.ucla.edu/">University of California at
Los Angeles</a>.  The start date of this project is July 1, 1995.

<P>
TIS and UCLA intend to build on their experience with replicated file systems and public key infrastructures for privacy enhanced mail to develop a
user-level, distributed, replicated file system, with security.  The resulting
system will be called User-Level Truffles (ULT).  ULT is the successor to <A
HREF=" http://ficus-www.cs.ucla.edu/ficus/arpa_web_pages/truffles_summary.html">Truffles</a>,
the Trusted Ficus File System. Truffles was built using Ficus from UCLA
and TIS/PEM from TIS. Ficus provides a distributed, optimistically replicated
file system service and TIS/PEM provides privacy enhanced mail and a public
key infrastructure. ULT will be built using Rumor from UCLA, a user-level
successor to Ficus, and TIS/MOSS from TIS, a MIME-oriented offshoot of
TIS/PEM. </p>

<p>Click <a href="http://ficus-www.cs.ucla.edu/ficus/arpa_web_pages/truffles_summary.html">here</a>
for a more detailed description of Truffles, the predecessor to User-Level
Truffles. </p>

<p>The diagram above illustrates the Internet operation of User-Level Truffles.
Three different sets of files (called &quot;volumes&quot;) are being shared
among three geographically distinct sites. One volume is shared between
TIS and UCLA, another between TIS and ARPA, and yet another between TIS,
ARPA, and UCLA. Each volume is distinct and access to one volume does not
imply access to any other. For instance, UCLA does not have access to the
volume shared between TIS and ARPA. </p>

<p>TIS's involvement in the ULT project is primarily in the area of security.
Some security-relevant areas of concern are: </p>

<ul>
<li>A security policy for ULT, against which a security analysis of ULT
can be performed. </li>

<li>Secure transport of shared file data: transport with authentication,
integrity, and confidentiality. </li>

<li>System administrator-controlled authorization of the capability of
users to share data with remote sites. </li>
</ul>

<p>For more detailed project information, see the 1996 <a href="/docs/research/network/ultps.html">Project Summary</a> for ULT. <p>
<address>Maintained by: <a href="mailto:jvc@la.tis.com">Jeff Cook (jvc@la.tis.com)</a>
<br>Last updated: 25 July 1996 </address>
</blockquote>

<center><p>
