<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 6>Security Consulting and Cooperative Research</font>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/docs/images/oss.gif">
</CENTER>
<Blockquote>
This Web page contains information on the Security Consulting and Cooperative
Research task of the INFOSEC for Networked Systems project funded by DARPA/ITO.

<HR>

<H2>PROJECT SUMMARY</H2>

<H3>ARPA Order Number:</H3>

8685

<H3>CONTRACTOR:</H3>

Trusted Information Systems, Inc.
<BR>
3060 Washington Road
<BR>
Glenwood, Maryland  21738
<BR>
Phone: (301) 854-6889
<BR>
FAX:   (301) 854-5363

<H3>PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATORS:</H3>

Martha Branstad
<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:mb@.tis.com"><I>mb@tis.com</I></A>
<BR>
<BR>
Dennis Hollingworth
<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:holly@.tis.com"><I>holly@tis.com</I></A>

<H3>TITLE OF EFFORT:</H3>
INFOSEC for Networked Systems

<H3>SUBTASK:</H3>
Security Consulting and Cooperative Research

<H3>OBJECTIVE:</H3>

The primary objective of this effort is to enhance the knowledge
and awareness of security issues of OS researchers conducting
research on new OS paradigms to encourage consideration of
security issues earlier in the operating system development
cycle than typically occurs.  A secondary objective is to identify
collaborative research topics that will help address the
security requirements of these new OS paradigm research efforts.

<H3>APPROACH:</H3>

TIS will interact and consult with university operating system
researchers and other DARPA-specified research groups to enhance
their knowledge of security issues and approaches.  In particular,
TIS will work with the University of Utah, the University of
Washington, the University of Arizona, the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, and the Oregon Graduate Institute of Science & Technology,
staying current with their research activities and providing security
consulting to them, explaining security concerns and working
cooperatively to suggest viable approaches to security problems.
TIS will attend operating system and security conferences and
meetings. 

<H3>RECENT 1996 ACCOMPLISHMENTS:</H3>

<UL>
<LI>
TIS engaged in early discussions with Brian Bershad of the University
of Washington's SPIN project to identify prospective security
consulting activities as well as TIS security research activities that
might apply to the SPIN project.

<P>
<LI>
TIS engaged in early discussions with Larry Peterson of the University
of Arizona's Scout project to identify prospective security
consulting activities as well as TIS security research activities that
might apply to the Scout project.

<P>
<LI>
TIS met with Jay Lepreau of the University of Utah to discuss his
current research work in the Flux Operating System and discuss areas
where Utah and TIS might collaborate on operating system security.
Work will begin when the initial design of the Flux project has been
completed and is ready for review.

</UL>

<H3>FISCAL YEAR 97 PLANS:</H3>

<UL>
<LI>
Provide security consulting to DARPA-specified university operating
system researchers performing research in new operating paradigms
on at least a bimonthly basis.  Develop collaborative research
efforts between TIS and these researchers as appropriate joint
research topics become evident.

<P>
<LI>
Develop and populate a WWW-accessible collection of informative
security-relevant papers and documents.  Included will be papers
and documents in the public domain felt to provide useful
information on identification and specification of OS security
policy statements and models and current security validation
methodology as well as published materials that demonstrate
such work in OS or related software development efforts.

<P>
<LI>
Attend operating system and security conferences and meetings to
stay abreast of new OS development activities and security
methodologies and issues.

<P>
<LI>
Produce white papers on technical issues relevant to new OS technologies
and development methodologies.
</UL>
<H3>TECHNOLOGY TRANSITION:</H3>

This task is, itself, primarily a technology transition effort intended
to pass security knowledge and insight embodied in the experiences and
research activities of the security community on to operating system
researchers conducting research on new OS paradigms.  Some of this new
OS paradigm research will undoubtedly influence the architectures of
COTS operating systems utilized by the DoD in the future and it is
important that security issues be given due consideration during the
performance of new OS paradigm research.  To facilitate this technology
transition effort, TIS will continue to interact with researchers
specified by DARPA and provide security consulting on identified topics of
interest.  TIS will also prepare papers and reports on topics considered
appropriate.

<P>

<ADDRESS>
Last modified: 3 July 1996
</ADDRESS>




</BLOCKQUOTE>
