<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Replaceable TCB Elements</title>
<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:holly@la.tis.com">
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=172 height=15 SRC="/docs/images/ossecurity.gif" border=0 ALT="OS Security">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 6>Replaceable TCB Elements</font>
<BR>
<Blockquote>

This Web page contains information on the Replaceable TCB Elements task of the
INFOSEC for Networked Ssytems project funded by DARPA/ITO.<P>
View the <a href="/docs/images/arpa/rtcb-quad2.gif">quad chart</a> graphic for more information on this completed project.
<HR>

<H2>PROJECT SUMMARY</H2>

<H3>ARPA Order Number:</H3>

8685

<H3>CONTRACTOR:</H3>

Trusted Information Systems, Inc.
<BR>
3060 Washington Road
<BR>
Glenwood, Maryland  21738
<BR>
Phone: (301) 854-6889
<BR>
FAX:   (301) 854-5363

<H3>PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATORS:</H3>

Martha Branstad
<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:mb@.tis.com"><I>mb@tis.com</I></A>
<P>

Rich Feiertag
<br>
<A HREF="mailto:feiertag@tis.com"><I>feiertag@tis.com</I></A>
<P>

<H3>TITLE OF EFFORT:</H3>

INFOSEC for Networked Systems

<H3>SUBTASK:</H3>
Replaceable TCB Elements


<!--<RELATED_INFORMATION>
http://www.tis.com/docs/Research/replace-tcb.html
</RELATED_INFORMATION>-->

<H3>OBJECTIVE:</H3>

Replacing an element of operating system software without 
affecting the operating of the remaining elements is fairly well 
understood.  However, replacing an element of a highly trusted 
TCB without affecting the assurance of the remaining elements is 
a largely unexplored and controversial area of research.  This 
task will explore replacing fundamental elements of a high 
assurance TCB.  Effort will be made to limit the effect on the 
assurance and the evaluation documentation.


<H3>APPROACH:</H3>

TIS will use the Trusted Mach system as the base high assurance 
system.  A fundamental portion of the system, e.g., the 
microkernel, will be replaced.  TCB servers and libraries will be 
converted to work with the new TCB element.  TIS will search for 
ways to replace specific elements of TCB analysis and 
documentation without invalidating the majority of the existing 
material.

<H3>RECENT 1996 ACCOMPLISHMENTS:</H3>

<UL>
<LI>

The TMach microkernel was successfully replaced with the MK++ 
microkernel.  This replacement was greatly simplified by the 
strongly modular architecture and design of the TMach TCB.  
Extensive use of layering, abstraction, and data hiding also 
played a significant role in facilitating the replacement.

<BR> <LI>
Because of the modular organization of TMach, the incorporation 
of the MK++ microkernel had minimal impact on the assurance 
process.  Strongly localized implementation of portions of the 
system responsible for specific requirements limited reassessment 
of requirements to only those for which the microkernel had some 
responsibility.  Similarly, the modular organization of TMach and 
its documentation has greatly reduced the impact of the 
microkernel replacement upon document review, testing,, code 
review and penetration testing.

<BR> <LI>
Covert channel analysis is typically performed on the system as a 
whole.  A method for modular covert channel analysis was 
developed that permits analysis on each element individually and 
then provides a method for composing the individual analyses to 
produce an overall system covert channel analysis.
</UL>

<H3>FISCAL YEAR 97 PLANS:</H3>

Contract completed 31 JUL 1996.

<H3>TECHNOLOGY TRANSITION:</H3>

The Trusted Mach technology has been selected by NSA for use in 
the MISSI program.  The technology has also been used as the 
basis of other research efforts such as the TRIAD project where 
it provided the basis for demonstrating a trusted, distributed 
file system and it is being used in a study to evaluate potential 
implementation strategies for the Department of Defense Goal 
Security Architecture, for example.  Also, TIS is in the process 
of moving TMach to product status, with a Beta release planned 
for availability in August, 1996.

<P>

<ADDRESS>
Last modified: 12 August 1996
</ADDRESS>




</BLOCKQUOTE>
