<HR><A NAME="OVERVIEW"></A></P>

<H2>Overview of ICE </H2>

<P><B>DESCRIPTION:</B> The International Cryptography Experiment (ICE)
calls for a series of experiments to promote the international use of cryptography
in common computer software applications (i.e., word processors, spreadsheets,
electronic mail systems) in a manner that honors individual national controls
on the import, export, and use of cryptography. The general approach being
advocated by numerous organizations in several countries is the use of
a Cryptographic Application Programming Interface (CAPI) to separate the
actual performance of the cryptographic functions from the software applications
that call for encryption of specific messages or files. ICE is an informally
structured program to coordinate the many efforts underway in the U.S and
several other countries to advance the general understanding of CAPIs and
their use to promote international cryptography.</P>

<P><B>THREE PHASE PROGRAM:</B> The ICE program involves three overlapping
phases. The CAPI development phase is a rapid effort to identify an initial
set of existing or emerging CAPIs for use in ICE. The ICE development phase
involves the development of application software and PCMCIA card implementations.
M a jor software developers incorporate cryptographic-based security functions
into their software products. Cryptographic modules which conform to the
CAPIs would be implemented within each participating country using available
cryptography. The experimental use phase sees simultaneous use of resulting
products by a wide variety of users in several countries to refine CAPI
and common usage techniques. As experimental use matures, international
standards organizations can promulgate CAPI standards.</P>

<P><B>CRYPTOGRAPHIC APIs:</B> The identification of security APIs, including
Cryptographic APIs (CAPIs), at various levels of software applications
provides the best approach to establishing the separation needed between
applications asking for cryptographic-based security services and and hardware
or software actually performing the cryptography. There are a number of
existing and emerging CAPIs and CAPI-related efforts at this time. The
ICE program will identify all practical CAPIs and attempt to coordinate
their use in experiments with commonly available software applications.
To the extent possible, all publicly available interface specifications
will be included in the initial set of ICE experiments.</P>

<P><B>APPLICATION PROGRAMS:</B> Major software developers use high-level
CAPIs to incorporate cryptographic-based security functions into their
common computer software applications (i.e., word processors, spreadsheets,
electronic mail systems). TIS/MOSS will be used, among others, to ensure
at least one application is available for the experiment. These products
should be exportable. Export will be coordinated with the government of
the country in which the product is developed.</P>

<P><B>MOTIVATION:</B> What can we do to break the &quot;ice&quot;? There
is an ever growing need by individuals, businesses, and governments for
improved protection of their sensitive information, and cryptography provides
the most practical means to protect this information. At the same time,
governments worldwide need to maintain their prerogatives to control the
import, export, and use of cryptography by their own countries. To break
the stalemate we must explore alternative solutions that may provide at
least partial solutions to this dilemma while satisfying the interests
of all sides. The seeds of one possible solution, ICE, come from a number
of sources within various national government and industry initiatives.
The U.S. government has introduced &quot;key escrow&quot; that makes available
strong cryptography while maintaining the interests of law enforcement.
The NSA's FORTEZZA initiative, isolates the cryptography from the computer
system, by placing it in a PCMCIA card, making it difficult to modify and
easier to control its distribution. The FORTEZZA initiative has defined
a set of interfaces, but they must be endorsed by the information systems
industry for the initiative to succeed. Various industry leaders such as
Hewlett-Packard and National Semiconductor have proposed the development
of additional PCMCIA card configurations that make us of standard CAPIs
and allow individual countries to implement their own collections of cryptographic
algorithms. In the United Kingdom, the MoD TDP is specifically geared to
define CAPIs and attempt to get the widely adopted by industry and governments
throughout the world.</P>

<P><B>WHERE DOES THIS LEAD?</B> This leads to an approach that will let
information system developers integrate security functions into their products
without actually providing any cryptography, so that users in individual
counties can use these products with cryptographic algorithms and techniques
acceptable in their own countries, while allowing government to maintain
their prerogatives on import, export, and usage controls. What is needed
now is an international consortium of interested parties in industry and
government, including mass-market software developers, cryptographic product
developers, and user communities and governments in several countries (U.S.,
U.K., Germany, etc.) to define CAPIs, drawing from existing and emerging
work, and place them into use on an experimental basis to prove the feasibility
of this approach!</P>

<P>
<HR><A NAME="ADDITIONAL"></A></P>

<H2>Additional Information on ICE</H2>

<P>Individuals and organizations that wish to participate in ICE or to
remain abreast of its activities are encouraged to send email to <A HREF="mailto:ice@tis.com">ice@tis.com</A>
</P>

<P>The <A HREF="ice.html">DARPA/ITO Project Summary</A> provides more information
on recent accomplishments and plans.</P>

<P>Numerous articles and papers have been written regarding ICE and CAPIs.</P>

<UL>

<LI><B>NEW:</B> <A HREF="nsacapi/capi19.htm">Security Service API: Cryptographic
API Recommendation, Second Edition, NSA Cross Organization CAPI Team, July
1, 1996.</A><P></LI>

<LI>A <A HREF="/docs/research/crypto/ice/summary3.html">summary</A> of
the discussions that occurred during the 3rd ICE/CAPI Workshop, held March
11-12 at the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST)<P></LI>

<LI>Dr. Brian Gladman, formerly of the SHAPE Technical Centre, prepared
a white paper, <A HREF="/docs/research/crypto/ice/gladman5.html">US Government
Controls on the Microsoft CryptoAPI</A>. Dr. Gladman is concerned that
the signature proposals will create an unbalanced situation in respect
of the general availability of good cryptographic modules within and external
to the US (and Canada). His white paper sets out his reasons for concern
and makes alternative signature proposals. This paper is also available
in <A HREF="/docs/research/crypto/ice/outline.doc">Microsoft Word (.doc)
format</A>.<P></LI>

<LI>Dr. Brian Gladman, formerly of the SHAPE Technical Centre, prepared
a white paper, <A HREF="/docs/research/crypto/ice/outline.html">An International
Cryptography Experiment: An Outline for An International Demonstration
of 'Plug and Play' Cryptography&quot;</A>, which describes the ICE Experiment
proposed at the 2nd ICE Workshop. This paper is also available in 
<A HREF="/docs/research/crypto/ice/outline.doc">Microsoft Word (.doc) format</A>.<P></LI>

<LI>A <A HREF="/docs/research/crypto/ice/summary2.html">summary</A> of
the discussions that occurred during the 2nd ICE Workshop, held last September
18-19, 1995 at the NATO SHAPE Technical Centre (STC) in The Hague, The
Netherlands.<P></LI>

<LI>We published an article, <A HREF="/docs/research/crypto/ice/dsl.html">Update
on the International Cryptography Experiment,</A> in the May 1995 issue
of the TIS Data Security Newsletter (DSL).<P></LI>

<LI>The DSL article incorporates material from our January 1995 update,
<A HREF="/docs/research/crypto/ice/update2.html">International Cryptography
Experiment (ICE) - Status Report.<P></A></LI>

<LI>The first <A HREF="/docs/research/crypto/ice/update.html">International
Cryptography Experiment (ICE) - Status Report</A> was published in August
1994.<P></LI>

<LI>Steve Walker's original paper, 
<A HREF="/docs/research/crypto/ice/paper.html">An International Cryptographic 
Experiment - A Solution to the International Use of Cryptography?,</A> 
appeared in April 1994.<P></LI>

</UL>

