<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Policy-Based Cryptographic Key Release System</TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>

<HR  size=2 >
<a href="/docs/research/crupto/index.html">
<IMG width=180 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/cryptographic.gif" border=0 ALT="cryptographic"></a>
</center>
<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<Font size= 6>Task Title: Policy-Based Cryptographic Key Release System</font>

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<h3>Part 1: Cryptographic Key Release Language Design and
Specification </h3>


<hr>

<h2>1.0. Statement of Work (SOW) </h2>

This statement of work is divided into two parts, one to be initiated
as soon as practical and the second to be initiated if the results of the
first part are satisfactory to the ARPA sponsor. The second part is written
and priced as an option to this SOW.

<h2>1.1 Background </h2>

All users of modern computer networks want to control and protect their
information with high assurance. Military commanders require the ability
to share vital and sensitive information with one group of allies one day
and a different group the next day. Federal users need to disseminate public
information about their programs widely but then control and protect the
information obtained in response to these programs. Corporations want control
over valuable, sensitive information, even when created by employees working
on individual projects. Individual computer users want assurance that they
can get access to their archived personal or financial information, including
in times of crises. 
<P>
<center><img width=432 height=288 src="/docs/images/ckr1.gif" border=0 ></center>
<P>
Part 1 of this
task is to design and specify a Policy-Based Cryptographic Key Release
Language that meets a broad set of requirements. The goal is to go well
beyond traditional, static rules for key release and develop a dynamic,
policy-based automated system that unifies and enforces the rules for release
specified by the owner of encrypted information as well as by all organizations
having jurisdiction over the information. The key release policy specification
language forming the foundation of the system provides a flexible vehicle
for users and organizations to describe/select an appropriate policy for
releasing the key that is protecting information under their control. Emphasis
will be placed on specifying a language that is easy to use and is understandable
by users as well as computers. The language design will build on relevant
technologies available in the research community but will extend and unify
the results in a cohesive security infrastructure that supports multiple
security services in multiple security domains. 

<h2>1.2 Scope </h2>

<p>
Part 1 of this task is to design and develop a prototype key release
language that meets the requirements of a variety of government users,
including military services for unclassified applications, commercial organizations,
and private users. Part 2 of this task will be to design a flexible, scalable
system that can be built easily but that provides appropriate assurance
(in a quantified manner) that the rules established for the release of
a cryptographic key will be followed. The term &quot;key release&quot;
as used in this statement includes several types of key usage, i.e., transferring
the only copy of a key; providing a copy of a key for permanent use; granting
authority to have a key used to access data for a period of time; granting
authority to have a key used for a specific, authorized purpose.

<p>
The requirements of various interests (e.g., individuals, corporations,
security vendors, security service providers, national law enforcement,
national security) in commercial cryptographic systems and for military
organizations in unclassified applications will be identified. Requirements
for international computer network applications, such as international
trade or commerce, will be considered in the design model.

<p>
Key release is a subset of what is called key usage and includes the
rules covering special requirements such as key backup or key recovery.
A key-usage requirement may be as simple as the ability to generate one's
own key, keep it in a personal security device such as a smartcard or token,
use it for any personal data storage encryption that the &quot;owner&quot;
desires, and never release it. The key release policy is simple to state
at a high level but may be complex in detail. The key release system needs
to encompass individual-based policies, group-based policies, role-based
policies, context- or environment-based policies, and authorization-based
policies. 

<p>

Part 1 of this task is to design a specification language for key release
policies, including the syntax and semantics of the language. The design
will assume that a security infrastructure will provide the desired key
release services developed in this project along with other similar security
services such as user authentication, digital signature certificate management,
and user release authorization. 

<h2>1.3 Technical Rationale and Plan for Achieving Goals </h2>

<p>
A cryptographic key release system is needed that provides dynamic and
flexible authorization rules for releasing the key. The system will allow
a set of authorization rules, collectively called a key release policy,
to be created to control the release of a key. A specification language
for the rules will be developed. A logical precedence will be included
for specifying who can establish rules, the precedence of rules established
by different people or different organizations for the same data, and how
the rules provided by all these people and organizations can be combined
in a single policy. 


<p>
<br>Part 1 of the task includes identifying the requirements for key release
of potential users, their managers (for organizational users), the law
enforcement organizations having jurisdiction in the location of use, and
the national security organizations having jurisdiction in the location
of use. A broad set of real and hypothetical requirements will be identified.
Real requirements will be used whenever possible (e.g., by talking with
users, their managers, and law enforcement personnel), and hypothetical
requirements will be used when required (i.e., when real requirements are
classified). The goal is to build a representative set of requirements
to be included in the release system but not to attempt to be comprehensive
or complete. </p>

<p>

Using a set of real and theoretical requirements for key release, a
release authorization language will be developed. Various hypothetical
scenarios will be defined (e.g., a multinational military communication
system, a government agency's archival system, an individual's personal
records management system, a family's financial system, a corporation's
vital records system, an international electronic commerce trading system)
for which various key release policies could be specified. After the initial
set of release rules is developed, a specification language will be designed
in which the rules can be expressed. The proposed research will not impose
constraints on who may need access to encrypted data and for what reasons
and in what circumstances but will focus on establishing a rich syntactic
language in which the diverse requirements (i.e., rules) for key release
can be expressed and on synthesizing automated methods of meeting the requirements
(i.e., enforcing the rules). Emphasis will be on mathematical, logical,
and computational tools that can provide controlled key release. Major
emphasis will be placed on the use of cryptographic (secret sharing) tools
to enforce release rules and to minimize reliance on trusted computer systems
to enforce the rules. 

<p>

A mathematical-like language will be designed that includes sets of
sets (data objects, persons, devices, groups, roles, locations, organizations,
environments, ...), operators (AND, OR, NOT, SUBSET-OF, CONTAINED-IN, M-OF-N,
ALL, SEQUENCE, ...), constraints (ALIVE, WORKING, UNBROKEN, LOST, BEFORE,
AFTER, MAXTIME, SUBPOENAED...), and relationships (=, &gt;, &lt;, COLONEL,
SUPERVISOR, PRIORITY-N,...). Various key release policies will then be
specified for data objects to be encrypted and managed by the participants
in each scenario. Extensions to the language will be permitted and supported
in the software toolkit and prototype implementation.

<h2>1.4 Government Coordination </h2>


Performance of this task will be coordinated with the staffs of ARPA,
NSA, NIST, and FBI. Points of contact will be established within each organization
to identify goals and constraints of the key release system, provide technical
assistance as needed, and review the results of the tasks before public
release. A list of the current points of contact in each of these organizations
will be maintained by the PI. 


<h2>1.5 Personnel </h2>

<p>
The personnel selected to perform this task provide technical expertise,
security experience, and organizational representation for this topic.
Dennis Branstad will be the principal investigator (PI) on the task, utilizing
the identified consultants and TIS staff members as needed. He has extensive
experience in computer security at NSA and NIST in cryptographic-based
standards meeting a wide spectrum of requirements. Dorothy Denning has
done extensive work with law enforcement organizations in seeking to devise
cryptographic systems that will not prevent access to (i.e., the ability
to decrypt) data when authorized in accordance with the laws of the U.S.
Burt Kaliski has worked extensively with numerous commercial organizations
in designing cryptographic algorithms for commercial applications. Russell
Housley and Warwick Ford will provide input on FORTEZZA export issues and
international security issues, respectively. 
<HR>

<h2>2.0 Deliverables </h2>

<p>The primary deliverable of Part 1 of this task is the Key Release Language
design. The set of requirement specifications used in designing the language
will be delivered prior to language design. One or more computer-based
language verifiers, or theorem provers, or syntax/semantics analyzers will
be used and evaluated as a basis of the key release system. The language
will be developed using appropriate formal methods anticipating the use
of cryptographic-based secret preserving and sharing algorithms.

<HR>

<h2>3.0 Schedule and Milestones </h2>

<TABLE BORDER = 1 CELLPADDING = 4>
<TR> <TD><I>Item</I> </TD> <TD><I>Months After SOT</I></TD> </TR>

<TR> <TD>Key Release Requirement Specifications (User, Manager, L.E., N.S.)</TD> <TD><CENTER>6</CENTER></TD> </TR>
<TR> <TD>Key Release Policy Specification Language Design</TD> 					 <TD><CENTER>12</CENTER></TD> </TR>

</TABLE>
<HR>
<h2>4.0. Key Personnel </h2>

<p>
Dr. Dennis K. Branstad (TIS - PI)

<p>
Dr. Dorothy Denning (Georgetown University - Consultant)

<p>
Dr. Warwick Ford (Nortel - Consultant)

<p>
Mr. Russel Housley (SPYRUS - Consultant)

<p>
Dr. Burton A. Kaliski (RSA Labs - Consultant) 

<p>
An optional task following successful design and specification of the
language will include designing and developing a system that implements
and enforces the types of release supported in the policy specification
language. The optional key release system will be designed to operate within
a larger security support infrastructure providing several similar services,
such as user authentication, user authorization, and digital signature
certificate management services.<P>
<HR>
The <a href="krp.html">DARPA/ITO Project Summary</a> provides more information on recent accomplishments and plans.  

</blockquote>

