<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Secrets Agent continued</TITLE></HEAD>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (e-mail:jgang@jamesgang.com) -->

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/index.html">
<IMG width=378 height=27  SRC="/docs/images/tisbanner.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=115 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/cprofile.gif" border=0 ALT="cprofile">
</center>
<HR  size=2 >
<!-- Main Body -->


<P>
<center>
<IMG width=331 height=160 SRC="/docs/images/trees.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS trees; Photo: F.James"></center>
<blockquote>
"People would ask,  "How can you run a company out in the middle of nowhere?" recalled Walker, sitting in an office overlooking rolling hills, a two-lane road and a thicket of trees that hide his 19th century farmhouse. "When I started, it was just me in my house."
<P>
	Today, Walker's TIS has grown from nine employees in its first year to 150 employees-140 in Glenwood - and four branch offices in Northern Virginia, Los Angeles, San Francisco and London.
<P>
	Walker decided to keep the business centered in Glenwood for personal convenience. Quite simply, Walker said that after chucking a 22-year career at the Department of Defense, with its daily drive to Northern Virginia, he kind of liked his new commute.
<P>
	"Because of what we do, we can be anywhere in the world," Walker said. "But I wanted to stay here."
<P>
	He looks forward to the completion of TIS's $2.2 million expansion this spring, which will double the size of the company's headquarters to 40,000 square feet.
<P>
TIS needs the space: Its annual revenues grew from $85,000 in 1984 to $17 million this year.
</blockquote>

<center>
<IMG width=345 height=164 SRC="/docs/images/ext.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS exterior; Photo: T. Timberlake"></center>

<P>
<B><h1>Safe in cyberspace</h1></B>
<P><blockquote>
Calling TIS a computer security firm is deceptively simple. The company's mission is to help businesses and individual computer users  build an electronic "firewall" around their files as they communicate in cyberspace.
<P>
To construct those walls, Walker hired high-tech bricklayers - mathematicians, physicists and engineers. These scientists sit at computer terminals and design mathematical formulas to block access to information.
<P>
Just as you once needed a password to gain entry into a favorite speakeasy, TIS "firewalls" seek to keep uninvited intruders away from an individual's bank accounts and medical records or a business's marketing plans.
<P>
Before founding TIS, Walker's defense work included stints at the supersecret National Security Agency, the Advanced Research Projects Agency and the Office of the Secretary of Defense.
<P>
According to industry experts, Walker helped to spearhead the Defense Department's Computer Security Initiative and to develop standards for computer security that are now accepted worldwide.
<P>
He also founded the National Computer Security Center at NSA, developing communications programs that laid the groundwork for the creation of the Internet.
<P>
"He's been a player for a long time," said Dorothy Denning, a Georgetown University computer science professor who has studied electronic security issues since 1972.
<P>
	Denning first heard about Walker's work when the Internet was in its infancy in the early '70s.
<P>
	Walker  left his comfortable government job in 1983 after taking stock of where he was and where he was likely to go.
<P>
"I decided there had to be more to life than commuting to the Pentagon everyday," he said.
	
<P>
Armed with a $30,000 federal pension, Walker embarked on a consulting career. He says he has since advised almost "all the major multinational companies" involved in computer security.
<P>
Walker started out with five clients, thinking he would stick with the consulting career until a "real job" opened up. But after nine months, he had no desire to leave Glenwood every morning to go to work for someone else in a large company.
<P>
	"After staying away from the terrible bureaucracy in the NSA and the Pentagon, I kind of liked the idea of working for myself," he confessed.
<P>
	By most measures, Walker is a leader in the computer security field - and a family man. He and his second wife, Brenda, a Mary Kay cosmetics consultant, have three children, along with three stepchildren.
<P>
	Walker's son, Kenneth, 27, works for the company as a software engineer, while Mathew, 20, a student at University of Maryland College Park, helps out during the summer.</blockquote>
<P>

