<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>
Key Recovery Technology Enables Strong Encryption Export
</TITLE>

<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" 
ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/index.html">
<IMG width=378 height=27
SRC="/docs/images/tisbanner.gif" border=0
ALT="TIS"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<a href="/docs/corporate/press/index.html">
<IMG width=95 height=16
SRC="/docs/images/pr.gif" border=0
ALT="press"></a>
</center>
<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->


<Font size= 5>

TIS Key Recovery Technology First To Enable General Purpose Export For Very
Strong Encryption
</Font>
<P>
<Blockquote>

(Glenwood, MD) -- In a development that may signal the beginning of the end
of the long standing encryption export control controversy, Trusted
Information Systems (NASDAQ:TISX) today announced that products using very
strong cryptography with its RecoverKey&#153; technology have been approved for
general purpose export control under new Commerce Department export 
regulations.<p>

Among the products receiving this approval are 1) the TIS Gauntlet&#174; 
Internet Firewall with both the 56-bit Data Encryption Standard (DES) 
algorithm and Triple-DES, and 2) the TIS Cryptographic Service Provider 
(CSP) which supports the Microsoft Cryptographic Application Programming 
Interface(CAPI) using both DES and Triple-DES encryption.<P>

With this approval, TIS has achieved the first transfer of a set of
commercial products with very strong cryptography to the Commerce Department
under the US governments new encryption export policy.  TIS RecoverKey
technology is the first user-controlled encryption key recovery process
which can qualify cryptography products for general export, regardless of
encryption algorithm or key length.
<p>
"This announcement represents a major milestone in the evolution of network
security," said Stephen T. Walker, President and CEO of TIS.  "Until now,
strong encryption, an essential ingredient in protecting sensitive
information, was generally unavailable because of government imposed export
controls.  From now on, general purpose export of very strong encryption
will be available to any cryptography vendor, and products using such 
encryption can proliferate in both domestic and international markets.  
This development will allow full realization of the potential for 
electronic commerce."
<p>
<b>New Export Rules for Stronger Key-Recovery Encryption</b> 
<p>
As set forth in a Presidential Memorandum and Executive Order (E.O.13026,
November 15, 1996), export controls for all commercial encryption products
will soon be moved to the Commerce Department.  This new policy also defines
new rules for general exportability of hardware and software products that
use an approved key-recovery method such as TIS RecoverKey, regardless of
algorithm or key length. 
<p>
The approvals announced here are fully consistent with these new government
policies.
<p>
<b>Industry-Leading Technology Available for License</b>
<p>
Forty major information technology vendors and users, including TIS, have
formed a Key Recovery Alliance to encourage global, interoperable solutions
that use strong encryption.  TIS has affirmed its commitment to a worldwide
standard by offering its RecoverKey technology for license to hardware and
software vendors in the United States and abroad.   For example,
Hewlett-Packard, Inc. recently announced that TIS RecoverKey will provide a
key recovery capability for HPs International Cryptographic Framework (ICF).
<p>


<b>About Trusted Information Systems, Inc.</b><p>

Trusted Information Systems, Inc., is a leading provider of comprehensive 
security solutions for protection of computer networks, including global 
Internet-based systems, internal networks and individual workstations and 
laptops.  The company develops, markets, licenses and supports the Gauntlet
family of firewall products and other network security products, and 
provides cryptography and security consulting training, advanced research 
and engineering, and services for commercial and government customers.  For
more information, contact TIS at (301) 527-9500.  The TIS home page on the 
World Wide Web is http://www.tis.com<P>

<HR>

<I>For more information, please contact:<P></I>
<Table cellpadding=2>

 

   <TR> <TD>
    <b>Homayoon Tajalli</b> <br>
        Trusted Information Systems, Inc. <br>
        (301) 854-6889<br>
