<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> TIS's Gauntlet&#174; Internet Firewall First Firewall to Support Microsoft's 
     Authenticode&#153; Technology</TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" 
ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="http://www.tis.com/docs/index.html">
<IMG SRC="http://www.tis.com/docs/images/gtop.gif" border=0>
<HR  size=2 >
<a href="/docs/corporate/press/index.html">
<IMG width=95 height=16
SRC="http://www.tis.com/docs/images/pr.gif" border=0
ALT="press"></a>
</center>
<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<H2>TIS's Gauntlet&#174; Internet Firewall First Firewall to Support Microsoft's 
     Authenticode&#153; Technology</H2><br>
<i>Digital Signatures for ActiveX Executables and Java Applets Checked at 
     the Firewall<br>
     
     Firewall forwards only those executables and applets which were 
     securely transferred from trusted sources</i>
<P>
Glenwood, MD, December 9, 1996 -- Trusted Information Systems (Nasdaq: TISX), a leading 
     provider of network security software and services, confirmed today 
     that its Gauntlet&#174; product development team has been working closely 
     with Microsoft Corporation to support Microsoft's Authenticode&#153; 
     technology in the Gauntlet Firewall product line.  Authenticode's 
     signature verification capability gives network security 
     administrators a way to selectively control against the potential 
     virus and trojan horse attacks that could result from individual 
     users' downloading of ActiveX and Java objects, without having to 
     block out all objects. <P>
     
     Microsoft's Authenticode technology uses cryptographic mechanisms to 
     provide accountability and an assurance of integrity for software 
     objects downloaded over the Internet.  An unforgeable digital 
     signature, attached to an ActiveX or Java object, enables applications 
     to identify the publisher of the software object and to verify that 
     the software has not been tampered with during the delivery process.  
     The HTTP application gateway within the Gauntlet Internet Firewall 
     validates that programs arriving across the web are correctly signed 
     and come from an approved source.  Files that are unsigned or come 
     from non-approved vendors are not allowed through the firewall.<P>
     
     TIS was the first to offer Java and ActiveX blocking as a way to 
     address associated virus and trojan horse threats.  Steven Lipner, 
     Executive Vice President and General Manager for Network Security 
     Products at TIS, remarked, "Now, with Authenticode's signature 
     verification, we are the first to take the next step -- controlled 
     access to software from providers you trust.  Malicious objects simply 
     won't get delivered inside the organization where they can do damage.  
     They'll be stopped at the security perimeter." <P>
     
     Hank Vigil, General Manager of Microsoft's Internet Commerce Business 
     Unit, concurs that signature verification using Authenticode at the 
     firewall represents an important advance toward unleashing the power 
     of Web-distributed computing.  Vigil commented, "Authenticode and 
     Gauntlet provide the best of both worlds: strong security and dynamic 
     access to the latest and most powerful web technology.  We are pleased 
     that TIS has joined with us to promote better security for customers 
     using the Internet." <P>
     
     TIS will be demonstrating the signature verification features in the 
     Gauntlet Internet Firewall at the upcoming Internet World show in New 
     York (Booth 951).  Authenticode will be available on all Gauntlet 
     Internet Firewall platforms.<P>

  <!-- Next -->
<hr>

<address>For more information, please contact:</address>
Stacey Fairbairn<BR>
voice: (301) 527-9500<BR>
fax:  (301) 527-0482<BR>
email:  <A HREF="mailto:<sef@tis.com">sef@tis.com</A>

