<HEAD>
<TITLE>GAUNTLET&#174; FORCEFIELD&#153; From TIS Repels Attacks On Web Servers</TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" 
ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="http://www.tis.com/docs/index.html">
<IMG SRC="http://www.tis.com/docs/images/gtop.gif" border=0>
<HR  size=2 >
<a href="/docs/corporate/press/index.html">
<IMG width=95 height=16
SRC="http://www.tis.com/docs/images/pr.gif" border=0
ALT="press"></a>
</center>
<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<H2>Gauntlet&#174; Forcefield&#153; From TIS Repels Attacks On Web Servers</H2><br>
<i>First Software Product to Comprehensively Address the Security of Web 
     Servers</i>
<P>
Glenwood, MD, December 9, 1996 -- Trusted Information Systems (Nasdaq: TISX) today 
     announced a first-of-its-kind product designed to end unwanted 
     penetration of web servers. Based on Gauntlet&#174; Internet Firewall 
     technology, the Gauntlet ForceField&#153; helps prevent most common web 
     server attacks, including graffiti and flooding.  Gauntlet ForceField 
     hardens the web server's operating system, repels attempts to 
     penetrate the server system, and sets off "smoke alarms" when a 
     penetration attempt is noted.<P>
     
     "Nobody wants to click on their home page and find the site full of 
     some hacker's graffiti," says TIS Commercial Division President, 
     Harvey Weiss. "ForceField puts the power of Gauntlet security to work 
     to stop such attacks."<P>
     
     The new product includes a strong authentication process, so that a 
     site's own webmaster, working remotely, can have access to the 
     underlying HTML files.  Users may also take advantage of the system's 
     virtual private network capability -- the option of totally private 
     remote access by authenticated users over an encrypted communication link to the web
server. <P>
   
   
     Gauntlet ForceField will ship in January at a price of $495.  Version 
     1.0 is designed to work with all UNIX-based web server products such 
     as those from Netscape, Open Market, Apache and the National Center 
     for Supercomputing Applications (NCSA).  A version for Microsoft IIS 
     is expected in early 1997.<P>
     
     See Forcefield demoed at Internet World, booth #951.  
     New York, December 11-13.<P>
<!-- Next -->
<hr>

<address>For more information, please contact:</address>
Stacey Fairbairn<BR>
voice: (301) 527-9500<BR>
fax:  (301) 527-0482<BR>
email:  <A HREF="mailto:<sef@tis.com">sef@tis.com</A>

