<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Security Policy Development</TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) --->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/products/consulting/index.html">
<IMG width=230 height=33  SRC="/docs/images/tisc.gif" border=0 ALT="tis consulting"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=109 height=16  SRC="/docs/images/policy.gif" border=0 ALT="Policy">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 6>Security Policy Development Services</font>
<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>


<H3>The Foundation for Security</H3>

The information security policy is the foundation on which all information security efforts are built.  It is a visible representation of corporate priorities, and should definitively state all the underlying assumptions that drive security activities.  The policy gives credence to those efforts by asserting senior management's commitment to security.  In order to be effective, the policy must be understood by everyone as the product of a directive from an authoritative and influential person at the top of the organization.
<P>
Creating a security policy is nothing more than developing a framework for how to deal with computer and network security. Optimally, the time, energy and money put into a security strategy should be less than the time, energy and money used to recover from a security breach.  As a first step to achieving this goal, an organization must conduct a risk assessment to determine the cost/benefit tradeoffs involved in developing their policy.

<BR>
<H3>A good security policy should:</H3>
<UL>
	<LI>Support the organization's mission and goals
	<LI>Describe the overall security approach
	<LI>Define roles and responsibilities for implementation of countermeasures;
	<LI>Define appropriate behavior for users and administrators (sometimes represented as a separate "acceptable use" document) 
	<LI>Identify further resources for specific procedures and guidelines.
</UL>
<P>
The security policy and acceptable use documents need to address a broad audience that includes not only the user populations but system administrators, upper management, and the legal counsel of the organization.
<P>
Trusted Information Systems' analysts can work with your organization to assess your current security posture, enumerate and prioritize security needs, and develop an outline for the corporate security policy and overall strategy. We can assist you in developing new policies, or in reviewing and updating existing policies. We can also develop implementation plans and security awareness programs for your users.

<BR>
<H3>The Policy Development Process</H3>
TIS analysts will interview representatives of your organization to determine current and future security requirements and directions, evaluate ad-hoc policy as evidenced in current practices, and to begin to build a roadmap for the policy development process.  The analysis will also require review of personnel manuals, acceptable use agreements, policy statements or memos, mission statements, and ethical guidelines currently in use in the company. We will conduct interviews with representatives of relevant departments or functional areas, covering such topics as assets to be protected (hardware, software and data), formal or informal security goals, measures in place to achieve those goals, network and system access policies, and intrusion detection and response planning.
<P>
We would also be happy to facilitate discussions at your site with representives of your organization to more clearly delineate your policy goals.
<P>
<HR>

