<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Certification and Accreditation</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) --->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/products/consulting/index.html">
<IMG width=230 height=33  SRC="/docs/images/tisc.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Consulting"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG SRC="/docs/images/certification.gif" border=0 ALT="Network Security">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 6>Certification and Accreditation</font>
<Blockquote>
<P>
National policy states that computer systems, including networks, that are
used to process classified, sensitive, and unclassified government
information must be accredited.  Accreditation is a formal declaration by the
accrediting authority that a system, network, or computer resource is
approved to operate at an acceptable level of risk in a particular
environment.  Accreditations are reviewed periodically, generally every three
years.  An accreditation must also be reviewed when changes are made to
system functionality, architecture, information processed, environment, or
user communities that may result in increased risk to the system.

<P>
Certification is the technical evaluation of a system's security features,
made as part of and in support of the accreditation process.  Certification
establishes the extent to which a system's design and implementation of
security features meet a set of security requirements.  Although these
processes may differ from Service to Service and from agency to agency, these
processes must be completed in a satisfactory manner.

<P>
TIS's professional staff has experience developing many certification,
accreditation, and related documents including the following:

<UL>
<LI>Security Policy
<LI>System Security Plan
<LI>System Security Concept of Operations (CONOPS)
<LI>Risk Assessment & Corrective Action Plan
<LI>Security Model
<LI>Protection Philosophy Manual
<LI>Security Test Plan & Procedures
<LI>Penetration Testing
<LI>Covert Channel Analysis
<LI>Key Management Plan
<LI>Trusted Facility Manual
<LI>Security Features User's Guide
<LI>Contingency Plan
<LI>Disaster Recovery Plan
<LI>Network Memorandum of Agreement
<LI>Security Profiles
</UL>

<P>

TIS personnel have supported many government agencies and system integrators
concerned with deploying INFOSEC.
<P>
<CENTER><img width=238 height=237 src="/docs/images/certif.gif"></CENTER>

<P>
TIS professionals have experience with many of the current security policies
and in the INFOSEC engineering areas:

<UL>
<LI>Privacy Act of 1974
<LI>Computer Security Act of 1987
<LI>Orange Book (DoD 5200.28-STD)
<LI>DoD Directive 5200.28
<LI>DIAM 50-4
<LI>Security Requirements Analysis       
<LI>Network Security                     
<LI>Trusted Computing Base (TCB) Definition and Development             
<LI>Cryptography                         
<LI>Covert Channel Analysis              
<LI>Security Modeling                         
<LI>Security Test and Evaluation
<LI>Penetration testing
<LI>Risk Assessment
</UL>
<HR>

