<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Managing Network Security</TITLE></HEAD>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (e-mail:jgang@jamesgang.com) --->

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/products/consulting/index.html">
<IMG width=230 height=33  SRC="/docs/images/tisc.gif" border=0 ALT="tis consulting"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=123 height=16  SRC="/docs/images/training.gif" border=0 ALT="Training Services">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 6>Managing Network Security</font><br>
(One Day Course)
<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>


<b>Focus</b><br>

Managers of large computer networks face an ever-increasing array of security challenges. Firewalls have received a 
great deal of attention in the last year, as the way to secure connections between networks, but in fact firewalls are 
only one component in an organization's information security strategy. In this class, we will address a variety of topics 
concerning the security of computer networks and the hosts connected to them. We will discuss the trade-offs and 
costs for different approaches to security, and we will refer to real-life examples of attacks against corporate networks. 
We will help you understand what is involved in developing a security policy, and in creating your own security 
incident response plan.
<P>

<b>Who Should Attend</b><br>

This one-day course is intended for network and firewall administrators and staff, and technical managers of 
predominantly TCP/IP-based networks, who currently have an Internet connection or who are planning  to 
connect to the Internet in the near future. <P>

<b>Opening</b><br> 
<UL>
<LI> Agenda Review
<LI> Introductions
</UL>
<b>I.	Security Policy Issues</b>
<UL>
<LI> Use of corporate resources
<LI> Privacy issues, legal issues
</UL>
<b>II.	Physical Security</b>
<UL>
<LI> Hardware in a secure environment
</UL>
<b>III.	Security Awareness</b>
<UL>
<LI> Effects of corporate culture
<LI> "Social engineering"
<LI> Need for proper training
</UL> 
<b>IV.	Managing Trust Relationships  </b>
<UL>
<LI> Planning, implementation and management
<LI> Balancing protection vs. free flow of information
</UL>
<b>V.	Perimeter Security/Remote Access</b>
<UL>
<LI> Planning network design, security and policy
<LI> Remote configurations options
</UL>
<b>VI.	Web Servers</b>  
<UL>
<LI> Proper configuration
<LI> Security pitfalls
</UL> 
		
<b>VII.	Host-Based Security  </b>	
<UL>
<LI> Pros and cons
<LI> Securing the desktop
</UL>		
<b>VIII.	Threats and Risks </b>
<UL>
<LI> Understanding the who, what and where
<LI> Risks and impact on company
</UL>
<b>IX.	Classes of Attacks  </b>  
<UL>
<LI> System cracking techniques
<LI> Denial of service attacks
<LI> Password problem
</UL>
<b>X.	Expert Tools</b>
<UL>
<LI> Various shareware and proprietary tools
</UL>
<b>XI.	Incident Response</b>
<UL>
<LI> Developing an incident response plan
<LI> Legal issues
<LI> References
</UL>
</blockquote>
<HR>
<p>
<b>Course Information</b>
<blockquote>
<a href="gicm.html">Installation, Configuration and Management 
Course Description</a><br>
<a href="mns.html">Managing Network Security Course Description</a><br>
</blockquote>
