<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Network Security - SNMP-NG </TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<a href="/docs/research/network/index.html">
<IMG width=112 height=15 SRC="/docs/images/nsecurity.gif" border=0 ALT="Network Security"></a>
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 4>Network Security</font> <BR> <CENTER> <font
size=6>Simple Network Management Protocol - Next Generation</font>
</CENTER> 

<BLOCKQUOTE> 

This is an introductory page to the results of the SNMP-NG Advisory
Team.  The Advisory Team was formed after the 36th IETF to analyze the
proposed, existing approaches for SNMP security.  These approaches are
commonly known as USEC and v2*.  The general direction to the Advisory
Team was to analyze the two approaches and provide recommendations to
the Network Management community.<P>

The Advisory Team reported the results of their analysis at the first
Network Management Area open meeting at the 37th IETF on December 9th.
Since the Team continued work through the IETF, copies of the slides
were not distributed at meeting.  Because of the last minute editing,
the slides presented at the open had some minor errors.  These errors
have been corrected and a few minor clarifying changes have been made
to the version of slides referenced on this page.
<P>

A few words on annotations used on the slides:<P>
<UL>
<LI>Each illustration has a set of arrows which indicate direction
of a "flow" (i.e., data moving from one module/sub-module to
another):

<LI> Each solid arrow has words identifying the inputs
at the tail and a number at the head.

<LI> Each number on an arrow indicates the sequence of
events associated with that picture.

<LI> Solid arrows indicate that the particular "flow"
is needed for every occurrence of the function illustrated in the picture.

<LI> Dashed arrows indicate that the particular "flow"
may or may not be needed for every occurrence of the function
illustrated in the picture.  (for example, when processing a received
message, if that message has privacy encryption then it will go in and
out of the priv sub-module but if there is no privacy encryption then
it will not be sent through the priv sub-module.)
</UL><P>

<hr>

The slides are available in several formats:<P>
The entire set of <a href="ps/snmp/ietf_nm4.ppt">Power Point slides</a> in 
uncompressed format<P>
The entire set of <a href="ps/snmp/ietf_nm4.ppt.gz">Power Point slides</a> in gzip format<P>
The entire set of <a href="ps/snmp/ietf_nm4.ps">PostScript slides</a> in uncompressed format<P>
The entire set of <a href="ps/snmp/ietf_nm4.ps.gz">PostScript slides</a> in gzip format<P>
The entire set of slides in <a href="ps/snmp/ietf_nm4.pdf">Adobe PDF</a> format<P>
</Blockquote>

