<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>A Formal Semantics for C</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=78 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/assurance.gif" border=0 ALT="Assurance">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->


<font size=6>A Formal Semantics for C</font>
<BR>


<H3>Introduction</H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>

Correctness of source code is crucial for software assurance.  The most
popular programming language in use today is, arguably, the C programming
language.  Note that popularity does not imply that C is the <B>best</B>
programming language, in fact, we can effectively argue that quite the
opposite is true.  However, a huge amount of working software is written in C,
and some of this software includes security-cruitical code.  The correctness
of this code is of paramount importance.  And one cannot reason about the
correctness of source code, whether formally or informally, without
understanding the exact behavior of the code. This leads to the necessity for
a formalized semantics.  A formal semantics for C provides a foundation on
which to prove correctness properties of C source code, and also provides a
foundation for mechanical verification of C programs.


</BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Approach</H3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>

At TIS we have developed two formal semantics for C: a denotational semantics
for most of the ANSI/ISO standard C language and an Nqthm (Boyer-Moore logic)
semantics for a small subset of C.
<P>

<b>Denotational Semantics</b><br>

The report <A HREF="ps/csem.ps">"A Formal Denotational Semantics for C"</A>
describes our denotational semantics for C.  This report describes an
automated system, implemented in Common Lisp, for determining the denotational
semantics of arbitrary C programs, expressed in terms of a temporal logic that
is an extended subset of the classical temporal logic.  The only temporal
operator in this logic is the diamond (eventually) operator.  This logic has
been rigorously defined and can be used to specify the semantics of arbitrary
computer languages, that is, it is not in any way specific to C.  This logic
is also not specific to any mechanical verification system, and could be
embedded within any sufficiently powerful verification system, such as PVS or
HOL.


<P>

The semantic definition is divided into two phases: static and dynamic.  The
static semantics (type-checking semantics) are machine-independent, and the
dynamic semantics are parameterized by machine dependencies.  The static
semantics has been defined for all of ANSI/ISO standard C.  The dynamic
semantics has been defined for all constructs except floating point numbers,
sizeof, casting, and goto.  Hooks have been provided to deal with the
nondeterministic order of evaluation issues (in expressions, declaration
initializers, and so forth) and the associativity/commutativity of
expressions.

<P>

Both phases of the semantics were written in the Denotational Definition
Language (DDL), an executable semantic specification language.  The JADDS tool
(Jeff's Automated Denotational Definition System), freely available public
software, can generate executable Common Lisp code from DDL specifications,
allowing such semantic specifications to be interfaced with other software
tools, such as verification systems.  An LR(1) parser, also written in Common
Lisp, acts as the front-end to the semantics, driven by parse tables obtained
by applying an SLR(1) parser-generation tool to a grammar that was taken
directly from the ANSI standard.  Information on obtaining copies of the
syntactic and semantics tools for C can be obtained by contacting <A
HREF="mailto:jvc@tis.com">Jeff Cook (jvc@tis.com)</A>.<P>


<b>Nqthm Semantics</b><br>

An offshoot of our efforts at defining a denotational semantics of C was to
use our semantics as a basis for defining a semantics for C suitable for use
by <A HREF="http://www.cli.com/software/nqthm/index.html">Nqthm</A> (the
Boyer-Moore logic), available from <A HREF="http://www.cli.com/">Computational
Logic, Incorporated</A>.  To date, the Nqthm semantics has only been defined
for a small subset of C.  This semantics was used as the basis of the <A
HREF="obj-code-ver.html">C Object Code Verification</A> project. We formalized
the semantics of a subset of C by defining a C interpreter as a function in
the Nqthm logic. We developed a database of lemmas about the C interpreter and
mechanically verified the correctness of the following C functions.


<P>
<BR>
<B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
void swap(int *p,int *q){<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
    int tmp;<BR>
    tmp = *p; <BR>
    *p = *q; <BR>
    *q = tmp; <BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
}
</BLOCKQUOTE>
		
<BLOCKQUOTE>
int fact (int n){<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
     int result; <BR>
       result = 1; <BR>
       while (n > 0) {<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
            result = result * n; <BR>
            n = n - 1; <BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
      }<BR>
     return result; <BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
}
</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>
<P> The theorems we proved assumed the following form: <EM> Executing the C
interpreter with the body of a C function in <B>any</B> initial state
satisfying the given <B>precondition</B> will terminate in a non-error state
that satisfies the given <B>postcondition.</B></EM> A published <A
HREF="cver-final.ps">paper</A> on this work is available
and the entire Nqthm semantics should be available soon on this site.

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<hr>
<H3><A NAME="publications">Publications</A></H3>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="ps/csem.ps">
<b>A Formal Denotational Semantics for C</b></A><br>
<i>by Jeff Cook, Eve Cohen, and Tim Redmond, Trusted
Information Systems, Technical Report 409D, September, 1994.</I><p>

<LI><A HREF="ps/jadds.ps">
<b>An Introduction to Jeff's Automated Denotational Definition
System (JADDS)</b></A>
<br>
<I> by Jeff Cook, Trusted Information Systems,
Technical Report #402, July, 1992.</I><P>

<LI><A HREF="ps/nqsem.ps">
<B>A Formal Semantics for C in Nqthm</B></A><br>
<I>by Jeff Cook and Sakthi Subramanian, Trusted Information
Systems, Technical Report 517D, October, 1994.</I><P>

<LI><A HREF="ps/cver-final.ps">
<b>Mechanical Verification of C Programs</b></A> <br>
<I>by Sakthi Subramanian and  Jeffrey V. Cook,
Proceedings of the ACM SIGSOFT Workshop on Formal Methods in Software
Practice, January, 1996.</I>
</UL>

