<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Object Code Verification</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=78 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/assurance.gif" border=0 ALT="Assurance">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->


<font size=6>Object Code Verification</font>
<BR>

<h3>Summary</h3>
<BR>
<Blockquote>

An important step when applying formal methods to gain assurance of
trusted systems is the verification of object code against source
code.  One way to verify that the object code faithfully
implements the source code from which it is compiled is to verify the
compiler.  However, verifying the implementation of an industrial
strength compiler is a very difficult technical problem at the present
time.  For small, security sensitive fragments of code, it may be
easier to verify equivalence of source and object code by reasoning
about their behavior directly without dealing with the algorithm used
for translation.  Our aim in this project, therefore, was to build
a system for automatically verifying object code against source code.
<P>
We succeeded in building a system that automatically
verifies MC68020 object code against C source code.  The semantics of
MC68020 object code and a small subset of C were formalized in the
logic of Nqthm (a.k.a. the Boyer-Moore theorem prover).  After a
sufficient set of lemmas about C and MC68020 semantics were made
available, Nqthm was able to prove the correctness theorems
automatically for a small class of programs. For
practical use of the system to be possible we wrote a front-end to
Nqthm to generate correctness theorems given the C source file as
input.  Using our front-end, we tested our system by verifying the
object code produced by GCC and CC compilers for some small programs.
<P>
The figure below gives the inputs and outputs of our system:
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/docs/images/auto-proof-box.gif"></CENTER>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR  size=2 >

<h3>Approach</h3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
To verify implementation correctness of C programs automatically
using Nqthm we:
<UL>
<LI> Formalized C semantics in Nqthm by defining a C
interpreter.
<LI> Developed a suite of lemmas for reasoning  about
C programs.
<LI> Borrowed the MC68020 interpreter and lemma database about
object code programs.
<LI> Used the above two to prove equivalence of
source and object code automatically.
<LI> Wrote a front-end to generate implementation
correctness theorems given a C source file and a compiler name
as input.
</UL>
<P>
The MC68020 object code
produced by compiling a C function behaves the same way as its source
provided it changes the values stored in memory locations allocated to
C variables and returns the same value as the C function. 
Define that an MC68020
state <EM>corresponds</EM> to a C state if the MC68020 memory locations
of C variables store the same values as in C memory.  Then we verify
object code against source code by proving that if the initial
states of the C and MC68020 interpreters correspond then running the C
and the MC68020 interpreters on the source and object code programs
will produce corresponding states. In addition, we extract the values
returned from the final states and prove that they are equal. The meaning
of implementation correctness may be pictorially depicted using the 
following commutative diagram:
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/docs/images/comm.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
The following is a typical example of a C function whose implementation
correctness we verified:
<P>
<B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
int f() 
<BR>
{
<BLOCKQUOTE>
    int i = 1, *p, a[5]; 
<BR>
    p = &a[3]; 
<BR>
    *p = 2; 
<BR>
    return a[3]; 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
} 
</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR  size=2 >
<h3>Publications</h3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Our work was published in the following two papers:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="ps/compass96-final.ps">
<b>Automatic Verification of Object Code Against Source Code</b></A> <br>
<i>by Sakthi Subramanian and Jeffrey V. Cook,Proceedings of the Eleventh Annual Conference
on Computer Assurance (COMPASS'96), June, 1996.</I>
<LI><A HREF="ps/cver-final.ps">
<b>Mechanical Verification of C Programs</b></A> <br>
<I>by Sakthi Subramanian and Jeffrey V. Cook, Proceedings of the ACM SIGSOFT Workshop on 
Formal Methods in Software Practice, January, 1996.</I>
</UL>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-- signature -->

