<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Vertical Slice Assurance Methodology</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="http://shadowplay.tis.com/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="http://shadowplay.tis.com/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG SRC="http://shadowplay.hq.tis.com/docs/images/assurance.gif" border=0 ALT="Assurance" WIDTH=78 HEIGHT=16>
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<font size=6>Vertical Slice Assurance Methodology</font>
<BR>

<h3>Introduction</h3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>

The vertical slice assurance methodology (VSAM) was proposed to avoid
some of the prohibitive costs of current assurance techniques.  This
methodology fulfills a need for an assurance methodology that allows
system developers to balance a variety of assurance techniques with
one another, and with the realities of limited resources, to create a
maximally effective approach to assurance.  The methodology is
specifically designed to judge a subset of the most critical functions
of a system and to work with components at different levels of
abstraction.

<P>

The essence of this assurance methodology is the recognition that
there is a range of assurance techniques, none of which is
sufficiently effective and practical by itself, but each of which has
important applications in the correct context.  For example, broad
application of costly rigorous analysis techniques to an
implementation is neither feasible nor practical.  However, judicious
use of such analysis on critical routines can provide the high degree
of assurance that these routines need.  On the other hand, solely
applying lower-cost techniques may not provide adequate assurance for
a highly critical system.  Non-trivial trade-off analysis is needed to
determine which techniques are appropriate for which parts of the
system.  It is essential that the system be analyzed to determine the
specific correctness properties fundamental to its operation.  The
demonstration of these properties is the reason for applying the
assurance techniques.

<P>

The challenge is to develop an approach to assurance that retains the
usefulness of performing formal analysis to the entire system while
avoiding its expense and difficulties.  Experience has shown some
amount of formal design specification
very useful and similar formal
specification and analysis should prove useful at other, lower levels
of abstraction.  The experience has also shown that it is
too costly to apply uniformly 
the formal design analysis to the entire system.
However, assurance may be
significantly improved if selective specification and analysis are 
applied <it> vertically</it> - i.e.  applied
in limited amounts to several different levels of abstraction -
rather than <it> horizontally</it> - i.e.  applied broadly at one level
of abstraction only.

<P>

Initial steps of the methodology consist of analyzing the system, to
categorize its functions and subfunctions according to criticality.
Specific assurance techniques can then be selected, matching assurance
benefit and cost with function criticality.  Such analysis will
determine what resources to use for which techniques applied to which
parts of the system.  The second phase of the methodology is the
application of the assurance techniques themselves, applying a more
rigorous techniques to components whose criticality and complexity
demand such rigor and using less rigorous techniques for all
others.  In this manner, high assurance can be gained at a less
prohibitive cost.


</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR  size=2 >
<h3>Further Information</h3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="vsam-success.html">
    <b>VSAM Successes</b></A><BR>
<LI><A HREF="vsam-example.html">
    <b>An Application of the VSAM to the TMach File Open Call</b></A> 
<P>

</UL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-- signature -->

<HR size=2 >
