<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>SIGMA Project Briefing</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=191 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/dissys.gif" border=0 ALT="Distributed Systems Security">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 6>Sigma: Security for Distributed Object Interoperability
	Between Trusted and Untrusted Systems
</font>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<Table cellpadding=2>
<TR> <TD>
    <b>E. John Sebes</b> <br>
    Trusted Information Systems, Inc. <br>
    444 Castro St., Suite 800 <br>
    Mountain View, CA  94041 <br>
    <a href="mailto:ejs@ba.tis.com">ejs@ba.tis.com</a> <br> <br>
</TD>
<TD >
    <b>Terry Benzel</B> <br>
    Trusted Information Systems, Inc  <br>
    11340 W  Olympic Blvd  <br>
    Los Angeles, CA  90064 <br>
    <a href="mailto:tcvb@la.tis.com">tcvb@la.tis.com</a> <br> <br>
</TD>   
</TR>
</TABLE>

<h4>
Abstract:
</h4>
<blockquote>
The Sigma project is researching the integration 
and interoperation of security technologies into distributed computing
environments based on CORBA, the Common Object Request Broker Architecture.
The architectural results described in this paper are focused on security
technologies that allow controlled, selective exchange of object-oriented
services among separate distributed systems that differ in security policy,
mechanisms, and assurance.
A central goal for our work in this area is to identify and prototype
techniques that enable CORBA-based application interoperation between
trusted and untrusted distributed systems.
</blockquote>
<h2>
Introduction
</h2>

The Sigma project is 3-year research effort to investigate the integration of
and interoperation of security technologies into distributed computing
environments based on CORBA, the Common Object Request Broker Architecture.
Our focus is on architectures and security technologies that allow controlled,
selective exchange of object-oriented services among separate distributed
systems that differ in security policy, mechanisms, and assurance.
<p>

Overall, the Sigma project addresses a number of problem domains for
interoperability of distributed object applications that span multiple systems.
This paper describes the approach taken to one of Sigma's key problem domains:
cases that include applications executing on systems that must provide data
separation based on sensitivity or other content attributes. A central goal
for our work in this area is to identify and prototype techniques that enable
CORBA-based application interoperation between trusted and untrusted
distributed systems. Such interoperation will require not only security
mechanisms to control interoperability, but also also CORBA support
(including CORBA security mechanisms) in enclaves that include trusted systems.
<p>

The Sigma project recently completed its first year. This paper presents key 
elements of the architectural findings from the initial phase of the project,
during which we performed an in depth analysis of security issues associated
with the project goals. After presenting background information on CORBA and
security and Sigma objectives, this paper discusses three central areas of 
project work.  The first area focuses on inter-enclave interoperability and 
the use of mechanisms to control it. The second area is development of 
techniques for providing CORBA support for environments including trusted 
systems.  The final area concerns techniques for controlling interaction
between trusted and untrusted distributed systems, using a combination
of interoperability controls and CORBA trusted systems technology.
<p>

<HR>

<h2>
Background and Objectives
</h2>

The Sigma research project is being conducted against the general framework
of CORBA and the distributed system security issues arising from it.
Our analysis of these issues indicate that there are at least two
areas in which near-term CORBA solutions will fall short of meeting the
security requirements of some distributed environments.  These are:
<menu>
<li>
access control on interoperability between enclaves, and
<li>
high assurance security mechanisms for interoperability within enclaves.
</menu>
Our research efforts are addressing these two areas and related research topics
on access control and federation of policies for CORBA based interoperability.
This paper describes our analyses and proposed architectural solutions
for achieving secure interoperability between enclaves and within high
assurance enclaves.  

<h4>
Background: CORBA and Security
</h4>

CORBA is an emerging standard with broad industry support as the basis for
interoperable, object-oriented distributed computing. 
CORBA is an architecture for Object Request Brokers (ORBs), which enable
diverse applications to interoperate in a uniform, platform-independent manner.
An ORB hides platform and application heterogeneity (differences of
programming language, operating system, networking capabilities, hardware, and
object location) by transparently routing object method invocations to objects
implemented by servers throughout a heterogeneous distributed computing system.
<p>

ORBs are primarily designed to provide object management infrastructure for
one
<em>
enclave,
</em>
one independent distributed system operating under one
administration and using one set of security mechanisms.
<a href="footnotes.html#Enclave">[1]</a>
Interoperability
<em>
between
</em>
enclaves is also a goal, but the state of
practice in CORBA technology includes little experience with such
interoperability. Furthermore, CORBA security standards have only just
begun to address inter-enclave interoperation and the security functionality
needed to protect interoperating enclaves from one another. There is very
little experience with inter-enclave security mechanisms.
To address these issues, a primary focus of the Sigma project is
development of security approaches to
<em>
access controls
</em>
on CORBA-based
interoperability
<em>
between
</em>
distributed systems.
<p>

The recent CORBA Security specification defines interfaces for security
services, but avoids mandating any specific mechanisms, either mechanisms used
by an ORB to enforce security within one enclave, or mechanisms used by ORBs
to constrain interoperation between enclaves. As a result, there is little
experience with use of CORBA security mechanisms, and little or no understanding
of assurance and trustworthiness of implementation of such mechanisms.
This is not a shortcoming of the CORBA Security specification
<em>
per se
</em>
but rather an indication of the preliminary state of practice of CORBA security.
Nevertheless, there are some fundamental trust issues that remain to be worked
out.
<p>

Foremost among these trust issues are the assurance issues of the
non-bypassability and proof against tampering of the critical security
mechanisms of ORBs. The CORBA Security specification advises that these
are critical aspects of assurance of any implementation of the CORBA
Security specification's interfaces.
However, today's common commercial OS platforms lack security
features that can be used by ORB vendors to ensure that security components
are non-bypassable and tamperproof. Early indications are that performance
concerns of COTS ORB vendors have resulted in ORB implementations that consist
of library software that resides in the process address spaces of client
and object server processes.
<p>

As a result, there are no strong protections of security software from the
application software upon which security is enforced.
Even if ORB security software were to be embodied in separate processes,
there is no effective mechanism for preventing distributed client-server
communication from bypassing such processes.
Nevertheless, it appears that some ORB vendors (and/or third-party security
software vendors) are planning to provide security implementations that are
sufficient to the needs of commercial environments that already have non-CORBA
experience with existing distributed security solutions, such as those of
Kerberos and DCE.
In such environments, some amount of trust is placed in the users of
the environment, and stronger security measures are not cost effective.
<p>

<h4>
SIGMA Objectives
</h4>

Given this current state of practice, the Sigma architectural components
described in this paper have been defined to address two areas in which
near-term ORB technology is
<em>
not
</em>
likely to meet security needs:
high assurance access controls for within-enclave interoperability,
and access controls on inter-enclave interoperability.  
<p>

The first area we identified is inter-enclave security. Even if an enclave's
users are trusted to some extent, the same trust should
<em>
not
</em>
be extended
to outsiders. Thus, even though an enclave may not employ high-assurance
security within the enclave, high-assurance security mechanisms are required
to ensure that only authorized outsiders may interoperate with the enclave,
and even then may only use the services that are intended for outside use.
Given that commercial OSs don't support such strong unbypassable
interoperability controls, the network architecture must be used
to ensure the unbypassability of interoperability controls.
<p>

<center>
<a href="/docs/images/fllarge.gif"><img src="/docs/images/fl.gif" border=0></a><br>
Figure 1: Abstract Architecture of Enclave<br>
<font size=1>Click on image for a full-screen view</font>
</center><p>

Figure 1 illustrates an abstract view of an enclave
interoperating with other enclaves. The key point of the figure is
that network communication with the outside must in all cases pass through
a single point of control. This restriction is enforced not by any
OS mechanisms, but by the network architecture itself; the physical
network media carrying outside traffic are connected to the system
components which implement the control point.
Another aspect of the figure is the variety of places that security mechanisms
(shown as shaded rectangles) may be implemented. Even though the single point
of control does use security mechanisms to constrain outside access, other
enclave components (such as the OS, the ORB, and security-aware applications)
may also use security mechanisms to implement policies restricting access
within the enclave. Thus, within-enclave security
mechanisms complement the security mechanisms at the boundary
of the enclave, and each set of mechanisms can have the degree of
assurance appropriate to it.
<p>

The second area we identified is the need for security within enclaves that
include assets that require very strong protection. Government and military
systems are common examples of systems that require strong protection using
some form of sensitivity label-based access control.  
Similar requirements are emerging for commercial environments,
as traditionally separate computing bases merge into corporate intranets
in order to share infrastructure, services, and data.
Although wide data sharing is a goal, some data must be rigorously controlled,
including cases where content-based data separation is required in a manner
similar to military sensitivity. A classic example is that while some
financial data can be accessed by non-financial users, other financial
data is strictly for financial users only, and neither primary databases
nor extracted or copied data should be accessible outside of finance.
<p>

We refer to these kinds of of access control requirements as multi-level
security requirements, out of recognition that work on these issues has
often been targeted at government and military systems.
Just as in commercial environments, there is much interest in the use of
CORBA technology in government and military systems.
Unlike many commercial environments, however, such systems have well-defined
and long-standing operational restrictions. As a result, there is little
consensus on how CORBA may be used in a way that enforces security properly and
with the required level of assurance.
Therefore, a particular objective of Sigma is to enable distributed
application interoperation between multi-level enclaves 
(enclaves which manage various data with differing sensitivity) and other
enclaves ranging from open, security-neutral systems to highly sensitive,
system-high mode systems.  Interoperation between such systems is being driven
by the vast array of commercial object-oriented information brokers which are
readily available over the world wide web today. Thus the goal of
interoperability between enclaves does not apply solely to DoD computing
environments, but also to commercial environments and hybrid combinations
of commercial and DoD information systems.
<p>

<HR>

<a name="Sgateway">
<h2>
Inter-Enclave Interoperability via ORB Gateways
</h2>

Our analysis of architectural requirements for inter-enclave interoperability
have shown that effective controls require a single point of access control.
We have defined an architectural component, which we have called an
<em>
ORB Gateway
</em>
that provides this single point of control on external access.
An enclave's ORB Gateway is central to enforcement of the enclave's
security policy on CORBA-based application-level interoperation with
other enclaves.
<p>

An enclave must be protected from the outside world, if there is to
be any effective constraint on interoperation with the outside world.
This protection takes the form of isolating the enclave's network so
that there is only a single point of connection to outside networks.
At that single point of connection are placed the security mechanisms that
restrict communication to the forms allowed by the enclave's
security policy.
<a href="footnotes.html#Practice">[2]</a>
Network firewalls are a common example of such a perimeter security mechanism.
The network architecture prevents all outside communication except
communication that flows through the firewall.
<p>

An ORB Gateway is in principle similar to a firewall. The distinction
between the two is that firewalls currently enforce policies on widely
used existing network-based services, while ORB Gateways must enforce
policies on CORBA-based application communication. As a result, ORB Gateway
functionality must be based on different and potentially more complex
mechanisms. From an architectural perspective, however, an ORB Gateway
can be thought of as a logical part of an enclave's firewall. That is, an
ORB Gateway logically operates at the single point of connection on the
perimeter of an enclave's network, and is a "choke point" for all
network communication of CORBA applications.
In practice, an ORB Gateway may well not be part of the actual firewall,
and may have non-trivial relationships with a firewall. Further aspects
of ORB Gateways and firewalls are described in the section on
<a href="#Sfirewall">firewalls</a>.
<p>

Following sections describe various means to control the invocation
of object methods, based on characteristics of the invocation or invoker.
Common to all these cases, however, is the requirement for manageability
of ORB Gateway's controls, which must be flexible and scalable in spite
of the potentially large number and variety of factors. To meet this 
requirement, ORB Gateway authorization mechanisms are based on Domain and
Type Enforcement (DTE)
<a href="#Sherman">[Sherman]</a>
which is used to define an ORB Gateway's policy.
Other Sigma project work is focused on the extension of DTE specifications
and enforcement mechanisms to object-oriented environments.
Results of this work will be used in ORB Gateways, where
application services, methods, objects, object attributes, and invoker
attributes are related to one another by the definition of domains and types.
The ORB Gateway uses these definitions to determine the domain and type of
each object request. The domain and type is then used as input to 
access checking software generated from the object-oriented DTE domain
and type definitions.
<p>

<h4>
Restrictions on Outside Access
</h4>

An ORB Gateway's primary function is to examine and process every incoming
object request. As a result, an ORB Gateway's functionality is dependent
on processing some inter-ORB protocol, i.e., a protocol that is a common
language between different ORBs, and in which object requests are conveyed
between enclaves running potentially different ORBS. Given the implementation
of an inter-ORB protocol, an ORB Gateway can restrict application traffic in
a variety of ways, based on information in the object request. The Sigma
project has focussed its work on CORBA's Internet Inter-ORB Protocol (IIOP).
<p>

One important kind of restriction enforced by ORB Gateways is a restriction
on the services that outsiders can use. Each of an enclave's CORBA-based
application services is an implementation of one or more classes defined
in an interface specification in CORBA IDL. This service-access restriction is
based on information in an object request that specifies the interface being
used. Although there may be an object server in an enclave that implements the
requested interface, it may or may not be permissible for outside requests to
be performed by the servers. The ORB Gateway will be configured with
information about all the services for which outsiders are permitted access,
the communication ports over which these services' object requests are to be
made, etc. The ORB Gateway permits only object requests for allowed services.
<p>

A second kind of restriction is on the methods that outsiders can invoke.
Each method is defined as part of an interface specification, and is an
operation that can be invoked on specific object instances of the class
to which the method belongs.
For some services, outsiders may be permitted to use the service, but only
a subset of the methods of the service's interface. For example, some methods
may be invokable by outsiders because the methods do not alter the state of
the object, i.e., the methods have read-only semantics.
<p>

An ORB Gateway can enforce method-access restrictions with any combination
of methods, with arbitrary semantics (i.e. more complex than read-only
or write-only). Semantic interpretation of methods is encoded in the
configuration of an ORB Gateway. The contents of the configuration are the
result of human review of the semantics of the various applications' methods,
and a comparison of the semantics to the organization's security policy.
Enforcement of the policy is performed by the ORB Gateway based on this
configuration data. In its simplest form, such configuration data would
simply be a list of methods that are permitted to outsiders. We are exploring
more powerful ways of expressing method-access restrictions, based on grouping
methods into equivalence classes, and controlling method access based on
accessors' authenticated identity (also grouped into equivalence classes).
<p>

A third kind of restriction is object-access restriction, in which distinct
objects can be instances of the same class, yet be governed by different
access controls. For example, although a service may be permitted to
outsiders, only certain objects may be accessible to outsiders. Both
method-access and object-access restrictions may apply simultaneously.
Again, configuration data specifies outsider-accessible objects, so that
ORB Gateways do not depend application-specific data about objects.
Likewise, we are exploring more powerful methods of expressing these
restrictions on object access.
<p>

Note that in all of these cases, there is no requirement for an ORB Gateway
to perform unmarshalling and examination of application-specific data.
A rich array of access control policies can be implemented solely on the
basis of service requests, methods invoked, and objects targeted.
<p>

<h4>
Authentication and ORB Gateways
</h4>

Authentication provides another dimension for constraints enforced by ORB
Gateways, in addition to the above restrictions based on an object request's
service, method, and target object.
All three kinds of restrictions
<em>
could
</em>
be enforced uniformly on all
outsiders. However, authentication mechanisms provide the ability for
security mechanisms to implement policies that provide for limited access
based on identity and/or capabilities. Because an ORB's object request
access controls often must depend on fine-grained authentication data,
it seems likely that implementation of some interoperation policies
will also required use of authentication data. Therefore, we assume
that some ORB Gateways will implement policies that provide for limited
access between enclaves, i.e. one enclave permits to another enclave some
classes of access that are not permitted to other enclaves or the
world at large.
<p>

In order to implement these selective controls, the ORB Gateway must use
authentication data that comes with object requests. Cryptographic mechanisms
are necessary in many cases in order for authentication data to be validated
by recipients (including ORB Gateways) before being used as the basis of access
control decisions. Support for multiple mechanisms is required, because
interoperating enclaves may use different security mechanisms, and these
mechanisms may implement different security policies. By implementing multiple
authentication mechanisms, an ORB Gateway can validate the security attributes
of object requests that originate from other enclaves with different mechanisms.
<p>

Note, however, that ORB Gateways need not implement all the authentication
mechanisms of all the various ORBs. Rather, ORB Gateways can implement the
authentication mechanisms that various ORBs implement in conjunction with
inter-ORB interoperability. These must be defined as part of the CORBA
standards process, and there are likely to be few of them. We plan on
prototyping selected security mechanisms that are already in use and which
have significant liklihood to become part of inter-ORB security mechanisms,
e.g. Kerberos, DCE security, certificated-based digital signatures,
IP security.
<p>

<h4>
Authenticated Outside Access
</h4>

Once an ORB Gateway has performed this validation of an object request, it can
then interpret the security attributes of the request. Interpretation involves
assigning a meaning to a security attribute. As a result, other enclaves'
security attributes are meaningful within the enclave security policy, and the
attribute data can be used in access control decisions. In some cases, each
enclave can be ignorant of one another's policies and agree only on the meaning
of policy-independent data like identities. In other cases, one enclave
must be able to map security attributes of one policy to another.
As a result, an ORB Gateway's interoperability security mechanisms must
include the ability to extract security attributes from the data sent
by another enclave.
<p>

There are two basic approaches to the way that an ORB Gateway uses
authentication data to enforce restrictions on outside access to CORBA
application objects.
In one approach the ORB Gateway implements an access control policy on
outside access, and performs an access check for each object request.
These checks are based on both configuration data and object request
message data, including authentication data.
Configuration data defines which services, methods, and objects are
accessible by which outsiders. 
In the second approach, the ORB Gateway uses authentication data not for
access checks, but for translations between authentication mechanisms
and data of outside enclaves (or of interoperation protocols) and the
authentication mechanisms and data of the enclave. The ORB Gateway transforms
outside object requests into object requests that can be interpreted
by the ORB inside the enclave. The ORB Gateway allows all object requests
to enter the enclave, and the ORB performs access checks on these outside
object requests in the same manner as it does on inside requests.
<p>

We are focusing our attention on the first approach, for a number of reasons.
First, it provides a  "perimeter defense" against unauthorized use, rather
than a security-in-depth approach which depends heavily on the correct
configuration or operation of components inside the enclave. Second, the
perimeter approach does not require the ORB Gateway to be a highly trusted
component with the ability to create credentials on behalf of users.
Third, the perimeter approach decouples boundary security from end-to-end
authentication. CORBA inter-ORB interoperability mechanisms can enable
client credentials from one enclave to be usable in other enclaves.
An ORB Gateway implements inter-ORB authentication mechanisms and bases
its decisions on the authentication information. In doing so, however,
it does not impact client/target end-to-end authentication based on the
same inter-ORB authentication mechanisms. As a result, ORB Gateway
functionality does not affect end-to-end security mechanisms, such as
delegation or DAC, they may not be relevant to ORB Gateway functionality.
<p>

<h4>
Constraints on Insider Access to External Services
</h4>

Another possible function of an ORB Gateway is constraint on insider
access to outside application services.
Some enclaves may have a policy that is not restrictive of insider's
use of outside services. Some enclaves may restrict use of only a few
specifically suspect services. Some enclaves may restrict access
to only specifically approved services. Again, restrictions may
be service-specific or method-specific (or even object-specific)
and may include restrictions based on the identity of the insider
or attributes of the outside accessed object.
<p>

These restrictions may be to prevent outward information flow,
in a manner analogous to firewall policies that prohibit file transfer
protocol (FTP) usage to transfer files from the inside to the outside
(while allowing the reverse). These restrictions may also exist to
support an inter-enclave policy where enclave
<B>A</B>
provides the same access to all requests from enclave
<B>B</B>,
and relies on the ORB Gateway of enclave
<B>B</B>
to ensure that only authorized
<B>B</B>
parties can uses enclave
<B>A</B>'s
services.
<p>

In all of these cases, the actual functionality of the ORB Gateway
is the same as in restrictions on incoming requests.
That is, the same mechanisms are applied to outgoing requests as
incoming requests, although the specific manner is dictated by
distinct configuration data.
The only additional functionality is the ability to differentiate between
two different kind of outgoing messages: those that are replies to outside
requests, and those that are requests to outside services.
<p>


<a name="Sfirewall">
<h4>
Firewalls
</h4>

CORBA-based interoperability necessarily involves internet firewalls.
If two enclaves are interoperating, then one or both are
likely to be protected by a firewall.
The firewall examines all incoming network traffic, and permits only
that traffic which is for an application service that is specifically
permitted by the security policy of the system that the firewall is
protecting.
<p>

Interoperation between different systems' ORB is accomplished
by sending object requests in the Internet Inter-ORB Protocol (IIOP).
As a result, a firewall must support inter-ORB communication by
permitting the IIOP traffic that carries it.
<a href="footnotes.html#Focus">[3]</a>
For a firewall to process CORBA application traffic like any other
application's network traffic, the firewall would need to be able
to recognize traffic in each permitted application-level protocol.
In practice, however, there is a dilemma: current firewalls do not have the
ability to process IIOP and the application-level protocols that it carries.
In the future, when there is enough experience with IIOP to determine
what approaches to IIOP are appropriate for a firewall, some firewalls
may incorporate support for IIOP.
For the present, however, and particularly for exploratory usage
of CORBA-based interoperability between enclaves, some near-term
mechanism is required.
<p>

The Sigma project approach is to retain the basic firewall architecture and
approach, but to provide IIOP processing on a separate, ORB Gateway host.
The firewall permits IIOP traffic to flow to only the ORB Gateway host,
where the ORB Gateway examines each IIOP message to determine whether
and how a message is permitted to enter the enclave.
<a href="footnotes.html#Critical">[4]</a>
The ORB Gateway permits traffic only for services which have been
specified as externally accessible by the system's security policy.
That is, just because an enclave contains a host providing a CORBA-based
distributed object service, that service is
<em>
not
</em>
automatically
exposed to external access by the Gateway. Rather, the Gateway must be
specifically configured to permit that application's traffic, subject
to certain constraints.
<p>

Since this processing could be complex, and certainly is not currently
well-understood, it would be premature to place this processing on a firewall
host, and risk the compromise of other important and well-understood functions
of a firewall. Given the nascent state of IIOP usage, there is no way for IIOP
proxying code to be effective and still meet the criteria for firewall
software: small, simple, compartmentalized, and well-understood. Use of IIOP
is not well understood in terms of wide use, or worked examples of policies
governing IIOP traffic, or experience with mechanism needed to enforce such
policies.
<p>

<center>

<a href="/docs/images/abslarge.gif"><img src="/docs/images/abs.gif" border=0></a><br>
Figure 2: Network Architecture of Firewall and ORB Gateway<br>
<font size=1>Click on image for a full-screen view</font>
</center>
<p>

However, the firewall must still be able to funnel IIOP traffic from the
outside to the ORB Gateway host. This can be accomplished with a firewall
feature known as a plug, which sends to exactly one known internal host
all traffic on a specific TCP port. (TCP is the transport protocol used
by implementations of IIOP). Figure 2 illustrates this plug
from the firewall to the ORB Gateway host, and how the plug differs
from the firewall's relaying of permitted applications' traffic to
any inside host. The figure also illustrates how the ORB Gateway's
relaying is similar to that of the firewall.
<p>

Finally, a note of caution is in order. An ORB Gateway can provide
a very valuable means of restricting external access to object
services provided within an enclave. However, although such a service
can be exported, that does not imply that it should be exported.
As a mechanism, an ORB Gateway is not a substitute for human judgement
about two distinct aspects of the advisability of export.
First, external use of the service must be consistent with the
organizations internal use of it, and conform to the organization's
overall security policy on access to the organization's data.
That is, application data must be able to be properly protected even
when external access is allowed.
Second, in addition to assessing the vulnerability of an application,
administrators must also assess the potential vulnerability of the whole
enclave that may be posed by the application.
Even if it is safe for outsiders to make controlled, legitimate use
of an application, it may be that the application's implementation
makes it vulnerable to attacks that could allow an outsider to
make illegitimate use other resources within the enclave.
The more complex an application, the more difficult it is to make
such an assessment.
<p>

<HR>

<a name="Sdtm">
<h2>
Within-Enclave Interoperability via Distributed TMach
</h2>

In addition to the high-assurance between-enclave security mechanisms
described in the previous section,  the Sigma project is also addressing
high-assurance security mechanisms for use
<em>
within
</em>
enclaves.
This project goal is driven by the need of government/military systems to
support distributed applications which handle information of multiple
sensitivity levels, and to embed these applications in a CORBA distributed
environment.  However, there is a problem with embedding multi-level
applications in a CORBA environment, in that COTS ORBs do not run on MLS
operating systems that can support multi-level applications.  This is because
high assurance trusted systems usually have very specialized and
non-standard programming interfaces.  As a result, there is little
chance that COTS ORBs will be supported on MLS systems in the near term.  
<p>

The Trusted Mach (TMach) system, however, provides a distinct advantage.
It is a high assurance multi-level system
<em>
and
</em>
it supports a
standard Unix operating system interface.  The interface is
provided by multiple instances of a Unix "personality" so that
COTS application software can run at multiple sensitivity levels.
As a result, there can be several sensitivity levels at which there
are application clients and servers all interacting at that level.
TMach also supports MLS servers, and access of their services
by clients at several levels.
In addition, the Distributed Trusted Mach system provides
an additional capability for clients on one host to access services
of a server on another host, while remaining unaware of the distributed
nature of this interaction.
<p>

As a result, Distributed TMach (DTM) can provide the platform for an enclave
which supports multi-level processing requirements. This section describes
how DTM can provide a CORBA environment for a multi-level
enclave, and how an ORB Gateway works in a DTM enclave to
enable and constrain interoperation with outside enclaves.
<p>

<h4>
Multiple Single Level Applications
</h4>

DTM is designed to satisfy the requirements of systems for computing at
multiple levels of sensitivity.  For some of these
systems, there is no requirement for true multi-level applications, but there
are requirements for applications to execute at each of several sensitivity
levels.  Historically, this need has been met through an architectural
concept of polyinstantiation, which consists of multiple single-level
components separated by a high assurance trusted computing base.  
DTM supports this multiple single-level mode of operation with its
support for multiple instances of a Unix OS execution environment,
or personality. A single host can support several distinct Unix
personalities, each running at a different level. 
Each host can run a Unix personality and a COTS ORB at a given level.
This yields a distributed application environment which is provided by the
collection of ORB software running at a given level on all the hosts.
Furthermore, this can be provided for the complete range of levels
represented by the OS personalities and corresponding ORB's.  
<p>

In such a distributed multiple single-level environment, clients
have transparent access to both local and remote objects.
The presence of the ORB, the OS, and the underlying DTM
TCB is invisible to clients and object servers.
<a href="footnotes.html#Directly">[5]</a>
The ORB may provide object access control by mediating each object request.
The OS protects OS resources (on which object implementations are based)
from tampering by software other than the application software that
manages the resources to implement objects.
The DTM TCB ensures the separation between processing
at sensitivity levels, ensuring that clients at one level cannot
access objects at another level.
<p>

<h4>
Multi-Level Applications
</h4>

DTM functionality is also directly applicable to systems with requirements
for multi-level applications that provide true multi-level service for objects
which represent application data of multiple sensitivity levels.
Servers for these applications can be developed by basing them
directly on the services of the DTM system's TCB.
This architecture may also be applicable to services that
must run directly on DTM for other reasons, for example:
a single-level server that is trusted and hence cannot depend on untrusted
personality software; a server with real-time requirements that can be
satisfied by a real-time Mach kernel but not a personality.
<p>

These servers' clients run on an OS personality, and call on object servers
via IDL-based stubs, as is the norm for CORBA. Such MLS servers offer
service at various levels. That is, an MLS server can receive object
requests from clients of all levels within which the server is running.
The server can receive object requests from clients on remote hosts, because
DTM provides distributed communication between the hosts.
<p>

For a DTM-based object server, client object requests are delivered not by a
COTS ORB, but by the DTM system itself. The DTM system performs object request
brokerage for objects managed by DTM-based servers. DTM provides both basic
brokerage functionality and also object security functionality. Object security
consists of the object request checks performed by the DTM TCB's access
controls. Basic brokerage functionality is a result of DTM's ability
to transparently route a client request to the server that acts as
the requested object's manager, even when client and server are
on different hosts. Brokerage functionality is supported in part by
each of three aspects of DTM: Mach's communication facilities,
TMach's extensible object-based type mechanism, and DTM's location-transparent
global naming and distributed communication.
<p>

There are two distinctions between DTM's object request brokerage
functionality, and the functionality of COTS ORBs.
First, DTM uses an IDL that is not the standard OMG IDL of CORBA.
Second, DTM's interfaces are not compliant with CORBA interfaces
for comparable services, i.e. object naming and lifecycle management.
We plan to address the IDL issue by using the University of
Utah IDL toolkit to construct a CORBA IDL tool that processes CORBA
interface definitions and generates software for using DTM's IDL-based
services for client and server stub code.
We plan to address the service interface issue by developing software
that implements these service interfaces (for at least the CORBA naming
and lifecycle services) with calls to DTM services.
<p>

<h4>
Two-Level Architecture
</h4>

Using DTM's support for distributed object client/server communication, we have
defined an MLS system architecture that supports both object servers running on
an OS personality (and ORB), and also MLS object servers running on DTM. In
both cases, clients can run on an OS personality, which provides functionality
for management of displays (e.g. console and keyboard), graphical user
interface, and command interpretation.
In both cases, client programs can communicate with an object server via
a client stub library using underlying communication functionality.
In the first case, the client stubs are generated by a COTS ORB's IDL
tools, and use the ORB's communication features based on the mechanisms
of the OS personality.
In the second case, the client stubs are generated by a DTM 's IDL
tools, and use DTM's communication features.
In both cases, the same abstraction, object method invocation
performed by a stub library, is used to hide the details of how the
object request is carried out by the ORB runtime or the DTM system.
<p>

There is also an alternative approach in which clients of DTM services
(such as those implemented by an MLS server) do not actually make direct
calls on the object server. This approach uses the concept of a "wrapper"
server which takes an application object request message sent via a COTS
ORB and calls DTM client stubs that implemented the same interfaces.
Multi-level service could be provided by multiple instances of a wrapper
server running at each level that could access the underlying DTM-based server.
One reason for the wrapper approach is that the clients' object requests
pass through a COTS ORB, which could implement other CORBA services not
provided by DTM, such as transaction management.
Another potential use of wrappers would be as a target for object request
messages from another enclave. If the wrappers' ORB supports IIOP, then the
enclave's ORB Gateway can receive the message and send it on to the wrapper
as is (assuming the message passes security checks in the ORB Gateway).
<p>

<HR>
<a name="Sdtmint">
<h2>
Interoperability Architecture
</h2>

Previous sections of this paper have described approaches to security mechanisms
for control of interoperability between enclaves, and security mechanisms for
control of interoperability within enclaves with higher assurance requirements
than can be met by COTS ORBs and OSs. This section describe architectural
approaches to combining these two uses of security mechanisms.
The result of this combination is use of ORB Gateways to provide security and
interoperability between multi-level enclaves and other enclaves ranging from
open, security-neutral systems to highly sensitive, system-high mode systems.
<p>

The primary interoperability architecture is based on polyinstantiation of
ORB Gateways in a multi-level enclave. An enclave has an ORB Gateway host that
runs one ORB Gateway process at each level for which interoperation is
permitted. For example, an ORB Gateway process running at Secret would connect
to a Secret network providing connectivity to an enclave of hosts running in
system-high mode at Secret.
Each ORB Gateway process runs at some single level
<B>L</B>
and provides
security for interoperation between local-enclave components running at
<B>L</B>
and other enclaves running at
<B>L</B>.
The DTM TCB constrains these single-level ORB Gateway processes to communicate
only with local enclave components of the same level or of multiple levels
which include that level.
Each ORB Gateway process further constrains interoperability by
implementing access controls that limit the services, methods, and objects
that are permitted outsiders, including specifically authenticated outsiders.
<p>

In this base architecture, the ORB Gateway processes are untrusted with respect
to the DTM TCB's policies. However, these processes are trusted to implement
access controls to enforce an additional policy that defines which resources
can be accessed from other enclaves.
Note that ORB Gateway's control access to both single-level and MLS services.
An ORB Gateway process running at a level
<B>L</B>
can permit an outsider in an
<B>L</B>-level
enclave to access objects managed in either of two ways:
managed by an untrusted object manager running on a COTS ORB on an
<B>L</B>-level
OS personality; or managed by a trusted object manager running
on DTM, where the trusted object manager's operational range includes
<B>L</B>.
These trusted object managers include both application object managers
and DTM system TCB object managers, e.g. DTM file server.
<p>

<center>
<img src="/docs/images/dtmenclave.gif" border=0></a><br>
Figure 3: ORB Gateway to DTM Enclave: Base Architecture
</center>
<p>

Figure 3 shows an example of an ORB Gateway for a DTM enclave.
In the enclave are four hosts (shown as boxes), each running an OS personality
and ORB at two levels: Secret (shaded grey) and unclassified (shaded light
grey). The bottom host is the ORB Gateway host, with ORB Gateway processes at
each of the two levels, and with each connected to a network of the same level.
Secret enclaves (lower left) can send requests which the ORB Gateway may
forward via the ORB to an object manager running at Secret (arc from bottom
center to left).
Unclassified enclaves (lower right) can send requests which the ORB Gateway may
forward via the ORB to an object manager running at Secret (arc from bottom
center to right).
Both Secret and unclassified Secret enclaves can send requests which the
ORB Gateway may forward via DTM to an MLS object manager (upward arcs from
bottom center).
Also shown is a Secret client (right) sending requets via DTM to an
MLS object manager (arc from right to center).
Although not shown, the unclassified client (on the left) could send a
message via the ORB to the same unclassified server (on the right)
that other enclaves can communicate with via the ORB Gateway.
Note that in all these cases the ORB Gateway is also performing access control,
so that not every request is actually forwarded into the enclave.
<p>

In one variant of this base architecture, the ORB Gateways don't
actually apply access control to object request messages, but instead send
them into the enclave in a form appropriate for the ORB to perform
access control.  This would include forwarding 
authentication data used for object request mediation.
For requests on objects managed by DTM-based object managers, the
authentication data would include DTM security attributes
(such as identities denoting outsiders)
and the mediation would be performed by the DTM TCB.
Because the DTM TCB enforces the binding of identities to messages,
an ORB Gateway would have to be a privileged TCB component in order
to send object requests for a variety of outsider identities.
<p>

Another form of trusted ORB Gateway is one that enforces multi-level
security policy to permit object access between levels.
Such an ORB Gateway would essentially act as a guard for each
service for which cross-level access is permitted.
The ORB Gateway's guard logic would operate from configuration
information describing which methods of which services can be
invoked from a given level to a given level.
For example, one such rule might be that a particular method
can be called on a Secret object by requesters at higher levels.
This rule would be the result of a determination that the method
has read-only semantics, and so should be permitted as a read-down.
As mentioned above, the determination of a method's semantics is part of the
process of defining an ORB Gateway's configuration, while enforcement such
rules in performed by software using the configuration data.
<p>

Implementation of guard logic can be greatly simplified compared to
current approaches. Because of DTM's support for CORBA, the implementation
can re-use DTM-based technologies for multi-level security,
object-oriented application interface, distributed communication,
and secure interoperability between enclaves.
Software development of guard logic would be analogous to
(though considerably simpler than) the IDL-based approach to
implementing application functionality as object methods.
That is, the interfaces are already defined, the application data
passed in these interfaces are already defined, and server stub code
is generated. All the developer needs to do is fill in the stubs,
and the rest is already taken care of. In the case of the guard,
implementation is required only for methods that may be permitted,
and method implementation is limited to implementing the guard's
dataflow restrictions in terms of the previously specified interface data.
<p>


<HR>
<h2>
Conclusion
</h2>

The Sigma project is addressing a range of security issues of
CORBA-based distributed application interoperation.
Sigma's problem domain is large-scale heterogeneous computing environments
composed of multiple enclaves which may differ in security policies,
security mechanisms, and ORBs.
In both commercial and military settings, such complex environments
have requirements to protect assets in an enclave while allowing
limited, controlled access from other enclaves.
The union of these areas of distributed security requirements provides the
definition of the overall scope of Sigma:
security for interoperability both between and within enclaves of
various kinds, including enclaves that support multi-level computing.
<p>

This paper has described architectural results for a problem domain that
is not addressed by current ORB technology: enclaves where application data
must be protected by strong label-based separation mechanisms, and where
application service must be provided for several operational environments,
one for each label.
Requirements of this sort are exhibited in both military and commercial
computing systems, as distributed computing interconnects previously
isolated systems.
However, previous technology to meet these requirements-- multi-level secure
operating systems-- has not been widely accepted and is currently not part of
the COTS technology base of CORBA systems.
<p>

We have described an approach to supporting enclaves with multi-level security,
but using only standard OS and object service interfaces. In cases where
multi-level requirements can be met by polyinstantiated applications, these
applications run on COTS ORBs on polyinstantiated Unix execution environments.
In cases where MLS application require an MLS system base, object services
and object brokerage are provided by an MLS TCB. In both cases, clients
access objects in the same way, without regard for whether objects are
local or remote, or whether services are polyinstantiated or not.
<p>

Such enclaves can interoperate with a wide range of other enclaves, from
open, security-neutral systems to highly sensitive, system-high mode systems.
ORB Gateways use access controls to enforce security constraints on
inter-enclave interoperation, including cases where a multi-level enclave
interoperates with enclaves composed entirely of untrusted COTS software.
For such cases, interoperation at a variety of levels can be constrained,
without requiring that ORB Gateway software be trusted with respect to
mandatory security. In some cases, such trust is beneficial and leads
to ORB Gateways permitting controlled access by clients to objects.
<p>

Finally, ORB Gateway can be used to constrain interoperability via
limiting other enclaves' access to services within an enclave, 
whether or not the protected enclave uses any particular security
approach, technology, or level of assurance. The ORB Gateway approach
allows for high-assurance controls on outsiders even if within the
enclave security is provided by an ORB using lower-assurance techniques.
<p>

Based on these architectural results, the Sigma project will continue by
developing security technology, integrating with ORB services, and prototyping
distributed computing environments that make use of the security techniques
described in this report.
<p>

<HR>

