<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Security and the World Wide Web</TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#000000" VLink="#666699"
ALink="#666699">

<center>
<a href="http://shadowplay.tis.com/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28
SRC="http://shadowplay.tis.com/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS
Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<a href="http://shadowplay.tis.com/docs/research/network/index.html">
<IMG width=112 height=15
SRC="http://shadowplay.tis.com/docs/images/nsecurity.gif" border=0
ALT="Network Security"></a>
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<IMG src="http://shadowplay.tis.com/docs/images/WWWFall94.gif">
<P>

<Font size= 6>Security and the World Wide Web</font>
<P>



<I>David I. Dalva<br>
Trusted Information Systems<br>
&lt;dave@tis.com&gt;<br>
June 1994</I>
<P>



<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>
Introduction</h2>
<p>
The Internet "killer application of the 90s" may end up being Mosaic and the
World Wide Web.  However, along with its popularity and the ability it gives
to an Internet novice to - seemingly effortlessly - traverse the Internet,
come some security concerns.<p>

<p>
Trusted Information Systems, Inc.  is performing a security analysis of the
World Wide Web (WWW) project.  What is WWW?  To quote from the CERN, the
creators of the web:<p>
<p>
"The World Wide Web (W3) is the universe of network-accessible
information, an embodiment of human knowledge.  It is an initiative started at
CERN, now with many participants.  It has a body of software, and a set of
protocols and conventions.  W3 uses hypertext and multimedia techniques to make
the web easy for anyone to roam, browse, and contribute to."<p>
<p>
The web is composed of several interoperating components:  Servers, where
Internet-connected
sites may export data to the world; Clients, where users may navigate the web
(two popular navigators are Mosaic and Lynx); and Proxies, which are used to
facilitate communication and provide access control for sites that must rely on
an intermediary host for communication with the Internet, such as those sites
behind a firewall.<p>
<p>
The common protocol used by these various components of the web is HTTP, or
HyperText Transfer Protocol.  It defines a language for accessing web servers.
Another key term is URL, which stands for Uniform Resource Locator, used to
name a network-based resource.  A URL takes the form
"resource://server.host.name[:port]/[path]" (e.g., http://www.tis.com).
<HR>
<p>


<h2>
The Security Issues</h2>
<p>
As is often the case with systems that provide a high degree of data sharing,
there are a number of security issues for sites that want to take advantage of
the web.  They can be broken down into three major categories:  1) threats the
client software poses to the local computing environment, 2) access control and
threats to servers, and 3) authentication, confidentiality, and integrity
issues. <p>

<h3>
Client Threats</h3>
<p>
The major security issue with running client software comes about given the
nature of the web:  client programs interpret data that is downloaded from
arbitrary servers on the Internet.  If there are no checks on the contents of
this imported data, there exists the potential for this data to subvert
programs running on the client systems.  These  "Trojan horses" may take
several forms, from malicious URLs to rogue code that is run through
interpreters (such as PostScript) on the client system.<p>
<p>
Another significant security issue applies mostly to sites that are protected
by Internet firewalls.  These sites have implemented security policies in their
firewalls that describe the network services they want to permit within their
organizations.  A feature of URLs is that they support several resource types:
file, FTP, HTTP, Gopher, WAIS, NNTP, Mailto, Prospero, TELNET, and RLOGIN
(other resources are in the works).  It is likely that the firewall
implementation permits only a subset of these resources.  Therefore, since with
web servers provide these services independent of their normal mechanisms
(independent of the normal FTP channels, for example), it is possible to bypass
a firewall's security policy by using web services.<p>

<h3>
Server Threats</h3>
<p>
Threats to servers consist broadly of unauthorized modification of server data,
authentication and access control to server data, and compromising a server
system by exploiting bugs in the web server software. <p>
<p>
The HTTP protocol provides several methods (for example, PUT) for writing data
on a server.  It is possible that some of these methods may be used for
unauthorized modification of server data. Work is ongoing to address security
concerns in HTTP servers. <p>
<p>
Point to Point Security Issues<p>
<p>
There are a number of security issues that arise between clients and servers.
These security requirements depend on each other in many cases. <p>
<p>
-


Authentication<p>
<p>
For some potential uses of the web (e.g., electronic commerce), it is important
that clients authenticate themselves to servers, that servers authenticate to
clients, and that both authenticate to each other.  It is important that a form
of authentication be used that is not easily spoofed, such as cryptographically
signed certificates.<p>
<p>
-


Confidentiality<p>
<p>
Confidentiality is important for web uses that involve sensitive data.  Data
exported by web clients or servers may need to be protected from eavesdropping.
For example, services are available (on-line florist) that require the passing
of credit card information.  This requirement will be amplified when other
kinds of data, such as employee records, government files, etc., begin
traversing the web.<p>
<p>
-


Integrity<p>
<p>
Certain transactions have the requirement that transaction requests and/or
contents remain unmodified during delivery.  The electronic commerce example is
a case where data integrity is critical to proper functioning of the system.
<HR>
<p>

<h2>
Potential Solutions</h2>
<p>
There are a number of possible solutions to the security issues described
above.  These solutions are being studied further; this list does not represent
the definitive set of protective measures that can be taken.  Research is
underway.<p>

<h3>
Proxy Filtering</h3>
<p>
As described previously, proxies may be used in firewall environments to enable
hosts on the protected network(s) to use the web.  One popular proxy developed
by the CERN runs on a firewall system and relays requests between both sides of
a firewall.  Given this design where the proxy acts as an intermediary, it is
natural to design security-

relevant
mediation within the proxy. Proxy mediation that helps mitigate some of the
security concerns are <p>
<p>
-


Implementing access control for network services in the proxy that replace the
firewall protection that is lost when the proxy is installed.  This access
control would restore the security policy enforced by the firewall.<p>
<p>
-


Limiting potentially dangerous subsets of the HTTP protocol.  A site's security
policy may prohibit the use of some of HTTP's methods.<p>
<p>
-


Enforcing client and/or server access to designated hosts.  An organization
should have the capability to specify to which web sites it may connect.  <p>
<p>
-


Checking various protocols for well formed commands.  A bug existed  in a
previous version of the Mosaic navigator that permitted servers to download a
"Trojan horse" URL to the client that would cause the client to run an
arbitrary program.  The proxy is in a position to filter dangerous URLs and
other subsets of HTTP and HTML for malformed commands.<p>
<p>
-


Scanning the languages that are transferred from the server to the client.
Clients download several data formats, which include programming languages such
as PostScript.  It is conceivable that the proxy may filter out data and
programs that are known to be dangerous. However, it is not possible to do this
conclusively; automatic determination of program behavior is not computable,
and is generally referred to as the "halting problem." It is possible, however,
to perform some heuristics on known dangerous constructs.<p>

<h3>
Code Analysis</h3>
<p>
An approach to mitigating some of the security issues in clients and servers is
to perform code analyses on the client and server software and the interpreters
that are called to display the different data formats that may be downloaded
from the web.  Most of the popular client programs were not written with
security in mind, so they can be analyzed for instances where blind trust is
placed on the data it obtains from the web.<p>
<p>
If attention is paid to securing the programs that run at the endpoints, a
proxy may be configured to limit communication to these secure programs.<p>

<h3>
Operational Restrictions</h3>
<p>
Code analysis is a very time consuming and difficult proposition.  If one
assumes that the client and/or server programs have inherent security
vulnerabilities, it may be more prudent to restrict their running environments.
Most UNIX (TM) systems provide the capability to restrict the running of a
process to a sub-

hierarchy
of the filesystem space (i.e., the "chroot" system call).  If client, server,
and/or interpretive programs run in a restricted filesystem subspace, then most
security relevant events will be limited to that subspace, therefore limiting
exposure of the full system's filesystem.<p>
<p>
A research project at TIS is building a prototype distributed system that
provides Domain and Type Enforcement (DTE), a strong yet flexible form of
access control.  The heart of the prototype is an experimental UNIX system that
associates type attributes with system objects (e.g., files, packets) and
restricts processes to interact only with specified types.  This can be used to
implement restricted environments that are custom tailored for applications
such as web clients and servers.
<HR>
<p>

<h2>
State Of The Art And Future Directons</h2>
<p>
Several organizations are addressing security issues described above.  TIS is
working on a publicly available HTTP proxy that will address most of the
problems that make running the web a dangerous proposition to some
organizations.<p>
<p>
Enterprise Integration Technologies, Inc.  (EIT) is designing Secure HTTP,
consisting of a set of protocol changes to address confidentiality, integrity,
and authentication issues.  TIS, RSA, and NCSA have been asked to review the
protocol.<p>
<p>
EIT and RSA Data Security, Inc.  have formed a joint venture called Terisa
Systems that plan to develop secure Mosaic and Secure HTTP products.  The CERN
is working on "Shen," a set of security extensions to the HTTP protocol that
provide for authentication and encryption.  Shen is an alternative protocol to
Secure HTTP.  The designers of Shen have interacted with TIS. <p>
<p>
Some of the authors of Mosaic from the National Center for Supercomputing
Applications (NCSA) have joined a company called Mosaic Communications
Corporation.  They have plans for security, but no more information is
available at this time.  <p>
<p>
TIS is tracking the work in this area, and is working with some of these
organizations to develop common standards.  Recent developments may be followed
by checking the TIS web home page at http://www.tis.com
<hr>
<a href="/docs/research/papers/wwwslides.html">Slides</a> used in the presentation of this paper are also available.
</Blockquote>

