<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 6>Here's why the TIS Gauntlet Firewall is the most secure</Font>

<Blockquote>
Since an application gateway is the most secure type of internetworking
firewall, TIS has designed Gauntlet Firewalls to rely on proxies to provide
services. Therefore, no direct connection is ever made between machines
on opposite sides of the firewall; network packets are never passed between
the networks, only application data. Our unique design combines these seven
(7) tenets:

<OL>
<li>Simplicity in mechanisms and services provided </li>

<li>Simplicity in software design, development, and implementation </li>

<li>A&quot;Crystal Box&quot; approach, in which source code is distributed
to allow for assurance reviews by our customers, our resellers, and other
experts </li>

<li>No users are allowed on the firewall system itself </li>

<li>For a complete security audit trail, anything that can be logged, should
be logged </li>

<li>Strong user authentication methods and mechanisms must be supported
and encouraged </li>

<li>A firewall should enforce an organization's network security policy,
not impose one of its own </li>
</OL>
<HR>
</Blockquote>
<CENTER>
<IMG width=415 height=295
SRC="/docs/images/simple.gif" border=0
ALT="Gauntlet System">
</CENTER>
<Blockquote>
<HR>
<h3>Listen to what the trade press says...</h3>


<p><b>Editor's Choice
<br></b>&quot;Your firewall is your principal protection against intruders.
In considering which firewall product to recommend, we concluded that what
you really need a network firewall device to be is a kind of black box.
In the roundup, Trusted Information Systems' Gauntlet Internet Firewall,
our Editors Choice, probably gives you the best chance to obtain that
result.&quot;

<br><b>PC Magazine</b>, March 12, 1996 </p>
</Blockquote>

