<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Functional Summary - Product Overview</TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<CENTER>
<A HREF="/docs/products/gauntlet/index.html">
<IMG width=284 height=65 SRC="/docs/images/gtop.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="gauntlet"></A>
<HR SIZE="2">
<IMG width=135 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/funct.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="functional summary">
</CENTER>
<HR SIZE="2">
<!--top-->


<FONT SIZE="6">4. Product Overview</FONT>


<BLOCKQUOTE>



<H3>Overview of Core Proxies and Services</H3>

<P>
The Gauntlet Internet Firewall includes proxies for the following
services:
<UL>
<LI>Terminal Services (TELNET, Rlogin)
<LI>File Transfer (FTP)
<LI>Electronic Mail (SMTP, POP3)
<LI>World Wide Web (HTTP, SHTTP, SSL)
<LI>Gopher
<LI>X Window System (X11)
<LI>Printer
<LI>Remote Execution (Rsh)
<LI>Sybase SQL
<LI>RealAudio
<LI>ActiveX Guard - <em>New!</em>
</UL>

<P>
There is also a proxy that acts as a &quot;patch panel&quot; for
simple services in a one-to-one or one-to-many configuration,
called the &quot;plug gateway.&quot; Through this gateway, the
Gauntlet Internet Firewall supports
<UL>
<LI>Finger
<LI>Usenet News (NNTP)
<LI>Whois
</UL>

<P>
An authenticated circuit gateway allows the firewall manager to
configure certain &quot;plug gateway&quot; services to be available
on a per user basis after users authenticate themselves to the
firewall.
<P>
An authentication server supports the use of strong user authentication
(identification) via security tokens or one-time password mechanisms.

<H3>Operating System Modifications</H3>

<P>
In additional to application level proxies, providing a secure
internetwork gateway requires modifications to the base operating
system. In the Gauntlet Internet Firewall, we have modified the
operating system in these important ways:
<UL>
<LI>A packet filter has been added for the Gauntlet Intranet Firewall
version of this product for use in situations of reduced risk,
such as on an internal, trusted network.
<LI>IP packet forwarding is turned off. No information can flow
from one network to another through the firewall except via the
application gateways.
<LI>IP network addresses are related to network interfaces allowing
the Gauntlet Internet Firewall to detect an IP spoofing attack.
<LI>Support for encrypted IP communications has been added.
<LI>Transparent access to the proxies is supported.
<LI>No ICMP redirects are honored.
<LI>No source routed packets are allowed through the firewall.
<LI>All unsupported network service ports have &quot;smoke alarms.&quot;
Instead of just generating a &quot;no such service&quot; error,
the operating system is modified on the Gauntlet Internet Firewall
to log any attempts at connections to unsupported services. They
could be the results of misconfigured systems or users errors.
They could be an indication that the protected network is under
attack.
</UL>

<H3>Additional Features</H3>

<P>
The Gauntlet Internet Firewall acts as a secure server for:
<UL>
<LI>Domain Name Service -- configured to provide different information
to trusted and untrusted networks
<LI>Internet electronic mail
<LI>Anonymous FTP
<LI>HTTP (World Wide Web)
</UL>

<P>
A &quot;Java Guard&quot; capability has been added to the HTTP
proxy (see the section on HTTP).
<P>
Additionally, the Gauntlet Internet Firewall provides both Virtual
Private Network and Virtual Network Perimeter functionality (see
<A HREF="#Glossary">Glossary</A>) through industry standard cryptography,
and a secure, easy-to-use, &quot;Web-based&quot; management tool.
<H3>Hardware Configuration</H3>

<P>
The Gauntlet Internet Firewall comes pre-configured for &quot;dual-homed&quot;
Bastion host operation on a hardware platform. The precise configuration
changes with availability of newer processors and boards, but
the generic Gauntlet Internet Firewall hardware configuration
is:
<P>
Pentium CPU (call for latest processor supported)
<P>
16 MB RAM
<P>
SCSI hard disk (call for latest disk size)
<P>
1.4 MB 3.5&quot; floppy disk
<P>
Monochrome monitor
<P>
2 Ethernet cards (thin coax, AUI, TP)
<P>
2 9-pin serial ports
<P>
1 25-pin parallel ports
<H3>Design Approach</H3>

<P>
Since an application gateway is the most secure type of internetwork
firewall, TIS has designed the Gauntlet Internet Firewall to rely
on proxies to provide services. Firewalls that combine application,
circuit, and filtering gateway technology are only as secure as
the weakest link of the three. In the Gauntlet Internet Firewall,
all communication between one network and another is turned off.
Network services are individually enabled through the application
data bridges, called proxy software or proxies. Network packets
are never passed between the networks, only application data.
No direct connection is ever made between machines on opposite
sides of the firewall.
<P>
The design approach, expanded in  <A HREF="#sec6_2">Section 6.2</A>,
combines the following seven tenets:
<UL>
<LI>Simplicity in services provided and mechanisms
<LI>Simplicity in software design, development, and implementation
<LI>A Crystal Box&#153;  approach, in which source code is distributed
to allow for assurance reviews by our customers, our resellers,
 and other experts
<LI>No users are allowed on the firewall system itself
<LI>Anything that can be logged, should be logged, for a complete
security audit trail
<LI>Strong user authentication methods and mechanisms must be
supported and encouraged
<LI>A firewall should  enforce an organization's network security
policy, not impose one of its own
</UL>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

 

