<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>VSAM Effectiveness</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG SRC="/docs/images/assurance.gif" border=0 ALT="Assurance" WIDTH=78 HEIGHT=16>
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<font size=6>VSAM Accomplishments</font>
<BR>


<BLOCKQUOTE>

During the last two years, we have applied the
VSAM technology to the TMach system.  The purpose of the effort was to
determine how to gain the most assurance for a fixed cost.  In doing
so, we made several discoveries.

<P>

First, VSAM allowed us to focus the major portion of the assurance
effort on a small selection of the most vulnerable components of the
design or implementation.  Using the VSAM's vulnerability measure, we
were able to identify that the kernel, name server and file server are
the most vulnerable components of the TMach system.  This
identification allowed us to concentrate the assurance effort on these
three vulnerable components and to use testing on the remainder of the
system.

<P>

Second, VSAM allowed us to gain assurance that the implementation
correctly implements the system policy.  For instance, to gain
assurance of the correctness of the read operation, we mapped the high
level requirements to the behavior of how the kernel and the file
server handle page faults.  This type of mapping is very difficult
with other assurance methodologies.  Inexpensive assurance techniques,
such as testing and code-walkthroughs, in addition to being
incomplete, are usually validated against informally generated
requirements. In contrast, expensive formal assurance techniques, such
as formal verification, are usually applied only at the high level
design level.  As a result, they provide high assurance of the design
only and leave it unclear whether the implementation is faithful to
the design.

<P>

Third, in the process of formalizing the vulnerability measure used in
VSAM, we found our intuitive notion of vulnerability was inaccurate.
Before our analysis, we believed that one of two mechanisms that
implement the file access enforcement was more vulnerable than the
other.  However, to our surprise our analysis showed the exact
opposite.  When we estimated the maximal damage that can be caused by
flaws in each component, we found that the mechanism we thought was less
vulnerable actually caused more damage.  When we formalized our
thought process, we found that we overlooked some important factors.

<P>

Finally, VSAM allowed us to find a design flaw in access enforcement
sufficiently early to save precious development time.  Our analysis
uncovered an error in the design of the access enforcement.  While the
developers would have found the design error during testing, by
finding the error early the developers were able to avoid adverse
consequences.

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-- signature -->

