<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Applying VSAM</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG SRC="/docs/images/assurance.gif" border=0 ALT="Assurance" WIDTH=78 HEIGHT=16>
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<font size=6>An Application of the Vertical Slice Assurance Methodology</font>
<BR>

<h3>Introduction</h3>

<BLOCKQUOTE>

This web page provides an overview of how we applied the VSAM methodology
to obtain assurance that the TMach Operating System's file open call
behaved securely.  We will describe how the VSAM took advantage of
TMach's highly modular design to gain a cost effective assurance strategy.

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<h3>General Approach</h3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

To meet the architectural requirements of B3 of TCSEC and F-B3, E5 of
ITCSEC, the TMach operating system makes extensive use of strict
layering and modularization.  Not only is the TCB layered and
modularized, the architecture of every server is also modularized and
layered.  Each server is decomposed into subsystems, which are layered
so that every high layer subsystem within a server uses only the
interface services of lower layer subsystems.

<P>

The application of the vertical slice assurance methodology uses this
aspect of TMach architecture in determining the levels of abstraction
for its analysis.  We started with the policy layer for the file open
call and performed stepwise refinement until we reach the code level.
For all layers except the lowest, the specification of a component
describes a design for implementation in terms of its next lower layer
subcomponents.  We used a range of techniques for the specification
from graphic presentation to pseudo programming language.  The <A
HREF=#vertical">figure</A> below describes an example of functional
decomposition down to the four layers where the lowest layer is the
code.  For each component, we first determine the criticality of its
correctness and the complexity of its implementation.  This
information is then used to determine the type of specification and
assurance technique required.  The formality of specification of
components ranges from the most formal specification to informal
English descriptions.  The highly critical and complex components will
be specified using the Z notation.  Components that are not very
critical will be specified informally.  Similarly, the assurance
technique used will range from rigorous analysis to testing; more
complex algorithms require more rigorous assurance techniques, while
algorithms with low complexity will be tested to validate their
correctness.

<P>
<HR  size=2 >
<A NAME="vertical">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/docs/images/vertical.gif"></CENTER>
</A>
<HR  size=2 >
<BR CLEAR=ALL> 


</BLOCKQUOTE>
<h3>Application of VSAM to File_IO</h3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

For the file open call we instantiated the four levels of abstraction
above as follows.
The highest layer consisted of the formulation of the policy
requirements for the file open call.

<P>

At the second layer we described a high level algorithm for opening a
file.  The algorithm was written in terms of abstract service calls,
since, while there are three different ways to open a file, the TMach
servers perform essentially the same functions for each.  These
abstract services are provided by the Kernel, the Name Server and the
File Server.  At this layer, we specified the interaction of the three
servers and the correctness requirements for each abstract service
call.  Due to its criticality, all specifications at this layer were
done formally in Z.  The demonstration that the top layer
file open call was correctly implemented by these abstract service calls
was fairly rigorous, consisting of a detailed sketch of the
mathematical proof.

<P>

At the third layer, we described the three different ways to open a
file, and showed how each abstract service call was implemented by the
specific server interface calls.  Next, we refined each specific server
interface call in terms of subsystem interface calls.  We applied the
criterion for criticality and complexity to each subsystem interface
call; based on that determination, we specified each subsystem interface
call at the appropriate level of formality.  Using these
specifications we then showed that they correctly implemented the specific
server interface calls.  We then demonstrated the correspondence
between the second and third layers of abstraction, using the
specification of the specific server interface calls.  When the third
layer implementation of a service was deemed critical enough to have
formal specifications, we  used proof sketches to demonstrate that
the third layer implemented the second layer.  For the other
specifications we used an informal justification to show the
correspondence.  Lastly, depending on the computation of
criticality and complexity, we determined the assurance technique
to be used to show that the component was implemented correctly.

<P>

In the final layer of abstraction, we examined the source code of the 
major subsystems.  Since the TMach system is written in C++, an object 
oriented language, the classes provided a natural decomposition of 
the source code into components.  The Layer Four components were
the C++ classes representing the major datastructures and 
operations.  The class declarations defined the class interfaces and 
the definitions of the member functions defined how the classes 
interact.  We identified the roles and interactions of the classes to 
determine their criticality.
We then demonstrated the correspondence between the final layer of 
abstraction and the third layer of abstraction.  This correspondence 
was done through informal justification, code walkthroughs and 
testing.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-- signature -->

