<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>SIGMA Project Briefing - Footnotes</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=191 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/dissys.gif" border=0 ALT="Distributed Systems Security">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<font size=5>Footnotes</font><P>

<a name="Enclave">
[1] In Sigma, we use the term
<em>
enclave
</em>
rather than the term
<em>
domain
</em>
used in the CORBA Security specification to describe several different
kinds of groupings of distributed system components.
Each of the various kinds of domains has a separate role with respect to
inter-system interoperation and security.
Our use of the term enclave is to describe a domain that is protected
from outside systems, but which can interoperate with them.
<p>

<a name="Practice">
[2] In practice, large systems have multiple points of connection to
    outside networks, and hence multiple instances of security mechanisms,
    each enforcing (hopefully) the same policies.
<p>

<a name="Focus">
[3] As described above, Sigma will focus on interoperation by means
    of interoperability protocols, and specifically IIOP.
    However, the techniques discussed here are just as applicable
    to other interoperability protocols, or bridging approaches
    in which one ORB's internal protocols are translated to those
    of another ORB. The only difference is in the definition of
    the protocol that carries object requests from outside systems.
<p>

<a name="Critical">
[4] The ORB Gateway host is a security-critical system component, just as
    is the firewall host. Therefore, an ORB Gateway host must be protected in
    the same way that firewall hosts are, e.g. limited and strictly controlled
    set of software installed, no user login permitted, no other services
    offered by the host.
<p>

<a name="Directly">
[5] If needed, clients and servers can also directly access particular
    services of DTM, the OS, or the ORB.<P>

<a href="sigpap.html">Return to Sigma Research Paper</a>


