<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Security and the World Wide Web Presentation</TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#000000" VLink="#666699"
ALink="#666699">

<center>
<a href="http://shadowplay.tis.com/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28
SRC="http://shadowplay.tis.com/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS
Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<a href="http://shadowplay.tis.com/docs/research/network/index.html">
<IMG width=112 height=15
SRC="http://shadowplay.tis.com/docs/images/nsecurity.gif" border=0
ALT="Network Security"></a>
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<IMG src="http://shadowplay.tis.com/docs/images/www.gif">
<P>

<Font size= 6>Security and the World Wide Web</font>



<P>



<I>
David I. Dalva<BR>
Trusted Information Systems, Inc.<BR>
dave@tis.com<BR>
8/12/94
</I>


<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>WWW Security Issues</H3>

<UL>
<LI>Threats the client software poses to the local computing environment.
<LI>Threats to server data.
<LI>Authentication/Confidentiality/Integrity issues.
</UL>


<HR>

<H3>Client-based Threats</H3>

<UL>
<LI>Client/navigator programs (e.g., Mosaic) interpret data downloaded from
    arbitrary servers.  Potential for trojan horses.  Known as a data driven
    attack to which many other systems are vulnerable (e.g., MIME, sendmail).

	<UL>
	<LI>Trojan horse URLs
	<LI>Postscript trojan horses
	<LI>User-defined interpreters (.mailcap)
	</UL>

<LI>Internet services available to the client (e.g., FTP, WAIS, Gopher) may
    circumvent a site's security policy, especially sites that are protected
    by firewalls.
</UL>


<HR>

<H3>Threats to Servers</H3>

<UL>
<LI>Modification of server's Web data.
<LI>User identification and authentication.
<LI>Access control over server's Web data.
<LI>Breaking into server by compromising web server software.  Using
    compromised server to break into other systems.
<LI>Improper configuration/trustworthiness of other server software that may
    compromise Web data.
</UL>


<HR>

<H3>Authentication/Confidentiality/Integrity Issues</H3>

<UL>
<LI>Mutual authentication and protection from message stream modification
    (e.g., to support electronic commerce).
<LI>Privacy of information (e.g., credit card numbers).
</UL>


<HR>

<H3>Potential Solutions</H3>

<UL>
<LI>HTTP Proxy
	<UL>
	<LI>Implement application gateways for various Internet protocols
	    (e.g., Telnet, FTP).
	<LI>Enforce client and/or server access to designated hosts.
	<LI>URL/language filtering.
	</UL>

<LI>Running safe clients that only call safe interpreters (e.g., secure
    Ghostscript).
</UL>


<HR>

<H3>Potential Solutions (cont'd)</H3>

<UL>
<LI>Running the clients, servers and/or interpreters in a restricted
    environment.
	<UL>
	<LI>Chroot with no privileges.
	<LI>Type enforcement*
	</UL>

<LI>Client/Proxy cooperation and authentication.
</UL>

<I>* At TIS we have implemented an experimental UNIX system that associates
type attributes with system objects (e.g., files, packets, etc.)  and
restricts processes to interact only with specified types.  This can be used
to implement restricted environments that are custom tailored for applications
such as HTTP clients, proxies, and servers.</I>


<HR>

<H3>State of the Art and Future Directions</H3>

<UL>
<LI>WWW provides limited capabilities for user identification and
    authentication, host access control, and logging.
<LI>Encryption capabilities being added for user authentication,
    confidentiality, and integrity (Secure HTTP, Shen).
<LI>Ongoing proxy work.  CERN has proxy.  TIS producing HTTP proxy.
</UL>


<HR>

<H3>TIS HTTP Proxy</H3>

<B>Short Term</B>
<UL>
<LI>Use CERN proxy as development base.
<LI>Implement a unified access control model for all services that HTTP proxy
    provides in a style similar to the TIS Firewall Toolkit.
<LI>Enhance logging as needed.
</UL>

<B>Long Term</B>

<UL>
<LI>Would like to work with CERN to unify TIS and CERN proxies.
<LI>Include URL/language filtering.
<LI>Cooperate with trusted clients/navigators as they are produced.
<LI>Modularize proxy into small, easy to evaluate components.
</UL>

</Blockquote>

<!-- signature -->


