<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>The Top Ten Reasons</TITLE>

<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222"
ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/products/gauntlet/index.html">
<IMG width=284 height=65
SRC="/docs/images/gtop.gif" border=0
ALT="gauntlet"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=67 height=16
SRC="/docs/images/overview.gif" border=0
ALT="overview">
</center>
<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<TABLE border=0 >
<TR>
<TD><Font size= 6> The Top 10 Reasons Why an Application Gateway is the
Most Secure Firewall</font>
</TD>			
<TD><IMG width=115 height=147
SRC="/docs/images/clipboard10.gif" border=0
ALT="clipboard" ></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>


<CENTER>
<TABLE border=2 cellpadding=4>
<TR>
<TD Width="10"></TD>
<TD><B>Gauntlet/Application Gateway</B></TD>		
<TD><B>Packet Filter/Filtering Gateway</B></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>1</TD>
<TD>Built on a general purpose computer system</TD>			
<TD>Usually implemented on an internet router system, a &quot;black
box&quot; disallowing customization in service or control</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>2</TD>
<TD>No direct, IP connections between inside and outside hosts; inside
hosts are insulated from outside attack</TD>			
<TD>All traffic is analyzed in the form of IP network packets; direct,
&quot;hard&quot; connections are created between inside and outside
hosts</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>3</TD>
<TD>Data is handled through <I>application-level</I> data streams for more
granular access control</TD>			
<TD>Data is handled through <I>IP</I><I>packet-level</I> filters on
per-packet basis; access cannot be controlled based on specific data or on
a per-user basis, not even with so-called &quot;dynamic&quot; filters</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>4</TD>
<TD>&quot;That which is not expressly permitted, is prohibited.&quot; </TD>			
<TD>Often, &quot;That which is not expressly prohibited, is
permitted.&quot;</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>5</TD>
<TD>Proxy software can implement additional mechanisms to counter
application-specific attacks</TD>			
<TD>Inside host's application software could be threatened by certain
allowed services </TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>6</TD>
<TD>Service proxies can be modified for strong user authentication
requiring specific information for access </TD>	
<TD>Strong user authentication impossible</TD>
</TR>


<TR>
<TD>7</TD>
<TD>Proxies can perform application-specific screening to determine whether
or not to relay certain, potentially dangerous data  </TD>			
<TD>Since data is handled at the packet level, it cannot be analyzed for
potentially dangerous data</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>8</TD>
<TD>Can be programmed and tested to ensure that if a failure occurs, system
will fail in the &quot;off&quot; or &quot;closed&quot; position,
disallowing any information to pass</TD>			
<TD>A router can fail in the &quot;open&quot; position allowing access to
information</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>9</TD>
<TD>Majority of commercial firewalls are application gateways </TD>			
<TD>Majority of &quot;homemade&quot; gateways are filtering gateways </TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>10</TD>
<TD>More secure than other types of gateways; allows examination of data</TD>			
<TD>More flexible than other types of gateways, but less secure</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>


<P>
<I>
Application gateways provide necessary services to both local
and remote users without actually granting remote users direct
access to the private network. Application gateways support terminal
service (TELNET, Rlogin, TN3270), file transfer (FTP), electronic
mail (SMTP, POP3), Printer, Usenet News (NNTP), the Worldwide
Web (HTTP), Gopher, the X Window System (X11), Finger, and Whois.
Gauntlet Firewalls provide a generic interface to multiple forms
of user authentication, including both software- and token-based
one-time password systems.

</i>
<P>
<a href="/docs/products/gauntlet/gauntlet4.html">
<IMG width=60 height=24 SRC="/docs/images/next.gif" border=0 ALT="next">
