<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Secrets Agent continued</TITLE></HEAD>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (e-mail:jgang@jamesgang.com) -->

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/index.html">
<IMG width=378 height=27  SRC="/docs/images/tisbanner.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=115 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/cprofile.gif" border=0 ALT="cprofile">
</center>
<HR  size=2 >
<!-- Main Body -->
<P>
<B><h2>Clipper Chip alternative</B></h2>

<P><blockquote>
	To guarantee itself the ability to break new computer codes, the federal government proposed the so-called Clipper Chip, which would have given government agencies easy access to encrypted information. Many American companies and civil liberties groups loudly objected.</blockquote>
<P>
<B><h2>Enter Walker and TIS</B></h2>
<blockquote>
	TIS's solution is called "commercial key escrow." Rather than giving the decoder information directly to the government, a third-party that meets government security criteria would receive a set of keys.
<P>
	Such an arrangement, Walker and other's like Georgetown's Denning argue, would satisfy privacy concerns for companies and computer users while giving the government a way to search files after obtaining a warrant from a judge.
<P>
	"People need to use encryption to protect their communications," Denning said. "Key escrow goes a long way in addressing that problem in light of the government's interests." She said that about a half-dozen firms around the world offer encryption products with commercial key escrow, and that TIS would likely be the first American company to do so.
<P>
	Walker said that while the goals of the NSA, FBI and the State Department were laudable, the export ban placed on encrypted products has stunted the growth of America's encryption industry.
<BR>
	"The public wants to use it, but the government doesn't want us to," Walker said. "The crooks have all the protection they want."
<P>
	Walker insists that terrorists and drug dealers who communicate on the Internet probably don't give copies of the decoder keys to anyone other than their intended recipients. That means that as much as the government may want to decipher their computer transmissions, it can't do so by simply ordering up a spare set of keys.
<P>
	The government is close to accepting Walker's commercial  key escrow as a compromise, computer security experts said.
<P></blockquote>
<B><h2>Cosmetic change?</B></h2>
<P><blockquote>
	Not everyone considers Walker's plan  to be a satisfactory alternative, however, especially now that the Internet is poised to become a conduit for medical records, banking transactions and other sensitive communications.
<P>
	Some say TIS might as well be a branch of the government.
<BR>
	"Its nothing more than Clipper with a happy face," said Bruce Schneirer, a Minnesota-based cryptography consultant who has written a book on the subject. "All Walker has done is make a cosmetic change."
<P>
Schneirer insists the government shouldn't have easy access to private communications and that even with Walker's proposals, the American encryption market is doomed to failure.
<P>
	"The terrorists sure as hell aren't going to give their keys to anyone," he said.
<P>
	David Sobel, a Washington-based computer privacy advocate, agreed. "What is at issue here is the further development of the Internet as a widely used and secure means of communication," said Sobel, who serves as legal counsel to the Electronic Privacy Information Center. 
<BR>
"Why should we make it easier for the government to inspect private information of its citizens? I thought it wasn't our job to make it easier on the government. It's their burden."
<BR>
	Sobel compared commercial key escrow to leaving a spare set of keys to your house with the local police department.
<P>
	Although the controversy isn't expected to subside even with governmental approval of TIS's commercial key escrow, the company expects to continue growing-from Glenwood.
<P>
	"This is a company on the leading edge of the computer revolution," EDA's Story said.
	TIS is a point of pride for Story, and he uses it to lure other high-tech firms to join the 100 or so already in Howard County.
	"This is truly an international company that, in this economy, can go anywhere in the world. I am delighted that they  continue to choose to do this here."
</blockquote>
<A HREF="/docs/corporate/w032896.html"><IMG width=60 height=24 SRC="/docs/images/next.gif" border=0 ALT="next"></a>

