<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Secrets Agent continued</TITLE></HEAD>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (e-mail:jgang@jamesgang.com) -->

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/index.html">
<IMG width=378 height=27  SRC="/docs/images/tisbanner.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=115 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/cprofile.gif" border=0 ALT="cprofile">
</center>
<HR  size=2 >
<!-- Main Body -->

<P>
<B><h2>Building walls</h2></B>
<P><blockquote>
	For the past year, TIS's employees have been working to convince the Defense Department to allow unrestricted conversation on the Internet without anyone listening in-or at least listening in without a search warrant.
<P>
	The technology to communicate in secret has been around almost as long as people have been passing messages to each other. It's called cryptography, and, in its simplest form, offers a code understood by both the sender and the receiver of the message.
<P>
	Encryption - TIS's specialty - involves the use of codes developed by cryptographers to scramble computer files into unreadable gibberish.
<P>
	In earlier days, simple codes substituted one letter for another: "S" became "T"; "P" became "Q"; and "Y" became "Z," turning the word "SPY" into "TQZ." If you knew the substitution method, you could break the code.
<P>
	Today, instead of exchanging letters or substituting numbers for words, cryptography relies on algorithms and complex formulas to scramble messages. The "key" to unscrambling the code is usually a 64-character series of numbers.
<P>
	Once the sole province of governments, cryptography has become a widely used tool of corporations and individuals to control access to information.	
<P>
	Within the United States, businesses and other computer users may encrypt data for transmission anywhere in the country without giving the FBI or the Defense Department unrestricted access to the decoder keys.
<P>
	But exporting encryption computer software is another matter. Citing the joint concerns of law enforcement and national security, the departments of State, Commerce and Defense have ruled that the government must have a copy of the key to read the files.
<P>
	They contend that an international cyberspace jammed with communiques impervious to the watchful eyes of spies and cops could create a fertile breeding ground for criminal enterprises.
<P>
	American businesses have balked at giving the government such access and have turned instead to software companies in Europe to buy their security systems.
</blockquote>
<P>

</blockquote>
<A HREF="/docs/corporate/w032896-5.html"><IMG width=60 height=24 SRC="/docs/images/next.gif" border=0 ALT="next"></a>

