<!-- Main Body -->
<font size=6>Philosophy of Protection for Triad</font><p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<a name="Sservers">
<h2>
Trusted Server Mechanisms
</h2>

The trusted servers of the Triad TCB are based on the trusted servers
of the TMach system and use the primitive kernel abstractions
described in the previous section to produce the more sophisticated
abstractions which are then provided to the user.
The following sections provide more detail on server-level abstractions of
subjects, named security-objects, and unnamed security-objects.
All Triad system resources are used by subjects by means of accessing
security-objects.
<p>

<a name="Sserversubject">
<h4>
Subjects
</h4>

In Triad, the subject is based on the kernel abstractions of task and
thread: a group of tasks all with the same security ID is considered
a subject.  This definition permits the sharing of security-objects
among multiple tasks, which in turn facilitates the development of
multi-tasking application software.
To correctly enforce access mediation decisions, the TCB
permits only those object accesses which meet the following
requirement: the security ID of the task attempting to exercise an
access must be the same as the security ID
of the subject which had originally been granted that access.
In this way a child task can legitimately access security-objects
for which the TCB approved access for the parent task if they have the
same security ID.  
<p>

The creation of the initial task of a new subject is
performed by the TCB Subject Server.
The kernel provides a separate, privileged interface for creation of a
task with a different security attribute than the creating task;
the Subject Server has exclusive claim on this privilege.
The Subject Server also maintains the database which
maps from a security ID value to a specific set of
integrity, discretionary, and mandatory security attributes.
Since the kernel tags each message with the security ID of the sender,
the receiver of a message can extract the security ID
from the message and consult the Subject Server to obtain the
security attributes of its sender.
This functionality is of critical importance to the access mediation by
the TCB: all client access requests are in the form of IPC messages,
and mediation is based on the subject security attributes
derived from the security ID of the message.
Note that this database of the Subject Server is a global database,
i.e., each Triad host's Subject Server has the same database as
the other hosts.
In this way access mediation decisions---which are based
in part on subject security attributes---are uniform
throughout the distributed system.
<p>

Subjects are created in one of two ways:
login of human users or initialization of subsystem-based users.
<p>

Login is an interaction between a human and an instance of a TCB
component called the Trusted Shell (TSH).
If the human can authenticate for legitimate access, the TSH will create
a new subject, consisting of a new task.
The security ID of this task represents the human-specified user identity,
along with other associated security attributes: mandatory sensitivity level,
discretionary and integrity attributes.
The Authentication Server is a trusted server which maintains
a database on user information, including which levels
and integrity attributes are allowed for each user.
The TSH enforces the Identification and Authentication policy
by only creating subjects for which the security ID matches
the data in the authentication database.
<p>

Creation of subsystem-based subjects is similar, except that the security
attributes are not specified by a human as part of a login procedure.
Each subsystem-based subject's security attributes are drawn from an
administratively controlled database of TCB configuration data.
This database completely specifies the security attributes of each such subject,
and the code to run in the subject's tasks.
<a href="footnotes.html#Attributes">[5]</a>
This configuration data
is used by the TCB during system initialization time to create
subsystem-based subjects which are required to run at system startup.
Such subjects are analogous to ``daemon'' or ``background'' processes of
other systems.
<p>

In a complete, non-prototypical Triad system, creation of subsystem-based
subjects would not be limited to system initialization
or to the use of the security administrator's interface.
More likely, subsystem-based subjects would be created
using the services of an Application Management Server.
An Application Management Server would be an element of the TCB with 
access to system privileges such as
creating subjects with distinct security IDs.
An Application Management Server would incorporate system-specific
functionality to create, control, and terminate application-based subjects
as necessary to perform the mission of the dedicated/embedded system.
The means used to create subjects would be similar to that of
system initialization software, including the use of some
administratively controlled database describing the subjects.
Thus, clients of the Application Management Server could request that
certain application subjects could be created, but clients would not
be able to arbitrarily specify the security attributes of the subjects.
Also, existing MAC, DAC, and integrity mechanisms would be used to
enforce the system's security policy as it applies to application
subject creation.
<p>

<a name="Snamedobj">
<h4>
Item Management
</h4>

Other than the kernel, the TSH, and the Subject Server, the remaining TCB
components can be divided into three groups. The
<em>
Root Name Server
</em>
(RNS) manages the space of all named objects and mediates all security-object
access.
Trusted
<em>
item managers
</em>
are trusted servers which implement named security-objects and enforce the
access control decisions of the RNS. The remaining auxiliary components
(the Audit Server, the Authentication Server, the Host Control Server,
the Trusted Administration Shell) perform administrative functions.
These are not central to Triad's protection mechanisms,
and are not described in this document.
<p>

The interaction between subjects, the RNS, and item managers
is referred to as
<em>
item management.
</em>
<p>

The only way a subject can access a named object is by making an access
request to the RNS.
The request takes the form of an IPC message from the client task
to the RNS.
All tasks are provided at creation with a send right for a port
from which the RNS receives such access request messages.
<p>

In an access request message (step 1 in Figure 2)
the client specifies an object by naming an item within the name space managed
by the RNS.
If the name is valid and the RNS's mediation is successful, the RNS
gives the subject a ``handle'' for the named object (step 2a).
This handle is a send right for a newly created 
<em>
item descriptor port,
</em>
which represents the specific subject's access to the specific security-object.
The RNS sends receive right for this port to the item manager for the
security-object (step 2b), along with all relevant information concerning
the handle, including the security ID of the subject and approved
access mode(s) to the object.
<p>

Once the subject obtains the descriptor port, it can send messages
over the port to request the item manager to provide object data
or perform an operation on the object (step 3).
The item manager checks that the subject is indeed the valid holder for the
handle and the requested access mode is indeed allowed by the handle.
If both checks are satisfied, the manager provides the requested
service; otherwise, the manager denies the request.
These checks are called
<em>
access enforcement
</em>
of the access mediation
performed by the RNS.
<p>
<center>
<img height=188 width=322 src="ps/nsopen.gif" border=0 alt="NSOPEN">
<br> 
Figure 2: Client Request to Open an Item
</CENTER>
<p>

External paging is an alternative way for an item manager to provide
access to clients.
The File Server is the only trusted item manager which acts as an
external pager.
With external paging, the client obtains the item descriptor port as shown in
Figure 2.
However, rather than using the port to send messages to the File Server,
the client uses the port as a parameter to the kernel call used to map
the memory object.
Parameters to this
<em>
vm_map
</em>
call include the port---
which indicates which memory object to map--- and access modes,
which indicate how the client wishes to use it.
<p>

After this
<em>
vm_map
</em>
call, it is the kernel (rather than the
client) that communicates with the item manager via the port.
As part of memory object setup activity, the kernel and the pager
perform the same access enforcement as described above:
the memory-object can only be mapped by the subject for
which the RNS approved the access; and the client-requested memory access
modes must be consistent with the access modes approved by the RNS.
The RNS conveys this information to the item manager along
with the item descriptor port; the item manager conveys
the information in turn to the kernel, and the kernel
enforces these restrictions on client use of memory objects.
<p>

All items in the Triad name space are also security-objects.
Some are managed by trusted item managers which enforce the
access control mediation decisions made by the RNS. Other items
are mediated in a manner that requires no further enforcement,
and are managed by untrusted item managers. 
The following sections provide descriptions of the various
kinds of security-objects:<br>
<blockquote>
<a href="#Snmspobj">Directory</a><br>
<a href="#Snmspobj">Symbolic Link</a><br>
<a href="#Snmspobj">Typedef</a><br>
<a href="#Sfile">File</a><br>
<a href="#Ssdev">Virtual Terminal</a><br>
<a href="#Ssdev">Printer</a><br>
<a href="#Sconnpt">Connection Point</a><br>
<a href="#Sunnamed">IPC-Object</a><br>
</blockquote>

<a name="Snmspobj">
<h4>
Name Space Objects
</h4>

Every named object in the Triad system is part of the system name
space.  The individual named entries are called
<em>
items
</em>
and each item is an instance of a type, e.g., directory or file.  The
system name space is organized hierarchically as a directed graph of
items.  A
<em>
node
</em>
represents an item in the name space and an
<em>
edge
</em>
represents a named object.  A
<em>
pathname
</em>
for an item is an ordered list of item names giving a path from a specific
point in the name space to the item.  Every item in the name space has a
security level and an ACL associated with it.
<p>

<em>
Directories
</em>
are the kind of name space objects which are
internal nodes in the name space graph.  A directory is a repository
for other security-objects, e.g., files, directories, symbolic links.
<em>
Symbolic links
</em>
are name space objects that serve as pointers to
other parts of the name space, allowing for alternative pathnames for
the same item.
<p>

<em>
Typedef
</em>
objects are the final kind of name space object.  Every
item in the name space has a type associated with it.  For each type,
there is a typedef object in the name space, and the typedef object
contains the information that describes the type.  There are two kinds
of types in the Triad system: user types and TCB types.  The TCB types
are managed by the RNS.  Every typedef object contains
information which the RNS needs to perform access mediation on objects
of the type. However, this
information is only relevant for TCB types.  For types managed by
untrusted item managers, in contrast, the item managers cannot be
trusted to abide by the type data.  As a result the TCB treats all
non-TCB-managed type as consisting of objects of a single level, with
all operations being treated as read-write.
<p>

The RNS is the item manager for the name space.  A primary function of
the RNS is name resolution, which must be performed in order to
mediate access to an object.  Directory entries are matched against
pathname components until a terminal element is reached.  To interpret
directory entries and mediate access to them, certain
<em>
attributes
</em>
about each item---such as the item's security level, its access
control list (ACL), and its type---must be available to a name server.
<p>

The RNS is responsible for the
real-time aspects of the implementation of name space objects and item
management.  In implementing its services, the RNS must ensure the
real-time scheduling coherence of its activities.  Both real-time
clients and the RNS must cooperate to do so; clients may use RPC to
communicate with the RNS to resolve names and access name space
objects, and the RNS must be prepared to receive and process these
RPCs.  To do so, the RNS need only use kernel interfaces to create
threads capable of receiving RPCs, and allow these threads to receive
on the ports to which the RNS holds the receive rights.  As a result,
the kernel handles the scheduling coherence, and the real-time feature
of RNS services is ensured.
<p>

The RNS is also responsible for the distributed aspects of the
implementation of name space objects and item management.
The RNS's distribution functionality is that of replicating
the items which it manages.
The object replication functionality is similar to that of the
file server (described below) except that the RNS must ensure
the strict consistency of distributed object security data.
The need for distributed control of object security data arises
because some items in the RNS-managed name space may be replicated.
As a result, changes may be made to an item's security attributes
when there are multiple copies of the item and its attributes. For
each RNS to implement the same security policy, they must each
work from identical security databases.

<a name="Sfile">
<h4>
File Objects
</h4>

Files are permanent repositories for data.
The File Server (FS) manages files.
In addition to the RNS, the FS is the other of the two Triad servers
which implements real-time service.
The FS does so in the same manner as the RNS, by correctly
handling RPCs from clients.
Similarly, the FS is also the other Triad server with the distribution
functionality of object replication.
<p>

Object replication allows multiple hosts to maintain copies, or replicas,
of an object.
Triad files may be replicated, so the file may be locally accessed
on each node for which the local FS maintains a replica.
In addition to increased local availability, remote availability
can be increased as well.
For an unreplicated file, if there is a failure of the host which runs
the file's FS, then that file is completely unavailable.
For a replicated file, multiple replicas allow the file to be accessed
even if some replicas are unavailable.
<p>

With multiple replicas of an object comes the need to enforce consistency
on the replicas so that when one replica is updated, other replicas are as well.
Triad's replication mechanism provides flexibility in defining replica
consistency, which can be tuned to the requirements stemming from the
object's use.
For example, each replicated object has associated with it an 
attribute called a write quorum, which specifies how many replicas
must be updated during for any write operation on the object.
<p>

At one extreme, a write quorum of 1 means that any replica
can be updated without reference to any other.
The other extreme is a write quorum of all replicas; in such
cases, all replicas are locked before any write, and all
are updated before being unlocked.
With this ``strict consistency'' approach, there is no way for
one replica to become out of date with respect to others.
There are a range of intermediate approaches between these extremes.
Some allow out-of-date replicas but prevent inconsistent replicas
with conflicting values.
<p>

Some replicated objects are critical to the TCB, and strict consistency must
be applied to them to avoid out-of-date security-relevant data.
Similar to the RNS's strict consistency for object security data,
some replicated files may contain other security data.
Each such TCB data file is created so that strict consistency
governs its updates.
<p>

In the current Triad system, the RNS and FS are distributed servers
which use object replication.
A complete Triad systems would include other distributed versions of
other TMach servers that need to maintain distributed databases of
security-relevant data, e.g. the authentication database, the
security ID table, audit data.


<a name="Ssdev">
<h4>
Device Objects
</h4>

The Device Server is the manager for all physical devices on the system.
After gaining access to all physical devices, using its privileged master
device port, the Device Server services any client that has been successfully
mediated for access to a physical device.
<p>

Some physical devices are classified as fixed-level devices,
i.e., devices with a single security level which is defined
at the time of system initialization and never changed.
Since devices are not used by the TCB itself, the TCB permits them to
be used by subjects, in accordance with the usual access controls.
<p>

Each such fixed-level device is represented by a name in the name space.
The Device Server is the item manager for these named items.
Clients request access to devices using the usual RNS
interface for accessing an item.  The RNS grants access to the device
using the same MAC, DAC, and integrity checks as any other
security-object.  Once access has been granted, the client can
communicate with the Device Server to obtain a send right for the
device control port of the device.  Subsequently, the client can use
the device control port to communicate directly with the kernel, to
access the device.
<p>

However, most devices are not accessible to subjects in this manner,
because most devices are either multi-level devices, or devices which
operate at a single level that can change over time.  For
these devices, access is limitied to a specific trusted server which
virtualizes the device.  That is, the server creates named
security-objects which represent virtual devices.  Subjects can access
the virtual device through the name space, but the trusted item
manager services these virtual devices by using the resource of the
physical device.
<p>

There are two kinds of virtual device security-objects, each with a
separate trusted server that acts as an item manager. 
Printer objects represent printers on the system,
and are managed by the Printer Server.  Virtual terminal objects
represent terminals on the system, and are are managed by the Virtual
Terminal Server (VT Server).
<p>

Each of these servers obtains access to physical devices, and exports
a virtual device interface to clients, using a distinct named item
to represent distinct virtual devices which may be multiplexed over
the same physical device.
For example, the VT Server obtains access to the physical terminals from
the Device Server and exports a virtual terminal interface to its clients by
multiplexing multiple virtual terminals over a single physical terminal.
The Printer server performs similar kinds of virtualization.
<p>

An additional notable feature of the VT Server is its management of
the the Secure Attention Key sequence (SAK), which is a keystroke
sequence that can be used as a direct human interface (or trusted
path) to the TCB.  Even when a subject task is using a virtual
terminal and handling the keyboard input, the SAK is intercepted by
the VT Server, which suspends the subject task using the virtual
terminal.  Control of the terminal is then passed to a Trusted Shell
task.  Because of the authentication functionality of the TSH, the SAK
is the primary means of invoking the TSH.  Since part of TSH
functionality is authentication (e.g., as part of subject creation,
see the section on
<a href="serv.html#Sserversubject">Subjects</a>),
and since authentication can
include a password check, the SAK can be used to ensure that passwords
are typed to the TCB without danger of spoofing or eavesdropping by
software designed to capture passwords.  Use of the SAK is
particularly critical for users who perform administrative duties.
These duties are performed via the human interface of the TSH, which
uses authentication to determine whether the user is authorized to
perform administrative functions.
<p>

Note that there is no requirement for additional distribution
functionality for devices.
Virtual device security-objects and fixed-level device security-objects
are named items in the name space, and the distribution functionality
of the RNS allows distributed access to them.


<a name="Sconnpt">
<h4>
Other Named Objects
</h4>

The one remaining kind of named security-object in TMach is the
<em>
connection point.
</em>
Each of the other kinds of security-object corresponds to a type
managed by a trusted item manager, and every item of that type is
a security-object of the corresponding kind.
For example, each item of type file is both a file security-object,
and an item managed by the File Server.
Likewise, each item of type symbolic link is both a symbolic link
security-object, and an item managed by the Root Name Server.
<p>

However, even though access requests to all items are mediated by the
RNS, not all items need be managed by an item manager that is
part of the TCB. 
TMach is an extensible system with mechanisms for defining new types
and implementing new untrusted item managers for objects of those types.
Because such untrusted item managers cannot be relied upon to operate
in accordance with the security policy, the TMach TCB treats these
non-system-managed items differently.
<p>

Every item of every non-TCB-managed type is represented by
a connection point security-object.
Access to connection points is mediated on the basis of the
fact that access to a connection point gives the accessing
subject some access to another subject, i.e. the untrusted item manager.
The mediation is simple: the accessing subject must have the
same sensitivity label as the subject that is acting as the
item manager for the item in the request.
Equality of label is required because, given the port that connects the
client and item manager, the two can set up bidirectional communication.
<p>

Note that a connection point is simply a named security-object which
represents communication with a subject, i.e. the untrusted item manager
of the item named by a connection point.
However, when a client gains access to a connection point security-object,
it also gains access to another kind of security-object.
This other security-object is an
<em>
ipc-object.
</em>
An ipc-objects represents the state of one subject that is accessible
to another subject via IPC to the first subject.
When a client gains access to any one of potentially several items of a
given non-TCB-managed type, that client gains access to two
security-objects: the connection point item itself, and the ipc-object
of the subject that is the manager for the item.
For every non-TCB-managed type, every name of every item of that type can
be used to gain access to the ipc-object of the same untrusted item manager.
The next section describes ipc-objects in more detail.

<a name="Sunnamed">
<h4>
Unnamed Objects
</h4>

The one kind of unnamed object in Triad is the
<em>
ipc-object.
</em>
Each ipc-object represents the communication capabilities of one subject.
An ipc-object is implicitly created whenever a subject is created.  Whenever
a subject is destroyed, the associated ipc-object is implicitly destroyed.
A subject can obtain access to an ipc-object in one of two ways.
First, a subject is implicitly given access to its own ipc-object.
Second, a subject can acquire access to another subject's ipc-object
as a side effect of communication between the subjects.
As described in the previous section, the TCB mediates all cases of
communication between subjects, and therefore all ipc-object access
is mediated by the TCB as well.
<p>

Because inter-subject communication is potentially bi-directional
all ipc-object access is read-write. Therefore the policy enforced
on ipc-object access is that the label of the
accessing subject must be the same as the label of the accessed object
(which is the label of the subject associated with the ipc-object).
Because all ipc-object operations are implicit in inter-subject communication,
names are not needed for ipc-object access, creation, or deletion.
Because ipc-objects are unnamed objects, only mandatory access control checks
on labels are applicable to ipc-object access.
<p>

The rest of this section provides more modeling details of ipc-object
access that is a result of communication between subjects.
Such ipc-object access occurs when a task obtains a port right that
enables it to communicate with another task.
As described above, acquisition of such port rights can only occur
either by mediated access to a connection point item, or by port-right
acquisition via ports derived from the connection point.
When a task obtains a send right to a port, the task's subject
(the subject which the task is a part of) gains access to an ipc-object.
This ipc-object is the one associated with the holder of the
receive right to that port.
<a href="footnotes.html#Notevery">[6]</a>
Access also occurs when a task obtains a receive right; the tasks with send
rights to the port gain access to the ipc-object of the new receiver.
<p>

Ipc-object accesses are always read-write because of the potentially
symmetric nature of communication via Mach ports.
<a href="footnotes.html#Twoway">[7]</a>
In addition to potential bi-directionality, communication between
tasks is also transferable because port rights are transferable.
As a result, ipc-object access is potentially transitive as well as symmetric.
That is, when one task establishes communication with a second task, there also
may be yet other tasks which are also in communication with the second task.
If so, then the second task can establish communication between the first
task and any of the other tasks with which the second is in communication,
merely by transferring port rights between them.
The term
<em>
communicating group
</em>
is used to describe a set of subjects whose
tasks have this potential transitive communication with one another.
<p>

Triad does not mediate the transfer of port rights in general.
Mediation of port right transfers would enable Triad to prevent
bi-directional communication between tasks of different labels,
and to grant read-only or write-only ipc-object access based
on uni-directional IPC.
However, rather than embedding such mediation in the Mach kernel,
Triad enforces a policy that ensures that
<em>
if
</em>
such bi-directional
and/or transitive communication does occur,
<em>
then
</em>
it is permissible.
As a result, the policy is simple (labels must be equal), and easy to enforce.
<p>

The enforcement is on access to
<em>
connection points
</em>,
which provide
access to another subject for the accessing subject.
When a subject is created, it has no communication with any other subject.
A connection point is the means to contact another subject.
When a subject obtains access to a connection point--- and hence
obtains a port to the other subject--- Triad item access mediation
ensures that the two subjects have the same label.
Thus, if bi-directional communication is established, the resulting
information flow will be permissible.
Likewise, if either subject gains port rights to other subjects and transfers
port rights to establish transitive communication, then the result will still
be permissible because all parties had to have had the same label in 
order to be communicating in the first place.
<a href="footnotes.html#Notall">[8]</a>
<p>

In terms of ipc-objects and communicating groups, we say that
connection-point access mediation takes place
<em>
as though
</em>
symmetric and transitive ipc-object access actually occurs.
The following kinds of ipc-object access are permitted:
symmetric ipc-object access between the client and each of the subjects
in the item manager's communicating group; and
symmetric ipc-object access between the item manager and each of the subjects
in the client's communicating group.
In other words, the client's communicating group and the item manager's
communicating group are merged to form one communicating group.
There is no requirement for TCB awareness of whether or not symmetric or
transitive access actually occurs (as a result of subsequent port right
transfers), because mediation has already ensured that such ipc-object
accesses are permissible between any of the subjects in the new 
communicating group.
<p>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-- signature -->


