<!-- Main Body -->
<P>

<Font size= 6>Philosophy of Protection for Triad</font>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<a name="Sprotmech">
<h2>
TCB Protection Mechanisms
</h2>

Previous sections have described the following progression:
<menu>
<li>
the Triad TCB's services, stated in terms of subjects and security-objects,
<li>
the Triad policy on access by subjects of security-objects, and
<li>
the Triad access controls that enforce the policy.
</menu>
This section describes the
<em>
mechanisms
</em>
used by the Triad TCB to to implement these access controls in a manner
that is necessary and sufficient to enforce the policy.

The mechanisms fall into two groups.
First, there are hardware mechanisms that the kernel uses to implement
key security-critical aspects of its functionality.
Second, there are kernel mechanisms that the Triad servers use
to implement access controls.

<h4>
Kernel Use of Hardware Mechanisms
</h4>

The kernel uses basic hardware mechanisms to protect itself,
to protect the rest of the TCB from non-TCB code, and to protect
subjects from one another.

<h5>
Multi-state Hardware
</h5>
Multi-state hardware is the fundamental feature that the
kernel uses to protect itself.
The hardware provides more than one execution state.
Typically, two states are distinguished using the names
supervisor state and user state.
The kernel runs in supervisor state, which allows kernel software
to execute ``privileged'' instructions which provide basic control
over the physical memory and devices of the hardware.
The hardware prevents user state software from executing
these privileged instructions.
Because only the kernel has direct control of the hardware,
it can protect itself from tampering by any other software.
Being protected from interference, the kernel can provide the
security-critical functionality needed to implement the rest of the TCB.

<h5>
Separate Address Spaces
</h5>
Separation of address spaces is the primary security-critical functionality 
provided by the kernel.
The non-kernel TCB software is implemented as a set of trusted tasks.
Untrusted software also runs in tasks, which comprise subjects as
constructed by the server TCB software.
The kernel implements separate virtual address spaces using
memory management hardware, the control of which is possible
only in supervisor state
<a href="footnotes.html#VM">[9]</a>.
<p>

Because tasks have separate virtual address spaces,
TCB tasks are protected from interference by untrusted tasks.
Also of critical importance is the separation of untrusted
tasks from one another.
This prevents a task from accessing another task's data,
where the other task legitimately obtained the data from
the TCB via mediated access, but the first task did not.
Finally, task separation also enhances the assurance of
Triad by ensuring that each TCB task is separate from 
the others.
Each address space represents a separate domain in the non-supervisor state.
The switching between domains is controlled by a privileged
instruction in the supervisor state.  Triad makes extensive use of
this capability within the TCB in order to enforce modularity and
least privilege and to provide strong separation between TCB components.  

<p>
Thus, Triad usage of memory management hardware serves two purposes:
it gives a process an addressing environment which it can manage in
a controlled way; and it provides an efficient way of passing
information between processes, when and only when
the security policy allows it.  
Furthermore, the use of virtual memory techniques also subdivides an
address space into separate pieces which can be separately allocated
and have separate, different access attributes.
As a result, a task can have several memory-objects mapped, each
with its distinct memory access mode.

<h4>
Trusted Server Use of Kernel Mechanisms
</h4>

The Kernel Layer provides the primitive mechanisms that trusted servers
use to construct the subjects and security-objects of the system.
Trusted servers use kernel mechanisms to perform access mediation
and enforcement.

<h5>
Security ID
</h5>
The
<em>
security ID
</em>
is the fundamental kernel mechanism used by trusted
servers to mediate and enforce accesses of subjects.
Although the kernel does not interpret security IDs,
it does maintain the association of a security ID with each task,
which is specified at task creation by the creator of the task.
Trusted servers assign a security ID to each subject task, based
on identification and authentication data.
The kernel's role is to tag each message with the security ID of the
task that sent the message.
The receiver of the message can request the Security ID when receiving a
message.
Trusted servers use this feature to determine the identity of message senders.
Since subject-TCB interaction is by means of messages, the TCB can
always identify the security ID of a subject.

<p>
Just as the kernel is responsible for tagging local IPC with the
security ID of the sender, the distributed IPC mechanism is
responsible for the same tagging when IPC goes between hosts.
As described in the section on
<a href="kern.html#Sdipc">Distributed IPC</a>,
the distributed IPC mechanism delivers all messages tagged with the
security ID of the message's original sender.
As a result, trusted servers can determine the identity of the
subjects they are dealing with, even if the subject task is on
another node.

<p>
Given these basic security ID mechanisms, the trusted servers use
the security ID as a token which represents the security attributes
of the subject: MAC, DAC, and integrity attributes.
These subject attributes are used, along with security-object
attributes, in RNS access mediation decisions for both named
and unnamed objects.

<p>
In addition to mediation, the security-ID is also used in the
enforcement of access mediation.
When a subject initiates access to a security-object, the access
is mediated, but subsequently each use of the access must be
checked as well.
Each named security-object is implemented by a trusted server,
and each trusted server performs an enforcement check, by
comparing the identity of the subject accessing the object,
and the the identity of the subject whose access to the object
previously mediated.
The actual meaning of security ID need not be known, since
an identity comparison of the token value is all that is required.

<p>
The kernel also has a role in enforcement, in that some security-objects
are implemented via memory-objects, which are managed by the kernel.
The kernel also uses the security ID, to do the same identity
check for each memory object map operation: it checks the
identity between the mapping subject, and the subject to which
access was originally granted.
As for unnamed objects, basic kernel mechanisms are sufficient
for enforcement of mediation, without any specific
security ID checks (see the section on
<a href="serv.html#Sunnamed">Unnamed Objects</a>
.)

<p>
Note that although the kernel and the trusted item managers have a
critical role in security enforcement, untrusted item managers do not.
Unlike trusted item managers which are part of the TCB and which
implement security-objects, untrusted item managers are simply subjects
that might or might not correctly implement items.
Critical to this distinction is the difference between kinds of
<em>
security-objects
</em>
and types of
<em>
items
</em>
in the Triad name space.
For types which are managed by trusted item managers, all items of each
type are security objects of a kind that is specific to that type.
For types which are managed by untrusted item managers, all items of all
type are security objects of the same kind: connection points.
As far as the TCB is concerned, any untrusted item manager is free
either to misbehave, or instead to correctly maintain the distinction
between items, and to use security IDs to enforce RNS access mediation
decisions so that the RNS's access control mechanisms (e.g. ACLs) are
meaningful for the items.
In such latter cases, the untrusted manager supports well-defined
items in the name space, which from an
<em>
application
</em>
viewpoint seem to behave the same as TCB-managed items. From the
<em>
TCB
</em>
viewpoint, however, all non-TCB-managed items are
treated the same, without any assumption about the behavior of the
untrusted item manager.
This distinction is critical to the interplay of two important Triad goals:
Triad is an extensible object-oriented client-server system, but
the addition of a new untrusted item manager does not change
the TCB or the set of security-objects that it implements.


<h5>
Device Control and Mediation
</h5>

The security ID is the subject-related kernel mechanism
at the foundation of access control, but there must also
be an object-related mechanism as well.
Just as the security ID is a tamperproof way to store
subject security attributes, there must also be a tamperproof way
to store object security attributes.
<em>
Device control
</em>
is this kernel mechanism.
In contrast to subjects (where the kernel services of
tasks and threads are very close to the subject abstraction
implemented by the truster servers),
named security-objects are implemented by the trusted
servers using the relatively lower-level kernel service
of devices.

<p>
The RNS is the TCB component that maintains security-object security
attributes, and uses them in comparison with subject security attributes
in making access mediation decisions.
The RNS implements a name space which includes the name of each
named security-object.
The name space can be considered a database of information about all
names, including the hierarchical relationships that exist between names
because of the tree structure of the name space.
Security attributes are part of the data of each name in the name space.

<p>
This database is stored by the RNS on a mass storage device over which
the RNS has sole control.
The sole control is a result of the TCB's management of the master device port
and the device control port for the RNS's storage device
(see the sections on 
<a href="kern.html#Skdev">Devices</a>
and
<a href="serv.html#Ssdev">Device Objects</a>).
Therefore, it is the use of the kernel mechanism of device control
which allows the RNS to maintain the inviolability of the
security-critical data which is uses in mediation.

<p>
Note also that the RNS's name database is a distributed database, upon
which the RNS enforces strict consistency to maintain the integrity of
the database (as described in the section on
<a href="serv.html#Snmspobj">Name Space Objects</a>).

<p>
For ipc-objects, the name space also contains security data
critical to access mediation.
Access to an ipc-object is only granted if the
two connecting tasks have the same MAC label.
As described above, the MAC label of the client task (which requests
access to a connection point) is stored in the security ID tagged on
the request message.
However, connection point requests refer to a name, and the named item
has an untrusted manager task.
The MAC label of this manager task is stored as the MAC label associated
with the name, which was established when the item was created.
At item creation, the RNS performs mediation to ensure that the label
of the manager task matches the label stored as part of the name's data.

<p>
Because DAC and integrity constraints are not applicable
to ipc-objects, no further security data is needed for
mediation or enforcement.

<h5>
Device Control and Enforcement
</h5>

Device control is also used by other trusted servers to protect
the data and/or devices that they manage.
For example, the Printer Server retains control over printer
devices, to ensure no subject can use a printer, except via
the Printer Server, which implements security-critical
constraints on the use of printers.
As another example, the File Server retains control of its mass storage
device, so that no other task can access the data on it,
except by gaining RNS-mediated access to the file, and file service
through the File Server.
This has derivative effects for other trusted servers which store
TCB-critical data in files, e.g. the Authentication Server stores
the authentication database in files.

<h5>
Device Control and TCB Protection
</h5>

Device control is also used by the TCB to protect its own code and data.
There is a special disk partition for the system bootstrap process.
This boot partition contains both the executable code for the trusted
server software that is started at bootstrap time, and also the
initialization data that specifies details of server startup.
As with other TCB-critical devices, access to the device
(via the device control port)
is only given to the appropriate TCB task--- in this case the
initialization task--- which does not pass access to untrusted tasks.

<h5>
Access Control and TCB Protection
</h5>

In addition to the TCB code and data that is stored on the boot
partition, storage of other TCB code and data uses named security-objects.
Thus, these objects are potentially accessible to untrusted tasks.
However, such access is prevented through the use of the access
control list (ACL) of each name space item of such security-objects.
At system-build time when the name space is initialized, these
items are created, and the ACLs are set to prevent non-TCB access.
The ACL entries are set only for user IDs in a set of reserved
administrative user IDs, e.g. the user IDs for specific trusted
servers.
These user IDs are never used in the creation of subjects, so
untrusted code cannot access TCB security objects.
Furthermore, the ACLs are initialized such that the ACLs can
only be changed by tasks with a reserved user ID.

There are two categories of TCB security-objects: files,
and administrative control items.
Files are used to contain the following: authentication data,
audit logs, and executables of trusted software that may need
to be started after bootstrap (e.g. the TSH and administrative
utilities).
Administrative control items are items in the name space
which represent administrative access to trusted servers.
A successful open of such an item results in a port right which
can be used to send messages to a server which instruct it
to perform administrative actions, e.g. shutdown.

<h5>
Task Separation
</h5>

The kernel's task separation is also a critical mechanism used to
support access control.
Not all security-critical data is stored on devices.
Some is stored in the memory of trusted server tasks.
For example, trusted item managers maintain a mapping between
each item descriptor port and the subject which was granted
access via that port.
This data, used in the item manager's access control enforcement check,
is stored in memory.
Also, other trusted tasks may cache in memory some security-critical
data that is permanently stored on a device.

Therefore, the integrity of a trusted task's memory is critical
to its correct functioning and hence to the security of the system.
The kernel's task separation functionality ensures this integrity.
In addition, each trusted task is careful to not share access to
in-memory security-critical data, for example by shared memory
or external paging.
As a result, the integrity of in-memory TCB data in ensured.

The server TCB also relies in a similar way on the kernel's port mechanism,
namely that tasks can only gain access to another task's port if
that other task specifically grants it.
In other words, a task's port space is protected in a manner analogous
to a task's address space.
Given the central nature of ports in Mach, this aspect of task isolation
is just as critical.
In addition, each trusted task is careful not to share ports with
untrusted tasks, except as authorized by the RNS (e.g. sharing
item descriptor ports).<P>
<P>

<a href="/docs/research/distributed/refmon.html">
<IMG width=60 height=24
SRC="/docs/images/next.gif" border=0
ALT="next"> Reference Monitor</a>


