<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Triad Philosophy of Protection - Kernel Mechanisms</TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222"
ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28
SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS
Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<a href="/docs/research/network/index.html">
<IMG width=191 height=15
SRC="/docs/images/dissys.gif" border=0
ALT="Distributed Systems Security"></a>
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<FONT SIZE=6>Philosophy of Protection for Triad</FONT><P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<a name="Skernmech">
<h2>
Kernel Mechanisms
</h2>

Triad is based on the Mach MK7.0 microkernel from OSF.  Unlike traditional operating
system kernels, the Mach microkernel provides very few services of its own,
hence the  name ``microkernel.'' Kernel services are limited to task and thread
management, IPC, physical devices, and virtual memory management.  The
rest of traditional operation system functionality, such as the file
system, is provided by trusted servers residing outside the kernel.
The trusted servers virtualize the kernel objects (e.g., disk
partitions) and offer to their clients services for virtualized
objects (e.g., files).  The kernel provides the primitive services;
the servers use them to construct system-level abstractions of
subjects and security-objects, and system-level functionality
including access control.
<p>

The following sections describe in more detail these building blocks
and the various areas of kernel service, divided according to the
system's use of these services in implementing subjects,
security-objects, and access controls.
None of these kernel abstractions is by itself a Triad subject or
security-object, but each is used by some part of the server TCB
to implement the subject or one kind of security-object.
<p>

<a name="Sthreadtask">
<h4>
Threads and Tasks
</h4>

The kernel notions of tasks and threads are the basic abstractions for
execution environment and control.
Although tasks and threads are not subjects in and of themselves,
the Triad abstraction of subject is implemented by the server TCB
using these kernel abstractions.
<p>

The thread is the basic unit of execution control.  Each thread is a
logical processing unit able to execute instructions independently.
Threads are the only active entities in a system.  A thread's only
attributes are those comprising its execution state, e.g., stack,
register set, program counter, and scheduling and accounting attributes.
<p>

The task is the basic unit of resource allocation and access control.
A task provides an execution environment in which one or more threads
run.  Each task has a distinct, isolated virtual memory address space.
%that is separate from that of other tasks.
All threads within a task share access to all resources available to
the task.  This includes the task's virtual address space and
capabilities.  Consequently, the security attributes of a thread are
those of the task containing the thread.  When a task is created, it
is assigned an immutable, kernel-maintained attribute called a <em>
security ID</em>.  The security ID is used to contain such task-specific
attributes as mandatory security label, discretionary user
identities, and integrity attributes.
<p>

<h5>
Task Creation
</h5>

The task creation mechanism has three separate aspects.  The first
aspect is the actual kernel interface for task creation.  Any task can
create a child task which inherits the security ID of the parent task.
The kernel provides a separate, privileged interface for creation of a
task with a different security attribute than the creating task.  In
Triad, this kernel privilege is held only by TCB components;
no non-TCB task can create a task with a different security attribute.
<p>

The second aspect of task creation is memory inheritance.  Part of the
state of each task is information that notes which part of the task's
virtual address space is to be inherited by the child.  This state can
be changed by a task.  For each sharable region
of the parents' virtual address space, the child task's virtual
address space is initialized to contain a region that maps to the same
physical memory as does the corresponding region of the parent's
virtual address space.
<p>

The third aspect of task creation concerns the task-self port of the
child task which is returned to the parent task as the result of a
successful task creation.  Task-self ports (described below) can be
used by the parent to set up the child task for execution.  Using the
child's task-self port, the parent can perform a variety of operations
on the child task including: passing on to the child task any ports
and memory-objects (both described below) held by the parent; and
creating and manipulating threads.
A freshly-created task has no threads; it is the parent task's job to
create a thread or threads in the child task, and to set a thread or
threads to begin executing some code in the child task.  If needed
code isn't part of the child's inherited memory, then the parent must
use the task-self port to set up the child task's virtual address
space to contain the needed code.
<p>

<h5>
Task Creation and Security
</h5>

The immutable association of the task to a security ID is the
fundamental security mechanism that is implemented by the kernel.
Trusted server software constructs subjects from tasks (and the
threads running in tasks) and uses the security ID to determine the
security attributes of the subject.
<p>

<h5>
Task Separation and Security
</h5>

The other critical subject-related kernel functionality is task
separation.  Each task has a distinct virtual address space,
separate from other tasks.  As a result, tasks cannot freely access or
manipulate the code or data of other tasks.
<p>

The same is true of each task's ports (described below).  Tasks
reference ports via descriptors that are specific to each task and
which the kernel maps to true port descriptors in a manner analogous
to virtual memory mapping.  Therefore, a task can use only those ports
it has a right to, and can't freely use ports used by other tasks.
<p>

These kinds of task separation are analogous to the TCSEC notion of
process isolation, which is of fundamental importance to the security
of any system.  The only difference is that Mach tasks can have
multiple threads of execution, unlike the TCSEC notion of a
single-threaded process.  Task separation is critical for Triad not
only to maintain meaningful distinctions between subjects, but also
for the integrity of the TCB itself.
<p>


<h5>
Thread Scheduling
</h5>

The scheduler is the component of the kernel that manages the
execution of threads, choosing which threads to run on a processor.  A
critical real-time feature of the Triad scheduler is the replaceable
scheduling framework, which separates the mechanisms of scheduling
from the implementation of the algorithm which selects threads to run.
This separation makes it possible for system developers to replace the
scheduling algorithm.
Such replaceability is critical for the development of real-time systems
because different real-time systems have different scheduling requirements.
As a result of the framework, it is possible to replace schedulers with
minimal impact on the functionality and assurance of the rest of kernel.
<p>

In Triad the replaceable scheduling framework is used to add a
real-time scheduler called the Best Effort Scheduler.  This addition
to the kernel also necessitates the addition of new attributes to the
kernel's thread abstraction: in addition to the existing scheduling
attribute of priority, there are new real-time-oriented thread
scheduling attributes, such as deadlines.
<p>

The Best Effort Scheduler itself doesn't affect the nature of
threads-- it only affects the order in which threads are scheduled to
execute-- but the new attributes are an extension to the existing
thread mechanism.  However, the extension is minor in the sense that
threads already have several attributes, including scheduling
attributes, and the new attributes are accessed in exactly the same
way as existing thread attributes.
<p>


<h5>
Scheduling and Security
</h5>

A security-related benefit of the replaceable scheduling framework is
that a Triad system could use a scheduler which takes covert channel
threats into account when choosing which threads to schedule.
Research on security and Best Effort scheduling
<a href="refs.html#MLSBEsched">[MLSBEsched]</a>
shows the promise of development of such a scheduler.  Although the
Triad prototype effort does not include further research into
scheduling and covert channel management, the replaceable scheduling
framework used by Triad makes it possible for future Triad systems to
incorporate future scheduler implementations which address these
issues.  The current Triad prototype is targeted for embedded or
dedicated systems with minimal covert channel threats, but other
Triad systems that do have significant threats could counter these
threats using such a scheduler, and do so in a way that has no further
effect on the structure or assurance of the Triad system.
<p>

<HR>

<a name="Sports">
<h4>
Ports
</h4>

The kernel's basic inter-process communications (IPC) service allows
tasks to send messages to one another via kernel abstractions called
<em>
ports.  
</em>
Each port behaves like a queue of messages to which
several tasks can potentially append messages, and from which one task can
retrieve messages.  Each port has associated with it a set of 
<em>
port-rights
</em>
which allow tasks to use the port.  Port rights can be
transferred among tasks using the IPC mechanism itself: in addition to
message data, an IPC message
can also contain port rights which are held by the message sender and
which are to be transferred to the message receiver.

<h5>
Port Rights
</h5>

Mach defines four kinds of port-rights for each port.
There is exactly one
<em>
receive right
</em>
for each port, which allows
the holder to retrieve messages from the port.  Since every port right
is held by exactly one task, only one task at a time can receive messages.
There are potentially many
<em>
send rights
</em>
for each port.
Each send right allows the task which holds the right to send a message on the
port.
Therefore, there may be several different tasks with the ability to send a
message to the port's receiver.
More send rights for a port can be created by the holder of the receive
right for that port, or any of the holders of send rights for it.
A 
</em>
send-once right
</em>
is like a send right except that the holder can
only use it once and cannot use it to create any further rights for the port.
Finally, a task holding a receive right to a port can also obtain a
<em>
port-set
</em>
right.
A task may bundle together a number of receive rights that it holds,
thus creating a port set.
All of the ports that were bundled together then have one port-set right.
As a result, the task can use this port-set port-right to receive a message 
from any one of the ports in the port set.
<p>

The kernel maintains all port rights so that there is no way a task
can have a port right without the kernel's knowledge.  Each task has
its own name space of port rights.  For each task, the kernel
maintains a distinct mapping from the task's port names to an actual
port.  Every time a task uses a port, the port is referred to by name
and the kernel uses the mapping to determine which port is being used.
The kernel updates a task's port name space whenever the task receives
a new port right.  Tasks can obtain port rights in two ways: creating
a port, or receiving a transferred port right.  Port rights are
transferred by inclusion in an IPC message.
<p>

As a result of this port mapping, a task cannot even name a port
unless it holds a valid port right to it.
Because the kernel controls all transfers of rights,
a port can be thought of as a set of kernel-protected
port-rights for a queue of IPC messages.
<p>

<h5>
Task-Self Ports
</h5>

Task-self ports provide another way for tasks to communicate with each
other.  The kernel creates a unique task-self port for every task as
part of task creation.  The kernel keeps its receive right and gives
the send rights to the parent task, which in turn can transfer it to the
child task or any other task with which it can communicate.
Once a task transfers a send right to
its task-self port, it establishes an agent/target relationship,
where the task is the target and the recipient of the send right
becomes the target's agent.  An agent task can invoke any indirect
kernel calls
<a href="footnotes.html#Indirect">[2]</a>
on behalf of its target task, and the kernel performs the request as if
it had been made by the target task. 
Since a task operates on itself by sending a message on its own
task-self port, an agent task has as much control over a
target task as the target has over itself.
<p>

As part of the security policy, no TCB task ever transfers its task-self port.
<p>

<h5>
Ports and Security: Message Tagging
</h5>

The kernel both implements ports with the rules on
transference and use of port rights, and also connects this
communication mechanism to the fundamental security mechanism of the
security ID.  This connection is message tagging.  The kernel tags
each message with the security ID of the task that sent it.  The
receiver of the message thus has an unforgeable indication of the
identity of sender, including all security-relevant information about
the sender.  In cases where the receiver embodies the reference
validation mechanism, the information is used in the computation of
access checks.
<p>

The kernel implements the basic IPC and security mechanisms and leaves
to trusted servers the task of using the security ID to enforce the
security policy.
The Triad TCB enforces the security policy
in several ways, including mediating access requests
and ensuring that tasks can only communicate with one another
if they have the same mandatory security level.
<p>

<h5>
Ports and RPC: Scheduling Coherence
</h5>

An additional feature of Mach IPC, oriented to real-time issues, is
the Remote Procedure Call (RPC) mechanism.  The RPC mechanism is used
to avoid undesirable real-time effects of using the asynchronous IPC
mechanism which, in a client-server system such as Triad, has a
synchronous usage pattern and a semantics resembling that of a
procedure call.
<p>

When using asynchronous IPC a message is passed
from one task/thread
<a href="footnotes.html#Term">[3]</a>
to another, but the sender may continue processing and only later
check for a reply---in other words, the sender has an asynchronous
usage pattern.  However, more commonly in client-server interactions,
the sender blocks until the reply returns.  For such
synchronous usage of message-based IPC, the block results in an
undesirable full context switch to another task/thread.  Although
ideally the switch is to the recipient of the message, it cannot be
guaranteed that the the receiver is the next entity to execute.
Eventually however, the receiving task/thread will execute, receive
and process the message and return a reply, including another full
context switch that allows the sender to continue.
<p>

In addition to the undesirable context switching, the use of
message-based IPC also fails to preserve real-time scheduling coherence;
that is, there is no guarantee that the receiving thread will have
the same scheduling attributes as the sending thread.
Therefore, a client's request may be handled by a server thread
which has different scheduling attributes from the client thread
and which may as a result not get scheduled in time to meet a
client deadline.
<p>

Therefore, in addition to the asynchronous message-based Mach IPC,
Triad also uses the kernel IPC service of RPC.  Mach RPC is based on a
new internal kernel implementation concept, the
<em>
shuttle.
</em>
A shuttle is
the schedulable resource of a thread. Mach RPC re-uses the shuttle
of the sender to execute the receiver, which has the very desirable
effect that the receiver executes with the same scheduling attributes
as the sender.  In this way shuttle-based RPC reduces context switching
overhead to provide synchronous message passing behavior with coherent
thread scheduling across task boundaries.
<p>

Shuttles, however, are only an implementation concept and are not
visible outside of the kernel.  Indeed, the kernel's IPC and thread
interface is the same for RPC, except for the addition of two
interfaces: one to make an RPC, and one to create a thread that is
capable of receiving an RPC.  There is no other change to the kernel's
task and thread abstraction, to the existing kernel interfaces, or to
the security features of IPC.
<p>


<a name="Sdipc">
<h5>
Distributed IPC
</h5>

As a distributed system Triad requires IPC mechanisms that permit
communication between tasks running on different hosts.  Rather than
embedding distribution functionality into the Mach kernel, which is
otherwise solely concerned with the execution of one host,
distributed IPC is implemented in a trusted server which transparently
connects IPC services between hosts.  Just as each host has a kernel
that provides local IPC, so also each host has a distributed IPC
server that works with the local kernel and with distributed IPC
servers on other hosts, to provide distributed IPC.
<p>
<center>
<img height=492 width=468 src="ps/dipc.gif" border=0 alt="dIPC">
<br>
Figure 1: Client/Server Distributed IPC
</center>
<p>

In the Triad system clients use IPC to request services of servers,
and servers use IPC to provide the requested services.
In order to initiate requests, the clients use a send-right to a port
which is received by the server
<a href="footnotes.html#Details">[4]</a>.
When the client and server are on different hosts, the 
distributed IPC server is involved as an intermediary.
As shown in Figure 1, the distributed IPC server uses local
IPC to receive locally sent messages destined for other hosts.
The distributed IPC server is the receiver for all local ports
for which the true intended receiver (e.g. a remote server)
is on another host.
For each message the distributed IPC server receives on such ports,
the message data is transmitted to the destination host's distributed
IPC server using network protocols.
Once the message data arrives, the receiving distributed IPC server
uses local IPC to send the message to the destination task.
As a result, distributed senders and receivers need not be aware of
the intermediary role of distributed IPC servers.
<p>

The key security-relevant role of the distributed IPC server is the
propagation of the security ID of the sender of the message.
There is a kernel privilege which allows the holder of the privilege
to specify the security ID to tag on the message.
Normally, the kernel uses the security ID of the sending task, but using
a privileged interface the sending task can specify another security ID.
The distributed IPC server is the sole holder of this privilege on every
Triad host, and it uses the privilege to make messages arrive with the
correct security ID tag of the actual sending task on the remote host.
As shown in Figure 1, the distributed IPC server notes the
security ID of the original sender, transmits it over the network
with the message data, and uses a privileged kernel interface
to tag the final message with the security ID.
<p>

The distributed IPC server also supports the scheduling coherence
feature of the RPC form of IPC by propagating and using the
sending thread's scheduling attributes in a similar manner to
the propagation of security IDs.
The main difference is that no privilege is needed to use the
scheduling attributes.
When processing an RPC received from another host, the distributed IPC
server simply uses normal kernel interfaces to take the sender's scheduling
attributes and set them as the attributes of the thread which executes
the RPC locally.
<p>

<HR>

<a name="Skdev}">
<h4>
Devices
</h4>

A device is a kernel abstraction of a physical device, which the
kernel represents with a port.  Although devices are not
security-objects in and of themselves, various kinds of named
security-objects are implemented by the Triad TCB using the kernel's
device services.
<p>

The kernel provides tasks with access to each physical device via use
of the device's control port; the kernel holds the receive right to
all of these ports.  To obtain send rights to a device control port a
task must use the master device port.  After bootstrap the kernel
creates the init task, which is responsible for starting the trusted
tasks that comprise the rest of the Triad TCB.  The kernel passes to
the init task a send right to the master device port.  The init task
is responsible for correctly using the master device port or passing
it to another task or tasks that use it.  Thus, the bulk of control
over devices resides not with the kernel but with the tasks which
hold the master device port.
<p>

In Triad, control over the master device port is retained by the
TCB Device Server.
The Device Server uses the master device port to obtain send rights to
the individual device control ports.
Other tasks can request a send right to a device control port,
and the Device Server services these requests in conjunction
with policies specific to the particular devices.
In most cases only specific TCB tasks can get a device control port.
Hence, uses of most devices is restricted to the TCB, which uses them
as primitive resources needed to implement the security-objects
of the system (described in the section on
    <a href="serv.html#Sservers">Trusted Server Mechanisms</a>.)
The File Server, for example, uses a disk device for storage of
the file system data that is needed to implement its file service.
More details on Triad use of devices is given in the section on
<a href="serv.html#Ssdev">Device Objects</a>.)
<p>

<HR>

<a name="Smemobj">
<h4>
Memory-Objects
</h4>

The Mach kernel allows user tasks to provide the semantics associated
with the act of referencing portions of a virtual address space.  It
does this by enabling the specification of an abstract
<em>
memory-object
</em>
that represents the non-resident state of the memory ranges backed by
this memory object.  A TCB task that implements memory-objects, 
responding to messages sent to the ports naming those objects,
is called an
<em>
external memory manager.
</em>
Although memory-objects are not security-objects in and of
themselves, memory-objects are used by the server TCB to implement the
named security-objects that are memory-mapped files.  In addition,
memory-objects may also be used as part of the kernel resources that
comprise unnamed security-objects which are used by subjects for
memory sharing.
<p>

The external memory manager shares the management of virtual memory
with the kernel.  The memory manager is responsible for the initial
contents and permanent storage of the object; the kernel is
responsible for mapping memory objects into tasks' virtual address
spaces and handling page faults. 
<p>

<h5>
Out-of-line Data
</h5>

The Triad Kernel enforces a maximum size on messages a task can send to another
task, thereby allowing their receivers to pre-allocate adequately large
buffers to receive them.
To accommodate transmission of larger messages, the Triad Kernel allows
tasks to pass pointers to data items in a message.
When a message contains such a pointer, it is considered to
contain
</em>
out-of-line
</em>
(OOL) data.
When the a task receives a message with OOL data, the kernel allocates
space in the receiver's virtual address space for the OOL data and leaves
the pointer to the newly allocated region in the message body.

<h5>
Memory Access Summary
</h5>

In summary, the following are the four ways a task can access a memory object:
<menu>
<li>
directly, by being the manager for it.
<li>
directly, by inheriting memory from a parent task with access to it
      (see the section on
      <a href="kern.html#Sthreadtask">Threads and Tasks</a>.)
<li>
directly, by having it mapped into the task's virtual address space.
<li>
indirectly, by receiving a message containing out-of-line data that
      references it.
</menu>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
