<!-- Main Body -->
<P>

<Font size= 6>Philosophy of Protection for Triad</font>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<a name="Srefmon">
<h2>
Reference Monitor
</h2>

The TCSEC requires that B3-level systems implement the reference monitor
concept, an abstract access mediator and enforcer
that controls the flow of information between subject and objects
in a computer system.
<em>
Reference Validation Mechanism
</em>
(RVM) is the term given to an implementation of the reference monitor concept
that mediates and enforces a specified security policy.
An RVM must be shown to be tamper-resistant, unbypassable, and correctly
implemented.
In Triad, the RNS performs mediation and enforces the Triad Security
Policy.  Because it performs all access mediation, the RNS is the Triad RVM.

<p>
We have described the hardware and machine-dependent protection mechanisms that
are at the foundation of the Triad TCB.  Below we describe how:
<menu>
<li>
the RVM is tamperproof as a result of hardware-based separation
    of the RVM from untrusted code;
<li>
the RVM is unbypassable as a result of running only the TCB
    in the most privileged state needed for access to hardware resources
    and services; and how
<li>
meeting stringent B3-level requirements contributes to the high
    degree of assurance in the correctness of the implementation.
</menu>

<h4>
Tamperproof
</h4>

Process isolation satisfies the requirement that an RVM be tamperproof.
In Triad, the kernel uses hardware mechanisms to isolate the RNS from all
other tasks.
Process isolation is implemented by the kernel's hardware memory-mapping
mechanisms.
In turn, the kernel must also be tamperproof.
Therefore, it is also isolated by means of its privileged execution mode.
This hardware-enforced mechanism provides the kernel sole control of
physical memory.


<h4>
Unbypassable
</h4>

Because only TCB software runs in the most privileged hardware state, it
has sole access to hardware resources and services.
However, the RNS is the TCB component that mediates access, and the RNS
runs not in the kernel's privileged hardware state, but in a task.
Therefore, the kernel's unbypassability must be complemented by
unbypassability of the RNS.
That is, subjects may obtain access
to resources only after appropriate mediation by the RNS.
Each Triad subject has a well-defined initial set of resources and
available services, and this initial state ensures that additional resources
may only be obtained after RNS mediation.

<p>
Specifically, untrusted tasks initially have only two capabilities:
communication with the kernel via the hardware trap mechanism;
and use of the kernel port mechanism to communicate with the RNS.
Therefore, untrusted tasks initially can contact no other task than
the RNS.
Subsequently, untrusted tasks obtain resources only after RNS mediation.
These resources are provided in the form of security-objects, either
named or unnamed.
Named security-objects are implemented by trusted servers which enforce
RNS mediation decisions so that access to an object is provided only
after RNS mediation.
Unnamed security-objects are implemented by RNS, and kernel mechanisms
are sufficient for enforcing mediation.
Therefore, even though the RNS permits communication between
untrusted tasks and trusted servers, the trusted servers
do not allow the RNS to be bypassed.

<p>
Because Triad's TCB consists of a kernel plus trusted server tasks,
it is also necessary to demonstrate that untrusted tasks cannot
use their direct access to kernel services to bypass the RNS.
This demonstration corresponds to the five services of the kernel.
An untrusted task can manipulate its threads, or create new ones,
but these are part of the state of the subject, rather than being
part of any resources mediated by the RNS.
An untrusted task can manipulate itself or create child tasks
with the same security ID.
However, doing so only increases the kernel resources of the
subject (the group of tasks with the same security ID) that
the TCB already created.
Again, there is no access to any resources mediated by the RNS.
An untrusted task can manipulate its ports and memory-objects
or create new ones.
However, doing so only increases the kernel resources
of the subject, or of the subject's ipc-object,
access to which has already been mediated by the RNS.
The fifth and final kernel service is devices, but the direct access to
devices is controlled by the kernel privilege of the Master Device Port.
In Triad, subjects do not have this privilege and hence cannot 
obtain device access from the kernel (see the section on
    <a href="kern.html#Skdev">Devices</a>).

<p>
Because of Triad's kernel/server structure, it is also
necessary to demonstrate why the RVM is unspoofable.
The issue is that an untrusted task might try to obtain system resources by
masquerading as trusted server, thereby bypassing access mediation.
In order to prevent this, trusted servers must correctly identify one another.
The security ID is the protection mechanism that precludes such spoofing.
By correctly maintaining the security ID of tasks, and by tagging each
message with the security ID of the sending task, the kernel provides
the means for trusted servers to authenticate one another's security ID.
Trusted tasks have a distinguished security ID that is never assigned
to an untrusted task.
The TCB assigns security IDs to trusted tasks during subject creation
    (see the section on <a href="serv.html#Sserversubject">Subjects</a>),
and the kernel maintains the security ID of tasks.
As a result, untrusted tasks cannot run with the security ID of a
trusted server, and hence cannot masquerade as one.

<h4>
Correct
</h4>

Correctness of implementation has never been absolutely proven for any system.
The TCSEC requires various degrees and types of assurance as 
evidence of attention to correctness issues throughout the development cycle.
The demonstration of correctness should form a logical chain, such that:

<menu>
<li>
The model adequately addresses the protection needs,
<li>
The policy satisfies the model axioms,
<li>
The design embodies the policy, and
<li>
The system implements the design.
</menu>

For B3 systems, a Formal Security Policy Model is required. The section on
<a href="verif.html">Verification Plan</a>
shows how the Triad FSPM corresponds to the system design.

<p>
In addition to following the above logical chain, the implementation must
meet rigorous B3-level architectural requirements for modularity and layering.  
TMach's micro-kernel based, client/server architecture satisfies
these requirements.  In general, Triad is structured in a way that
facilitates independent analysis.

<p>
The Triad TCB is strictly layered according to the layering principle
required for a system of B3 class and F-B3 class of TCSEC and ITSEC
respectively.
In addition, TCB software is further structured to according to the
modularity  principles for B3.
In order to meet these principles, the Triad system is an
object-oriented, message-based operating system with a
small, extensible kernel and a small set of trusted servers.
The Triad system uses a client/server paradigm where subject tasks,
known as
<em>
clients
</em>
use obtain operating system services provided
by other tasks, known as 
<em>
servers.
</em>
This paradigm is also object-oriented, since each server provides services
related to some abstract object
<a href="footnotes.html#Abstract">[10]</a>.
Modularity is enhanced through the strict modular structuring
of the implementation that results from the use of the object-oriented
implementation techniques that naturally fit with the object-oriented
nature of the system.

<p>
The layers of the Triad system can be conceptually grouped into two
abstract layers:
the bottom layer consisting of the kernel, and the higher layer
consisting of all other trusted servers.
The kernel layer provides the primitive abstractions and
resources essential for building a trusted operating system.
The kernel deviates from the usual operating system kernels in
that it provides only a minimal set of essential abstractions.
Its goal is to provide essential abstractions so that servers residing
outside the kernel can provide the traditional operating system functionality.
The server layer uses the kernel services to provide personality-neutral
functionality of a trusted operating system, including services such
as mediation and enforcement of access control, identification and
authentication of users, audit, and trusted administration.
The kernel's role is minimized to providing the most basic security
mechanisms and enforcing mediated access on its objects.
 
<p>
Of the services that manipulate kernel abstractions, most deal
with thread and task management, virtual memory management, and IPC.
These services are not privileged and are available to all non-TCB tasks.
There are also a few privileged kernel calls which allow callers to
access protected system resources (as described in the section on
    <a href="priv.html">Privilege</a>).
Possession of privileges, and hence the ability to make privileged
kernel calls, is limited to the trusted servers.

<p>
In addition to the kernel/server layering, the server layer is
further divided into several server layers, some of which are
structured into separate server tasks.
Within the kernel and each server task, the implementation 
has an object-oriented modular structure.<P>
<P>

<a href="/docs/research/distributed/priv.html">
<IMG width=60 height=24
SRC="/docs/images/next.gif" border=0
ALT="next"> Privilege</a>


<hr>
<H3>More Triad Information</h3><P>
