<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Triad Philosophy of Protection - Verification Plan</TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222"
ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28
SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS
Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<a href="/docs/research/network/index.html">
<IMG width=191 height=15
SRC="/docs/images/dissys.gif" border=0
ALT="Distributed Systems Security"></a>
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<P>

<Font size= 6>Philosophy of Protection for Triad</font>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>
Verification Plan
</h2>
 
Triad is targeted at TCSEC level B3 and hence, is not required
to provide formal verification of its design.
However, Triad's Formal Security Policy Model
<a href="refs.html#FSPM">[FSPM]</a>
presents a formal specification of Triad's security policy.
This is shown to be an interpretation of the Bell-La Padula model.
Although the specification is not formally verified, the Bell-La Padula
model's proofs of sufficiency are applicable to Triad.
The Triad FSPM includes tables that indicate the specific correspondences
between the BLP model and the Triad model.
The section on <a href="secpol.html">Policy</a>
presents the mapping between
the FSPM and a detailed specification of the TCB's interface.
<P>
<P>

