<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Triad Philosophy of Protection - Privilege
</TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222"
ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28
SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS
Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<a href="/docs/research/network/index.html">
<IMG width=191 height=15
SRC="/docs/images/dissys.gif" border=0
ALT="Distributed Systems Security"></a>
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<P>
<Font size= 6>Philosophy of Protection for Triad</font>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>
Privilege
</h2>

In general, privileges are means by which trusted software
may operate outside one or more of the operational restrictions
of a system's TCB.
Therefore, there must be clear descriptions of a system's privileges, and
of the modes of privilege use and acquisition.
In Triad, some trusted servers require kernel privileges in order to
implement their parts of the TCB's protection mechanisms.
That is, some kernel operations are limited to tasks which
hold a privilege.
In Triad, this privilege mechanism is used to ensure that only
trusted tasks can perform the privileged operations, which
are central to the enforcement of the security policy.

<p>
There are four such kernel privileges,
which are implemented as ports for which the kernel is the receiver.
Thus, the kernel controls the acquisition of privilege, because
of its implementation of ports, rights, and transfers of rights.
The privileges themselves are used by Triad trusted servers in
the following manner: when a server makes a privileged kernel
interface call, the server includes in the call a port right
for the privilege port.
For each such privileged interface call, the kernel checks for
the inclusion of such a port right, and verifies that the
right is for the port representing th required privilege.
Thus, the kernel also uses the port mechanism to validate
whether the calling task has the required privilege.

<p>
The four privileges provided by the kernel are:
<p>
<em>
Master Device Port:
</em>
Any task that has access to this port can open physical devices.
In the Triad system, only the Device Server has access to this port
and manages all access to physical devices.
The section on <a href="kern.html#Skdev">Devices</a>
describes the Device Server's use of the master device port.
<p>
<em>
Message Security Port:
</em>
Any task that has access to this port can perform IPC which
the kernel will tag with a security ID specified by the task,
usually a different security ID than that of task.
In the Triad system, only the Distributed IPC Server is given this privilege.
The section on
<a href="kern.html#Sdipc">Distributed IPC</a>
describes the Distributed IPC Server's use of the message security port.
<p>
<em>
Host Security Port:
</em>
Any task that has access to this port can create 
tasks with a different security attributes than itself.
In the Triad system, only the Subject Server is given this privilege.
The section on <a href="serv.html#Sserversubject">Subjects</a>
describes the Subject Server's use of the host security port.
<p>
<em>
Host Control Port:
</em>
Any task that has access to this port can manipulate host process control
data structures such as the system clock or default memory manager.
In the Triad system, only the Host Control Server is given access
to this port.  
<a href="refs.html#HCS">[HCS]</a>
describes the Host Control Server's use of the host security port.

<p>
In Triad, the use of these kernel privileges is restricted to the
above-mentioned trusted servers.
During system initialization, the appropriate privilege port
is transferred to the appropriate trusted server task.
Trusted servers never transfer these privilege port rights to any other task.
Because set of privileges is small and because the acquisition of
these privileges is tightly controlled, there can be assurance of
appropriate use of special privileges within the Triad TCB.

<p>
These four kernel privileges are the only privileges in Triad.
The Triad TCB itself does not export any privileges that permit
Triad subjects to operate outside of Triad's security policy.
<P>
<P>

<a href="/docs/research/distributed/tsubj.html">
<IMG width=60 height=24
SRC="/docs/images/next.gif" border=0
ALT="next"> Trusted Subjects</a>


