<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Triad Philosophy of Protection - Security Policy</TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222"
ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28
SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS
Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<a href="/docs/research/network/index.html">
<IMG width=191 height=15
SRC="/docs/images/dissys.gif" border=0
ALT="Distributed Systems Security"></a>
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<FONT SIZE=6>Philosophy of Protection for Triad</FONT>
<blockquote>
<a name="Spol">
<h2>
Security Policy and Access Controls
</h2>

The Triad system enforces a security policy that is somewhat stricter
than the traditional confidentiality-based access control policy modeled
by the Bell-LaPadula Model
<a href="refs.html#BLP">[BLP]</a>
Access to named objects is constrained by mandatory and discretionary
confidentiality axioms and also by the integrity constraints of
Triad's mandatory integrity policy.
Access to unnamed objects is constrained only by mandatory confidentiality.
<p>

In the Triad system, a subject can access the contents of a named object
only if the subject's request for access successfully passes mediation by
the TCB.
The TCB compares the object's security level against the subject's level,
checks whether the user associated with the subject has the appropriate
discretionary permission to access the object, and
compares the subject's integrity attributes with those of the object.
Only if all three checks are successful is a subject allowed to
access the contents of an object.
<p>

Subjects are allowed to create named objects provided that
the subject satisfies both the mandatory and discretionary
access mediations.  
<p>

Subjects are allowed to create and access unnamed objects if
the subject satisfies the mandatory access mediation.  
<p>

The policy presented in the Formal Security Policy Model
<a href="refs.html#FSPM">[FSPM]</a>
consists of the following assertions:

<menu>
<li>
For a subject to gain read access to a named object, the
subject's level must dominate the object's security level and
the subject must have discretionary permission to read the object.
<li>
For a subject to gain write access to a named object, the
subject's security level must be the same as the object's level and
the subject must have discretionary permission to write the object.
<li>
For a subject to gain append access to a named object, the
object's security level must dominate the subject's security level and
the subject must have discretionary permission to append to the object.
<li>
For a subject to write or append access to a named object, the
subject's usefulness must be such that the access does not diminish
the object's usefulness.
<li>
For a subject to modify the ACL of a named object, the
subject must have discretionary permission to control the object.
<li>
A subject can create a named object provided the security level
of the object dominates the security level of the subject and
the subject has discretionary permission to create the object.
<li>
A subject can destroy a named object provided the object's
security level dominates the subject's security level and
the subject has discretionary permission to control the object.
<li>
For a subject to gain access to an ipc-object, the
security level of the accessing subject must be the same as
the security level of the ipc-object, which is the security level
of the associated subject.
(The single access mode to ipc-objects permits accessors to read,
write and append to the object, and to destroy the object.
Ipc-objects are implicitly created when subjects are created, and
implicitly destroyed when subjects are destroyed.)
<li>
The security level and integrity of subjects and objects is constant.
</menu>

Triad's access controls hinge on access mediation, which is performed
solely by the RNS.
Enforcement of access mediation is performed by the trusted item managers
(as described in the section on
    <a href="subjobj.html#Snamedobj">Security Objects and Subjects</a>)
and supported by the kernel (as described in the section on
    <a href="subjobj.html#Sunnamed">Unnamed Objects</a>).
<p>

The RNS's mediation is performed each time a subject attempts to create,
open, or destroy an item.
The RNS performs the requisite access control checks for the
security-object that corresponds to the name of the item.
Thus, each policy assertion can be mapped to an interface of the RNS,
where the RNS performs mediation that implements the assertion.
There are three kinds of RNS interfaces involved in this mapping.
<p>

Firstly, the
<em>
ns_resolve
</em>
interface is used to gain access to an item.
Therefore all the access assertions map to 
<em>
ns_resolve.
</em>
However,
<em>
ns_resolve
</em>
also applies to the assertion
for creation of named items, because in order to create an item,
one must first access the directory item in which the object is 
to be created.
Likewise,
<em>
ns_resolve
</em>
also applies to the assertion
for destruction of named items, because in order to destroy an
item, one must first access the directory item that contains it.
Finally,
<em>
ns_resolve
</em>
also applies to ACL modification because
one must resolve the directory containing the object to be modified.
<p>

The second class of RNS interfaces are those for item creation:
<em>
ns_create_secure,
ns_create_type_secure,
</em>
and
<em>
ns_create_symlink_secure.
</em>
(Types and symbolic links are created with separate interfaces
because each requires special parameters not required for other
kinds of object creation.)
These creation interfaces apply to the creation assertion,
as well as the constancy assertion, because creation sets the
attributes that are subsequently constant.
The creation interfaces also apply to the ACL modification assertion,
because an item's ACL is given its initial value when the item is created.
<p>

Thirdly,
<em>
ns_set_protection
</em>
interface in used to change an item's ACL.
This interface does not apply to any other policy assertion.
<p>

The following table summarizes the mapping between the policy assertions
and the system interfaces:
<HR>
<table cellpadding = 0>
<TR> <TD> Assertion        <TD> Resolve <TD> Create  <TD>   Set Protection </TD>
<TR> <TD> Read             <TD> x       <TD>         <TD>   </TD>
<TR> <TD> Write            <TD> x       <TD>         <TD>   </TD>
<TR> <TD> Append           <TD> x       <TD>         <TD>   </TD>
<TR> <TD> Usefulness       <TD> x       <TD>         <TD>   </TD>
<TR> <TD> ACL Modification <TD> x       <TD> x       <TD> x </TD>
<TR> <TD> Creation         <TD> x       <TD> x       <TD>   </TD>
<TR> <TD> Destruction      <TD> x       <TD>         <TD>   </TD>
<TR> <TD> Ipc-object       <TD> x       <TD>         <TD>   </TD>
<TR> <TD> Constancy        <TD>         <TD> x       <TD>   </TD>
</table>
<hr>
<P>
