<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Triad Philosophy of Protection Subjects and Security Objects</TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222"
ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28
SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS
Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<a href="/docs/research/network/index.html">
<IMG width=191 height=15
SRC="/docs/images/dissys.gif" border=0
ALT="Distributed Systems Security"></a>
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>
Security Objects and Subjects
</h2>
<a name="Sobjsubj"> 

This section explains the subjects and security-objects of Triad, starting
with a description of basic concepts and terminology to be used in the
following discussions.
The trusted servers provide the functionality of
implementing subjects and security-objects.
This server functionality is based on the kernel's services.
Therefore, we first describe the kernel's services, and then describe
how the servers use them to construct Triad's subjects and security-objects.

<p>
<a href="basic.html">Basic Concepts and Terminology</a>
<p>
<a href="kern.html">Kernel Mechanisms</a>
<p>
<a href="serv.html">Trusted Server Mechanisms</a>
<p>

<h4>
Summary of Security Objects
</h4>
<a name="Ssosummary">  

The previous sections have presented the security objects of the Triad system.
Security objects include every item that may be referenced by a name in
the RNS's name space.  In addition to named items, there is also one kind of 
unnamed security object: the ipc-object.
All named security objects
are items.  If an item's type is managed by a trusted server, then access
requests to the item are mediated by the RNS and enforced by that trusted
server.  If an item's type is not managed by a trusted server, then access
requests are mediated by the RNS in such a way that
no further enforcement is required.  In
this case, the kind of security-object associated with the item is a connection
point.  <em> Every </em> item of every non-TCB-managed type is
represented by a connection point object.
<p>

The table below summarizes the relationship between kinds of security objects
and types of items.  Note that the column on the right, ``Access Controller,''
always includes the RNS.  In the case of items managed by trusted
servers, the column also includes ``IM'' to denote enforcement of access
mediation decisions by the item manager appropriate for the item's type.
In the case of connection points, no further enforcement beyond the RNS'
mediation is necessary.  In the case of directories, symbolic links, and
typedefs, the RNS is the item manager appropriate for those items' types.

<HR>
<table cellpadding = 0>
<TR> <TD> Kind of Security-Object <TD> Type of Item <TD> Item Manager <TD> Access Controller </TR>
</table>
<HR>
<table cellpadding = 0>
<TR> <TD> Directory        <TD> Directory           <TD> RNS   <TD> RNS </TR>
<TR> <TD> Symbolic Link    <TD> Symbolic Link       <TD> RNS   <TD> RNS </TR>
<TR> <TD> Typedef          <TD> Typedef             <TD> RNS   <TD> RNS </TR>
<TR> <TD> File             <TD> File                <TD> File Server        <TD> RNS & IM </TR>
<TR> <TD> Virtual Terminal <TD> Virtual Terminal    <TD> Virtual Tty Server <TD> RNS & IM </TR>
<TR> <TD> Printer          <TD> Printer             <TD> Printer Server     <TD> RNS & IM </TR>
<TR> <TD> Connection Point <TD> various other types <TD> various untrusted tasks <TD> RNS </TR>
<TR> <TD> Ipc-object       <TD> none                <TD> none                    <TD> RNS </TR>
</table><hr>
<p>
<a href="/docs/research/distributed/secpol.html">
<IMG width=60 height=24
SRC="/docs/images/next.gif" border=0
ALT="next"> Security Policy and Access Controls</a>


