<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Triad Philosophy of Protection - Basic Concepts and Terminology</TITLE>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222"
ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28
SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS
Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<a href="/docs/research/network/index.html">
<IMG width=191 height=15
SRC="/docs/images/dissys.gif" border=0
ALT="Distributed Systems Security"></a>
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<Font Size=6>Triad Philosophy of Protection</FONT> <p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h3>
Basic Concepts and Terminology
</h3>

<em>
User:
</em>
The user is the system abstraction representing an individual
who has been authorized to access the system.  Given Triad's intended
use as a base for dedicated and embedded systems, where the mission is
to perform specific functions in response to events that are not
necessarily human generated, we extended the concept to include
application subsystems as users.
<p>

<em> 
Subject:
</em> 
active entities that execute within the system on
behalf on users.  Each user is authorized to operate within a range of
security levels.  Once a user is properly identified and authenticated
at a level within its range, the user can create subjects to operate
on its behalf at that level.  For human users, login activity is the
means of authentication and subject definition.  For subsystem-based
users, subjects are created automatically by the system using
configuration data which specifies for each subject its corresponding
user and other security attributes.
<p>

<em> 
Security Object:
</em>
The Triad TCB controls all system resources and makes them available
to subjects in the form of security-objects, which can be used
as repositories of information.  The only way a subject can access a
security-object is by making an access request of the TCB, which will
service only those requests satisfying its security mediation.  The
security-objects can be categorized into two groups: several kinds of
<em> named objects </em> used for information storage or communication;
and one kind of <em> unnamed object, </em> the ipc-object, which represents
the state of each subject that is accessible to other subjects.
<p> 

<em>  
Security Levels:
</em> 
For the purposes of Mandatory Access Control (MAC), the Triad system
supports a set of security levels.  The set of security levels forms a
lattice with the traditional <em> dominates </em> predicate denoting the
partial order for the lattice.  Each Triad subject has an attribute
which denotes the level at which it is operating, i.e., the maximum
sensitivity of the information accessible to the subject.  Similarly,
Triad security-objects have a label which denotes the maximum
sensitivity of the information contained in the security-object. Each
security-object and subject is assigned an immutable mandatory
security level at creation.
<p> 

<em>  
ACLs:
</em>  
For the purposes of Discretionary Access Control (DAC),
each named security-object has an associated access control list (ACL)
where the access rights of users to the object are defined.
ACLs are assigned at object creation and may be modified after creation
by subjects with proper discretionary permission.
<p>

<em>  
Integrity Attributes:
</em>  
In addition to the above traditional aspects of access control, Triad
enforces an integrity policy.  Each subject has an integrity
attribute that represents the subject's trustworthiness and
competence.  Each named object also has an integrity attribute that
indicates the object's overall usefulness.
<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-- signature -->


