<IMG width=191 height=15
SRC="/docs/images/dissys.gif" border=0
ALT="Distributed Systems Security"></a>
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<FONT SIZE=6>Philosophy of Protection for Triad</FONT>
<h2>
Scope
</h2>

Trusted Information Systems, Inc. (TIS) and Locus Computing Corporation are
pleased to  present this Philosophy of Protection for the Triad
Operating System.

<h4>
Identification
</h4>

This document, the ``Philosophy of Protection for the Triad System,''
is CDRL A007  of U.S. Government contract number F30602-93-C-0235.

<h4>
System Overview
</h4>

Triad is a prototype multi-level secure, real-time,
distributed operating system.
The purpose of Triad is to provide
processing capabilities for real-time, distributed  military
C3I applications which process information of different
classifications.

<h4>
Document Overview
</h4>

The Philosophy of Protection (PoP) describes the
essential concepts, the security policy, and the protection mechanisms
of the Trusted Computing Base (TCB) of the Triad System.
This description addresses the TCSEC
<a href="refs.html#TCSEC">[TCSEC]</a>
requirement (in section 3.3.4.4) for documentation that:
<menu>
<li>
  ``provides a description of the manufacturer's philosophy of protection
  and an explanation of how this philosophy is translated into the TCB,''
<li>
  identifies the ``specific TCB protection mechanisms,'' and
<li>
  describes ``how the TCB implements the reference monitor concept and ...
  why it is tamperproof, cannot be bypassed and is correctly implemented.''
</menu>
This description first addresses the functionality of the Triad system,
and its security policy.
It then identifies the functionality that is used to implement the
policy-enforcing protection mechanisms, and explains how those
mechanisms are used to meet the reference monitor requirements.
<p>

The outline of the body of the document is:
<menu>
<li>
fundamental concepts behind the
higher-level abstractions which are central to Triad's security;
<li>
step-wise descriptions of the building blocks of Triad's
<em> functionality </em>
and explanation of how this functionality is implemented in terms of
subjects and security-objects;
<li>
summary of the Triad security <em> policy </em> which
governs the accesses of subjects to security objects;
<li>
identification of the set of previously-described
building blocks that comprise the Triad <em> protection mechanisms </em>
that implement the policy;
<li>
critical <em> reference monitor </em> issues including explanation of how
the protection mechanisms are used to construct a TCB which both protects
itself and enforces the security policy;
<li>
explanation of how the principle of
least privilege is addressed in the Triad system.
</menu>

<!-- signature -->


