<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Joint Task Force -
Advanced Technology Demonstration</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/products/consulting/index.html">
<IMG width=230 height=33  SRC="/docs/images/tisc.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Consulting"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=172 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/govtcon.gif" border=0 ALT="Government Consulting">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 4>Support for Operational Commanders<BR>
Joint Task Force -
Advanced Technology Demonstration</font>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
The JTF ATD program seeks to provide "Anywhere, Anytime, Information
Support" to a deployed JTF Commander in battlefield operations. It also
supports applications for use in disaster relief and law enforcement
operations. The JTF ATD is developing a supportable, portable, command,
control, communications, computers and intelligence (C4I) software
technology base for crisis management, planning and execution. Program
features are the "plug and play" and "ease of use" capabilities
which enable geographically despersed functional experts to connect
their computing systems and exploit the information-based services
on emerging large scale, high speed communications webs.
<P>
The generic services provide support for various C2 concepts and 
functions important to the JTF. These include maps, messages, data,
situations,plans, communications, and computerized models. Underlying
a number of these services is a more generic service, that of webs.
A web describes how an overall product, such as a plan or situation
assessment, is composed from parts, which are in turn composed from
other parts. The web also carries additional information describing
other facets of the composite product, such as how it is evaluated
and a justification for its current status. Services are provided 
by servers which interact using a CORBA Object Request Broker (ORB).
The key initial applications include: anchor desks for logistics,
meteorology and oceanography, and disaster relief; campaign
planning; and distributed collaborative planning.
<P>

The JTF-ATD is part of an integrated testing and development
environment known as the Virtual Testbed (VTB). The VTB's purpose is 
to facilitate rapid transition of advanced technology into operational
use, and consists of different layers of activities: Research and
Development, ATDs, ACTDs, and GCCS LES. Ultimately, the new
successful technologies will be integrated into the operational GCCS. 
The VTB consists of a variety of networks, software infrastructures,
applications, procedures, and support which contribute to the 
complexity and range of security implications and issues.
<P>
TIS's efforts focus on providing ongoing security engineering
research and analyses to NRaD for the JTF ATD Reference Architecture.
In particular, TIS is investigating how the CORBA security 
specifications are being implemented by COTS ORBs and analyzing
how this functionality meets the security requirements of the 
JTF ATD. Additionally, TIS is monitoring security developments
within the GCCS Common Operating Environment (COE) and the
Distributed Computing Environment (DCE).<P>

TIS is also providing ongoing security engineering, and certification
and accreditation support to NRaD for the JTF ATD 
as well as expertise regarding analysis of how these efforts
potentially relate to other applications and command 
environments.<P>
<HR>
<H3>Additional Information</H3>
<P>
