<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Global Command and Control System-Pacific (GCCS-P) Security Engineering and Support</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=230 height=33  SRC="/docs/images/tisc.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Consulting"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=172 height=15 SRC="/docs/images/govtcon.gif" border=0 ALT="Consulting for Government">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 4>Global Command and Control System-Pacific (GCCS-P) Security Engineering and Support</font>
<BR>
<Blockquote>

This Web page contains information on the Global Command and Control
System-Pacific (GCCS-P) Security Engineering and Support task of the INFOSEC
for Networked Systems Project funded by DARPA/ITO.<P>
View the <a href="/docs/images/arpa/nrad9-quad2.gif">quad chart</a> graphic for more information on this project.<P>
<HR>

<H2>PROJECT SUMMARY</H2>

<H3>ARPA Order Number:</H3>
1824

<H3>CONTRACTOR:</H3>

Trusted Information Systems, Inc.
<BR>
3060 Washington Road
<BR>
Glenwood, Maryland  21738
<BR>
Phone: (301) 854-6889
<BR>
FAX:   (301) 854-5363

<H3>PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATORS:</H3>

Herman Lubbes
<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:lubbes@tis.com"><I>lubbes@tis.com</I></A>

<BR><BR>
Robert Paczynski
<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:bob@tis.com"><I>bob@tis.com</I></A>


<H3>TITLE OF EFFORT:</H3>
Global Command and Control System-Pacific (GCCS-P) Security Engineering and
Support


<!--<RELATED_INFORMATION>
http://www.tis.com/docs/Research/arparesearch.html
</RELATED_INFORMATION>-->

<H3>OBJECTIVE:</H3>
The Navy Command, Control, and Ocean Surveillance Center (NCCOSC) is the
principal Navy Research, Development, Testing, and Evaluation (NRaD) center
for command, control, communications (C3) and ocean surveillance.  Trusted 
Information Systems, Inc. has been tasked by the Defense Advanced Research 
Projects Agency (DARPA) to support the NRaD research and development efforts 
for the Global Command and Control System-Pacific (GCCS-P) -- the new, 
unified worldwide U.S. military comamnd and control (C2) system.


<H3>APPROACH:</H3>
This task focuses on providing ongoing security engineering, certification
and accreditation support to NRaD for the JTF ATD program.  Support efforts
include revising the System Security Plan for the GCCS-P, Site MOA 
Information Package, Key Management Plan, Annotated Outline for a Keying 
Material Support Plan, and Security Concept of Operations (CONOPS) for 
Controlling Release of Data to Korean C2 Systems, as necessary, due to 
changes in the operational environment and/or network topology (which affect 
the existing, accredited operating environment).  
<P>

In addition, support efforts also include analysis and identification of
security issues that affect the JTF ATD program.  Such issues included the 
releasability of data to Coalition and Allied forces (e.g., releasability 
issues, natural language translation issues, and the issues associated with 
implementing guards.)

<H3>RECENT 1996 ACCOMPLISHMENTS:</H3>

<UL><LI>
Provided certification and accreditation support for the Internationalization
and Shared Perception (ISP) effort.  Delivered a report called the "Security 
Concept of Operations (CONOPS) Document for the Global Command and Control 
System (GCCS)-Lite and Radiant Mercury (RM) Interface".  The ISP component 
uses the Radiant Mercury guard to control release of subsets of GCCS data to
Coalition and Allied forces.  The released information is displayed to the 
Coalition force using a series of language translation database servers to 
display the information in a native language window.

<BR><LI>This effort is being used as the model that will be employed in other
worldwide theaters and areas of conflict, by merely substituting the
appropriate language translation database server(s) and rewriting the
security rules (as necessary) to identify which information is to be shared
with which countries/organizations and *when* and *how.*

<BR><LI>
Developed a white paper that addressed MLS guard devices that would satisfy
the needs of the JTF ATD program for sharing information with Coalition and 
Allied forces in a controlled and secured manner.  The paper also compared 
and contrasted the two leading candidate products: Radiant Mercury and the 
Command and Control Guard.  This paper was the basis for the use of Radiant 
Mercury for the current ISP effort and for selecting candidate technologies 
to be used in future, related efforts.

<BR><LI>
Delivered the updated the "System Security Plan for the Global Command and
Control System - Pacific (GCCS-P) document.
</UL>

<H3>TECHNOLOGY TRANSITION:</H3>

The purpose of the JTF ATD program is to investigate new technologies to 
determine their applicability to existing program areas.  Technologies 
developed as part of the JTF ATD effort, if deemed feasible, are transitioned 
to the more operational environment at USACOM and are further tested for 
military relevance through the Advanced Joint Planning (AJP) Advanced Concept 
Technology Demonstration (ACTD) program.  Eventually, certain components of 
the AJP ACTD are transitioned to the Global Command and Control System (GCCS) 
Leading Edge Service (LES) where further testing is performed and the 
security functionality of the component is analyzed.  The end goal is the 
provision of distributed collaborative planning capbilities to members of the 
USCINCPAC staff, other Commanders-in-Chief (CINCs), US forces, allies (e.g., 
NATO), and coalition partners.  This task analyzes the security functionality 
and appropriateness of technology proposed for a distributed collaborative
planning environment with diverse and dynamically changing communities of 
interest.

<P>

<ADDRESS>
Last modified: 12 August 1996
</ADDRESS>




</BLOCKQUOTE>
