<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>
Advanced Joint Planning (AJP) - Advanced Concept Technology Demonstration
(ACTD) Security Engineering Support
</title>
<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:holly@la.tis.com">
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=230 height=33  SRC="/docs/images/tisc.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=172 height=15 SRC="/docs/images/govtcon.gif" border=0 ALT="OS Security">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 4>
Advanced Joint Planning (AJP) - Advanced Concept Technology Demonstration
(ACTD) Security Engineering Support

</font>
<Blockquote>
This Web page contains information on the Advanced Joint Planning (AJP) -
Advanced Concept Technology Demonstration (ACTD) Security Engineering Support
task of the INFOSEC for Networked Systems project funded by DARPA/ITO.<P>
View the <a href="/docs/images/arpa/nrad10-quad2.gif">quad chart</a> for more information on the AJP-ACTD project.
<HR>

<H2>PROJECT SUMMARY</H2>

<H3>ARPA Order Number:</H3>
1824


<H3>CONTRACTOR:</H3>

Trusted Information Systems, Inc.
<BR>
3060 Washington Road
<BR>
Glenwood, Maryland  21738
<BR>
Phone: (301) 854-6889
<BR>
FAX:   (301) 854-5363


<H3>PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATORS:</H3>
Pamela Cochrane
<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:cochrane@tis.com"><I>cochrane@tis.com</I></A>

<BR><BR>
Herman Lubbes
<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:lubbes@tis.com"><I>lubbes@tis.com</I></A>

<H3>TITLE OF EFFORT:</H3>
Advanced Joint Planning (AJP) - Advanced Concept Technology Demonstration
(ACTD) Security Engineering Support

<!--<RELATED_INFORMATION>
http://www.tis.com/docs/Research/ajp-actd.html
</RELATED_INFORMATION>-->


<H3>OBJECTIVE:</H3>

This task focuses on providing ongoing security engineering, certification
and accreditation support to NRaD for the Advanced Joint Planning (AJP)
Advanced Concept Technology Demonstration (ACTD) program at USACOM.
Support efforts include revising the Security Concept of Operations
(CONOPS), the AJP ACTD Security Requirements and the AJP ACTD Security
Plan, as necessary due to changes in the accreditation environment and
network topology.  In addition, support efforts will also include analysis
of how the AJP ACTD relates to applications in other command/theater
environments, emerging and evolving security requirements, and new
security products such as FASTLANE.  A major focus of this task will be
to identify and support resolution of security issues associated with
communities of interest, web-like environments, and data transfers to
coalition forces.  Such issues could include releasability issues related
to the implementation of guards, the use of firewalls to restrict assess
to operational data, and the investigation of existing security mechanisms
in the context of evolving technology.


<H3>APPROACH:</H3>

TIS is concentrating on the development, certification, and accreditation
of the AJP ACTD interfaces with higher authority, as well as the AIC, NATO,
and coalition forces.  The Security CONOPS will document system data flows,
provide a basis for determining security requirements and the security mode
of operation, and support certification and accreditation requirements.
The AJP system security requirements are evolving due to changes in
classification policies, network topology, and new functional capabilities.
The System Security Requirements document will describe a high-level security
architecture; describe required subnetworks; identify, access mediation, identification and 
authentication, cryptographic, guard, gateway, and firewall
requirements; and assess architectural alternatives relative to ease of
accreditation.  The System Security Plan will define system security
boundaries and perimeters; identify certification requirements within
perimeters; and provide guidelines for the development of necessary 
accreditation documents.  In addition, emerging technology developments will be assessed
and evaluated, and their security impacts will be documented in white papers.

<H3>RECENT 1996 ACCOMPLISHMENTS:</H3>

<UL>
<LI>

Provided certification and accreditation support for the Internationalization
and Shared Perception (ISP) component of JWID96.  Delivered a report called
the "System Security Plan for the Internationalization and Shared Perception
Component of the Joint Warrier Interoperability Demonstration 1996 (JWID96)".

<BR><LI>
Investigated the security functionality of the Intelligence Guard for
the Office of Naval Intelligence Replication (IGOR) processor.  IGOR
transfers database updates and deletes in one direction between enclaves
of the same classification level. Delivered a white paper describing the
findings, "Intelligence Guard for the Office of Naval Intelligence (ONI)
Replication (IGOR)".

<BR><LI>Researched issues associated with security functionality in DCE and
CORBA and how proposed security mechanisms impact the JTF ATD Reference
Architecture.  Discussed the findings in white paper, "Security for the
JTF ATD Architecture on GCCS: DCE and CORBA Issues".

<BR><LI>The JTF ATD would like to provide contractor connectivity to the TCCS LAN
using an existing connection on the NRaD Lab unclassified LAN.  Investigated
how the connectivity could be accomplished in a secure manner and made
recommendations for the installation of a pair of firewalls.  Delivered to
NRaD a white paper called, "NRaD/Contractor Connectivity White Paper".

<BR><LI>
The AJP ACTD has an interim accreditation to operate at USACOM.  ACOM
asked for help in determining the security requirements for a full
accreditation of the AJP ACTD.  This information was provided in a
report called, "The AJP ACTD Accreditation Process".

<BR><LI>
The AJP ACTD Security Concept of Operations (CONOPS) has been updated
and provided to USACOM for review.
</UL>

<H3>TECHNOLOGY TRANSITION:</H3>
Technology developed as part of the JTF ATD effort transitions to the
more operational environment at USACOM and is tested for military relevance
in the Advanced Joint Planning (AJP) Advanced Concept Technology Demonstration
(ACTD).  AJP ACTD applications and servers must be accredited to run on
the USACOM ATM LAN.  Eventually, certain components of the AJP ACTD are
transitioned to the Global Command and Control System (GCCS) Leading Edge
Service (LES) where further testing is performed and the security
functionality of the component is analyzed.  The goal is to provide
distributed collaborative planning capbilities to members of the USACOM
staff, other Commanders-in-Chief (CINCs), other US forces, allies (e.g., NATO),
and coalition partners.  This task analyzes the security functionality and
appropriateness of technology proposed for a distributed web-like environment
with diverse and dynamically changing communities of interest.  In addition,
it assists in the certification and accreditation of the AJP ACTD at USACOM.


<P>

<ADDRESS>
Last modified: 12 August 1996
</ADDRESS>




</BLOCKQUOTE>
