<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Pacific Data Center</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/products/consulting/index.html">
<IMG width=230 height=33  SRC="/docs/images/tisc.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Consulting"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=172 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/govtcon.gif" border=0 ALT="Government Consulting">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 4>Support for Operational Commanders<BR>
Pacific Data Center</font>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
The PDC consists of a Command Center 
at the State Emergency Operations Center and an Application 
Center at the Maui Research Technical Center. The PDC 
capabilities include: 1) providing centralized information 
processing; 2) allowing for the use of advanced computing 
and image processing; 3) introducing new data sources; 
4) expanding existing databases; 5) assisting disaster planners; 
6) developing new information products; 7) distributing 
tailored information to all users; and 8) improving the Pacific 
Regional Emergency Management Information System (PREMIS) 
communications infrastructure. The PDC will facilitate the 
predication, planning, execution, monitoring, and response 
to disasters in Hawaii and the Pacific Insular States (e.g., 
Samoa, Palau, Micronesia, North Marianas, Marshall Islands, 
and Alaska). Several current technologies, such as the 
Logistics Anchor Desk, the Weather Anchor Desk, the Disaster 
Information Anchor Desk, and components of the 
<a href="/docs/products/consulting/govt/jtf.html">JTF ATD</A>
will 
transition into the PDC. The goal of seamless interoperability 
between military and non-military government agencies, private 
disaster relief organizations, and coalition systems presents 
security issues associated with the release of classified 
information to non-classified networks and to other communities 
of interest. 
<P>
The PDC is part of an integrated testing and development
environment known as the Virtual Testbed (VTB). The VTB's purpose is 
to facilitate rapid transition of advanced technology into operational
use, and consists of different layers of activities: Research and
Development, ATDs, ACTDs, and GCCS LES. Ultimately, the new
successful technologies will be integrated into the operational GCCS. 
The VTB consists of a variety of networks, software infrastructures,
applications, procedures, and support which contribute to the 
complexity and range of security implications and issues.
<P>
TIS's efforts will focus on the security issues associated with 
the development of the PDC interfaces with higher authority, 
as well as with PACOM, other non-military government agencies 
(e.g., FEMA, Civil Defense), private disaster relief organizations 
(e.g., the Red Cross) and coalition forces. Efforts include the 
Security CONOPS for the PDC which documents system data flows, 
provides a basis for determining security requirements and the 
security mode of operation, and supports certification and 
accreditation requirements. In addition, TIS plans to investigate 
and propose solutions to the security issues associated with the 
releasability of classified information to appropriate communities 
of interest. 

<P>
<H3>Additional Information</H3>
<P>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.pdc.org/">
Pacific Data Center Home Page</A><br>
</UL>

