<!-- Main Body -->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
<h3>III.  Firewall Services</h3><p>
	The following services were tested by the Gauntlet team:  
<a href="#telnet">telnet</a>, <a href="#rlogin">rlogin</a>, 
<a href="#ftp">ftp</a>, <a href="#NNTP">NNTP</a>, <a href="#http">http</a>, 
<a href="#http">Gopher</a>, <a href="#X">X-windows</a>, <a href="#smtp">smtp</a>
 (e-mail), <a href="#auth">authentication</a>, and <a href="#crypt">encryption</a>. 
The specific tests performed and the results of each performed are captured below.  <p>
<a name="telnet">
1.  TELNET<p>

	Telnet provides a remote character terminal over the internet.  
Using telnet, a system can offer simple or complicated interactive information services.
    It can be configured to look like a normal login, or use a customized login 
procedure, or no login at all. As a rule, telnet daemons call login to authenticate 
and initialize the session.  The Gauntlet firewall offers the option of configuring 
the telnet proxy with a plaintext password or with strong authentication on incoming 
connections using skey or Digital Pathways Secure Net Key (SNK).  In addition, the 
Gauntlet also provides proxy transparency on outgoing messages.  That is, the 
firewall will automatically intercept the outgoing connections and invoke a 
proxy on behalf of the user.  In this way the user does not have to interact 
with the firewall, and the administrator is still able to capture auditing 
information.  The following tests include a verification of the telnet 
transparency capability:<p>

		Test #1:  Telnet from badguy.attack.mil to hq.peaceful.mil through 
gauntlet.peaceful.mil (the Gauntlet firewall)<p>

<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  To verify that the Telnet protocol works as expected on the 
firewall.  SKey authentication will be used to verify that the user on the
 external computer badguy.attack.mil is a legitimate user.<p>

<p>

	<i>Procedures:</i><p>

<i>Note</i>:  Commands issued during tests will be in bold typeface.  Responses will 
be normal typeface.<p>

<p>

badguy% <b>telnet gauntlet.peaceful.mil</b><p>

username:  <b>muser1</b><p>

Skey Challenge: s/key 661 bo 27315 <b>IS HATH ODIN IONS AMOK AMMO</b><p>

Login Accepted<p>

gauntlet.peaceful.mil telnet proxy (Version g3.0.3) ready:<p>

tn-gw-&gt; <b>connect hq.peaceful.mil</b><p>

Trying 199.211.151.11 port 23 ...<p>

Connected to hq.peaceful.mil<p>

<p>

UNIX (r)   System V Release 4.0   (hq)<p>

<p>

login:  <b>muser1</b><p>

Password:<p>

Last login:  Wed Jan 24  14:51:40  from gauntlet.peaceful.mil<p>

Sun Microsystems Inc.   SunOS 5.4   Generic July 1994<p>

You have mail.<p>

hq%<p>

<p>

	<i>Expected results</i>:  If successful, the command prompt (hq%) should appear 
on badguy.attack.mil, the computer initiating the telnet session.<p>

<p>

		<i>Observed Result</i>:  Telnet session initiation from the outside 
(badguy.attack.mil) through the firewall was successful<p>

<p>

<p>

	<i>Test #2</i>:  Telnet from hq.peaceful.mil to badguy.attack.mil through 
gauntlet.peaceful.mil (the Gauntlet firewall) without transparency.<p>

<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  To verify that the telnet protocol works as expected from the 
inside to the outside, thruough the firewall.  The user should have to log 
into the firewall before logging into the target machine, given that 
transparency is inactive.<p>

<p>

	<i>Procedures:</i><p>

hq% <b>telnet badguy.attack.mil</b><p>

Trying 222.222.22.2<p>

<p>

(<i>Note</i>:  This attempt to telnet directly to badguy.attack.mil through the 
firewall was unsuccessful because transparency was disabled on the firewall.  
Therefore, the test will be repeated by logging into the firewall first.)<p>

<p>

hq% <b>telnet gauntlet.peaceful.mil</b><p>

Connected to gauntlet.peaceful.mil<p>

Escape character is `^]'<p>

gauntlet.peaceful.mil telnet proxy (Version g3.0.3) ready:<p>

tn-gw-&gt; <b>connect badguy.attack.mil</b><p>

