<p>
<a name="rlogin">
2.  RLOGIN<p>

	Rlogin provides remote terminal service that is similar to telnet, 
except that rlogin does not require that the user type his/her username 
and if the connection is coming from a ``trusted host'' or ``trusted user'', 
then the user can login without typing a password. Because of the many 
known security hazards with the rlogin service, it is generally not 
recommended that this service be supported through a firewall.  The 
Gauntlet firewall gives the administrator the option to use strong 
authentication for incoming access through the rlogin daemon.  The 
Gauntlet firewall test team strongly recommends that if this service 
is allowed through the firewall, that it ONLY be available with the 
strong authentication enabled.  The following tests were run on the 
rlogin service provided on the Gauntlet firewall: <p>

	<i>Test #1</i>:  Rlogin from badguy.attack.mil to hq.peaceful.mil 
through gauntlet.peaceful.mil (the Gauntlet firewall).<p>

<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  To verify that the rlogin protocol works as 
expected on the firewall using Skey authentication.<p>

<p>

	<i>Procedures</i>:<p>

badguy% <b>rlogin gauntlet.peaceful.mil</b><p>

Username:  <b>muser1</b><p>

Skey Challenge:  s/key 660 bo 27315<b>HUH TUN BLOT MALT DISH OX</b><p>

Login Accepted<p>

gauntlet.peaceful.mil rlogin proxy (Version g3.0.3) ready:<p>

rlogin-gw-&gt;  <b>connect hq.peaceful.mil</b><p>
Trying muser1@199.211.151.11 ...<p>

Last login:  Wed Jan 24  15:27:52 from gauntlet.peaceful.mil<p>

Sun Microsystems Inc.   SunOS  5.4   Generic July 1994<p>

You have mail.<p>

hq%<p>

<p>

	<i>Expected Results</i><:  If successful, the command prompt (hq%) 
should appear on badguy.attack.mil, the computer initiating the rlogin session.<p>

<p>

	<i>Observed Result</i>:  Rlogin session initiation from an external 
computer (badguy.attack.mil) with strong authentication was successful.<p>

<p>

<p>

	<i>Test #2</i>:  Rlogin from hq.peaceful.mil to badguy.attack.mil 
through gauntlet.peaceful.mil without transparency.<p>

<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  To verify that the rlogin protocol works as 
expected from an inside computer to an outside computer through 
the firewall.  The user should have to do an rlogin to the firewall 
before doing an rlogin to the target machine.<p>

<p>

	<i>Procedures</i>:  <p>

hq% <b>rlogin -l euser1 gauntlet.peaceful.mil</B><p>

gauntlet.peaceful.mil rlogin proxy (Version g3.0.3) ready:<p>

