<p>
<a name="ftp">
3.  FTP<p>

	The File Transfer Protocol supports the transmission and character
 set translation of text and binary files.  When a user uses ftp to contact 
a remote machine, the remote computer requires that the user login by 
providing a username and password. The Gauntlet firewall can be configured 
so that incoming users must use strong authentication to connect to the 
ftp proxy on the firewall.  Once authenticated, the ftp proxy then 
prompts the user to enter the username and password of the internal 
machine.  In a typical ftp configuration, the incoming user's ftp 
command opens a control channel from port 21 to the remote machine, 
and the actual data from a file transfer or directory listing is sent 
back over a data channel originating from port 20 on the remote machine.  
Because the protocol uses two TCP connections, this service is generally 
more difficult to proxy through a firewall.  The following set of tests 
were performed on the Gauntlet firewall ftp service.<p>

	<i>Test #1</i>:  Ftp from an external computer (badguy.attack.mil)  
to an internal computer (hq.peaceful.mil) through gauntlet.peaceful.mil 
(the Gauntlet firewall)<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  To verify that the Ftp protocol works as expected on the 
firewall.  Skey authentication will be used to verify that the user on 
badguy.attack.mil is a legitimate user.<p>

	<i>Procedures</i>: <p>

badguy%  ftp gauntlet.peaceful.mil<p>

connected gauntlet.peaceful.mil <p>

220 proxy first requires authentication <p>

220 gauntlet.peaceful.mil FTP proxy (Version g3.03) ready<p>

Name (gauntlet.peaceful.mil: root): <b>muser1</b><p>

331 skey challenge:s/key 663 bo27317<p>

Password:<p>

230 user authenticated to proxy<p>

ftp&gt;  <b>user muser1@hq.peaceful.mil</b><p>

331 (----GATEWAY CONNECTED TO hq.peaceful.mil----)<p>

331 (220 hq FTP server (Unix(r) System V Release 4.0) ready.)<p>

331 password required for muser1<p>

Password:<p>

230 user muser1 logged in<p>

ftp&gt;<p>

<p>

	<i>Expected Results</i>:  If successful, the ftp prompt should appear on 
hq.peaceful.mil, the computer initiating the ftp session.<p>

	<i>Observed Result</i>:  The ftp proxy works as described in the TIS 
Firewall User's Overview.<p>

<p>

	<i>Test #2</i>  Ftp from the inside computer (hq.peaceful.mil)  to the 
outside computer (badguy.attack.mil)l through gauntlet.peaceful.mil 
(the Gauntlet firewall) with transparency.<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  To verify that the ftp protocol works as expected from 
the inside domain through the firewall. <p>

 	<i>Procedures</i>:  <p>

<b># ftp 222.222.22.2</b><p>

connected to 222.222.22.2  <p>

220 badguy FTP server Unix(r) System V (Release 4.0) ready<p>

Name (222.222.22.2:root): <b>euser1</b><p>

331 Password required for euser1<p>

Password:<p>

230 euser1 logged in<p>

ftp&gt;<p>

	<i>Expected Results</i>:  If successful, the ftp prompt should appear 
on badguy.attack.mil ,, the computer initiating the ftp session.<p>

	<i>Observed Results</i>:  The ftp protocol, when used with the 
transparency option on, works as  expected thorugh the firewall.<p>

<p>

	<i>Test #3</i>  Ftp from hq.pacom to badguy.attack.mil through 
gauntlet.peaceful.mil (the Gauntlet firewall) without transparency.<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  To verify that the ftp protocol works as expected 
when the transparency option is turned off.  The user should have 
to log into the firewall  before logging into the target machine, 
given that the transparency has been inactivated.<p>

	<i>Procedures</i>:  <p>

hq% <b>ftp badguy.attack.mil</b><p>

Trying 222.222.22.2<p>

<p>

(<i>Note</i>:  This attempt to ftp directly to badguy.attack.mil 
through the firewall was unsuccessful because transparency 
was disabled on the firewall.  Therefore, the test will be 
repeated by logging into the firewall first.)<p>

<p>

hq% <b>ftp gauntlet.peaceful.mil</b><p>

Connected to gauntlet.peaceful.mil<p>

gauntlet.peaceful.mil ftp proxy (Version g3.0.3) ready:<p>

ftp-gw-&gt; <b>ftp badguy.attack.mil</b><p>

connected to 222.222.22.2  <p>

220 badguy FTP server Unix(r) System V (Release 4.0) ready<p>

Name (222.222.22.2:root): <b>euser1</b><p>

331 Password required for euser1<p>

Password:<p>

230 euser1 logged in<p>

ftp&gt;	<p>

	<I>Expected Results</i>:  If successful, the ftp prompt should 
appear on badguy.attack.mil , the terminal initiating the ftp session.<p>

	<i>Observed Results</i>:  The ftp proxy works as expected when 
the transparency option is disabled on the firewall.<p>

