<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
<h3>IV.  Additional Testing</h3><p>
1.  IP PORT SCAN <p>

	The port scanning software used for testing purposes was 
acquired from MITRE corp.  The following options are given when 
the program is run: 
1) edit the hosts file 
2) toggle run from hosts file 
3) test standard TCP/IP ports 
4) test unix privileged ports
5) test all possible ports 
6) execute all tests 
7) view test results 
8) change hosts 
9) print last run 
10) exit    <p>

Results of running 5) test all possible ports 
(a total of 65536 ports were scanned):<p>

TCP connection succeeded on port 21 ftp<p>

TCP connection succeeded on port 23 telnet<p>

TCP connection succeeded on port 25 smtp<p>

TCP connection succeeded on port 43 whois<p>

TCP connection succeeded on port 53 domain<p>

TCP connection succeeded on port 70<p>

TCP connection succeeded on port 79 finger<p>

TCP connection succeeded on port 80<p>

TCP connection succeeded on port 113<p>

TCP connection succeeded on port 119 nntp<p>

TCP connection succeeded on port 513 login<p>

TCP connection succeeded on port 7777<p>

<p>

These results show fingerd to be running on port 79/tcp:<p>

	However, on further examination of the netperm-table 
of the Gauntlet firewall, the following is the entry for 
the untrusted network use of the finger service:  <p>

 netacl-fingerd:  permit-hosts * -exec    /bin/cat  /usr/local/etc/finger.txt   <p>

The Gauntlet firewall does not actually allow the finger 
service into the firewall.  It responds to commands received 
on port 79 with a message indicating that the finger service 
is not available.  Thus, external users cannot obtain any useful 
information via the finger service. <p>

<p>

2.  SATAN<p>

	SATAN is a tool written by Wietse Venema and Dan Farmer.  
When executed against a network it recognizes common networking-related 
security problems and reports these problems without actually exploiting them.  <p>

	The Gauntlet firewall test team ran SATAN against 
the configuration shown in APPENDIX A.  The results of this 
exercise are not included in this report as they did not reveal 
vulnerabilities in the Gauntlet firewall configuration.  <p>

<p>

3.  ISS  <p>

	Internet Security Scanner (ISS) is a tool written by 
Christopher Klaus which can be used to automatically find the 
security holes in a firewall.  The tool scans a range of network 
addresses and attempts to exploit known vulnerabilities in SMTP, 
ftp, www, RPC, UDP, and numerous other services.  The tool is 
available commercially (ISS V 3.0) for approximately $2K.  <p>

	The commercial version of ISS is currently being procured 
by the X31 firewall team.  The Gauntlet firewall test team ran the 
public domain version of the tool, which is less comprehensive 
in its attack scenarios and produces less robust report documentation, 
against the Gauntlet firewall configuration.   These results 
indicate that the ISS tool was unsuccessful in its attempts to 
discover vulnerabilities in the Gauntlet firewall.  The results 
of ISS are included below for information purposes:<p>

Scanning from 199.211.151.20 to 199.211.151.20                                   199.211.151.20             gauntlet.peaceful.mil <p>

SMTP: 220 gauntlet.peaceful.mil  SMTP/smap Ready<p>

250 &lt;guest&gt;<p>

250 &lt;decode&gt;<p>

250 &lt;bbs&gt;<p>

250 &lt;lp&gt;<p>

250 &lt;uudecode&gt;<p>

500 command unrecognized <p>

200 Debug set -NOT!<p>

221 Closing connection<p>

<p>

FTP:  220 gauntlet.peaceful.mil  FTP Proxy (Version g3.03) 
ready 220 gauntlet.peaceful.mil <p>

501:  use user@site to connect proxy<p>

501:  use ``authorize'' command first<p>

500:  must be connected to remote server<p>

500:  must be connected to remote server<p>

500:  must be connected to remote server<p>

<p>

Inet Security Scanner Log<p>

host 199.211.151.20, port 21 (ftp service) opened.<p>

host 199.211.151.20, port 23 (telnet service) opened.<p>

host 199.211.151.20, port 25 (smtp service) opened.<p>

host 199.211.151.20, port 43 (whois service) opened.<p>

host 199.211.151.20, port 53 (dns service) opened.<p>

host 199.211.151.20, port 70 opened.<p>

host 199.211.151.20, port 79 (finger service) opened.<p>

host 199.211.151.20, port 80 opened.<p>

host 199.211.151.20, port 113 opened.<p>

host 199.211.151.20, port 119 (nntp service) opened.<p>

host 199.211.151.20, port 513 (login service) opened.<p>

host 199.211.151.20, port 7777 <p>

<p>

4.  IP WATCHER <p>

	IP Watcher is a tool that is offered by En Garde Systems for 
approximately $15K.  It is marketed as an administration tool which 
can be used to monitor, log, and control login sessions on a network.    
It provides the capability to monitor active TCP/IP sessions 
(login connections, mail connections, and file transfer connections)  
on the local subnet.  The tool also allows an administrator to terminate 
active connections by sending a reset command (either manually or automatically).  
Macro commands can also be executed by the tool.  	<p>

	Using this tool, a hacker could not only monitor all telnet, 
rlogin, ftp, and SMTP session on the subnet, but also hijack or 
terminate any connection on the subnet.  In addition, passwords 
can be snooped (including one time password information), electronic 
mail can be snooped, and session information can be compromised.   <p>

	The existence of tools of this nature emphasize the inherent 
limitations of any firewall system.  By monitoring all connections 
into the internal network and providing restricted access via proxy 
gateways, a firewall can offer a first line of defense against outside 
attempts to compromise the internal network. However, without continuous 
identification and authentication capability or the provision of encrypted 
IP tunneling the firewall cannot prevent sophisticated tools and experienced 
attackers from getting the information they are seeking.  <p>

	The Gauntlet firewall test team ran the IP Watcher software 
against the test configuration in order to better understand its 
capabilities.  We were successful in hijacking a telnet session 
and in watching SMTP e-mail messages being passed from the internet 
side into the internal network.  <p>

<p>

5.  MISCELLANEOUS TESTS / SCRIPTS<p>

	<i>Test #1</i>:  The following test was run to determine the 
effects on the Gauntlet firewall when the log file system is full:<p>

	<i>Procedures</i>:<p>

	Command:  Login to Gauntlet console as root<p>

	Command:   cd /usr/var/log<p>

	Command:  mkdir TESTS<p>

	Command:  cd TESTS<p>

	Command:  cp /bsd bigfile<p>

	Command: cat bigfile &gt;&gt; bigfile  <p>

	Result:  an error message occurs indicating that the file system is full<p>

	Command:  df  <p>

	Result:  shows that the /var/logs file system is at 105%<p>

	Command:  ftp 222.222.22.4 [ON BADGUY]   <p>

	Result:  username prompt appears<p>

	Command:  Enter `root' UID at prompt [ON BADGUY]  <p>

	Result:  error occurs indicating `root' login not allowed for ftp<p>

	Command:  Repeat the `ftp 222.222.22.4' command until 
new messages no longer appear <p>

	Result:  the last disk block of the messages file is filled<p>

	Command:  ftp 222.222.22.4 [ON BADGUY] <p>

	Result:   A username prompt appears<p>

	Command:  Enter `ftp' UID at prompt [ON BADGUY]  <p>

	Result: (UID accepted)<p>

	Command:  Enter `password' for `ftp' at prompt [ON BADGUY] <p>

  	Result:  password accepted<p>

	Command:  netscape [ON HQ 199.211.151.?]  <p>

	Result: application runs<p>

	Command:  Make `http' request to 222.222.22.2 for the home page <p>

 	Result:  home page obtained<p>

<p>

	<i>Observed Results</i>:  The results of this test show that if the 
Gauntlet firewall  /usr/var/log file system (where message logging 
occurs) fills, then the Gauntlet firewall  ftp and http proxies still 
allow services.  This is dangerous because attacks or attempted break-ins 
could occur when no audit trail exists.<p>

<p>

	<i>Test #2</i> :  This test will determine the Gauntlet firewall response 
when the /var/log/messages log file is deleted.<p>

	<i>Procedures</i>:  <p>

	Command:  login to the Gauntlet as root<p>

	Command: cd /var/logs<p>

	Command:  rm messages <p>

 	Result:  the messages file is deleted<p>

	Command:  reboot  <p>

	Command:  login to the Gauntlet as root<p>

	Command: cd /usr/var/log<p>

	Command:  ftp 222.222.22.4  [ON BADGUY] <p>

 	Result:  ftp successful connect<p>

	Command:  give invalid ftp UID<p>

  	Result:  ftp login denied<p>

	Command:  ls -ly messages<p>

 	Result:  no message file was found<p>

<p>

	<i>Ovserved Results</I>:  The results of this test show that if the 
/var/log/messages file is deleted, then the Gauntlet firewall logger 
process does not create a new one when it starts.  Consequently, the 
logging of events does not occur under these conditions and attacks 
and/or break-in attempts could occur without any record.<p>

<p>

<p>

	<i>Test #3</i>:   If someone inadvertently (or intentionally) 
deletes or moves the /var/log/message file and recreates a new one, 
logging will be disabled until the firewall is rebooted.  <p>

<p>

	<i>Test Analysis</i>:  This could cause a problem for administrators 
who move and save message files off because this actions would 
inadvertently shut down logging.<p>

<p>

