<!-- Main Body -->
<h2>Test Procedures and Report</h2><p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
<h3>I.  Introduction</h3><p>

	1.  Background<p>
	The Trusted Information Systems Gauntlet (V 3.0) firewall is designed to enforce 
security on connections between networks that have different administrative domains.  
The Gauntlet firewall is implemented with a conservative design philosophy, acting as 
a complete traffic block and transporting all traffic through application layer 
proxies that gateway each service on behalf of the user.  The Gauntlet (V 3.0) 
firewall also supports transparent proxies and IP-level encryption.  Gauntlet 
firewalls provide detailed traffic reports and a complete audit trail for 
information passing through the firewall.  <p>

	Trusted Information Systems, Inc. and NSA signed an MOA which provided for 
the installation and use of a Gauntlet firewall for the period of the testing. 
The testing is designed to take place over a 6 to 8 week period with the 
resulting report to be shared with the vendor.  Testing of the Gauntlet firewall  
was performed by a team consisting of members from NSA and the Mitre Corp. as 
part of an ongoing firewall testing effort initiated by the Firewalls, Routers, 
and Guards division of the Network Security Group.  Those members include:  
Kathy Dolan X31, Tammy Mannarino X31, Todd Paisley X31, Bob Hundley X31, 
Michelle Edwards X31, Ed Zieglar C41, Paul Huesken C42, Vicki Mosely V112, 
Norm Eko Y103, and Lisa Mitchell Mitre Corp.  Because of circumstances 
beyond the control of the team, this testing phase was extended an extra 4 weeks.  
However, the actual testing effort took place over an 8 week span.<p>

	2.  Purpose<p>

The X31 lab configuration is shown in <a href="appa.html">Appendix A</a>.  Please note the naming 
conventions used in this configuration.  The computers representing the 
inside enclave are named cinc and hq while the computers representing the 
outside enclave are named badguy and worseguy. These names were arbitrarily 
assigned with the intent to differentiate the two enclaves.  In accordance 
with the Gauntlet firewall Test Plan, the vendor claims of functionality will 
be validated and the following basic services will be tested:  Telnet, rlogin, 
ftp, NNTP, Gopher, HTTP, X-windows, plug-gw and SMTP e-mail.  Security features 
such as filtering,  auditing, authentication, and confidentiality will be examined 
as well. The firewall will be tested for vulnerabilities known through the various 
advisories and postings available in the open source.  Finally, the test team will 
perform additional tests as time permits.  <p>

3.  Scope<p>

	<a href="sec2.html">Section two</a> of the report consists of a table which documents the vendor 
claims about the product (found primarily in the administrator's guide) and 
whether or not the test team was able to validate these claims in the laboratory. <p>

	The <a href="sec3.html">third section</a> addresses the services provided by the firewall.  
This section includes the actual tests that were performed by the test team in 
order to validate a feature or establish vulnerabilities of a feature.  For each 
test performed the purpose of the test will be described, the expected results 
given, and the procedures and observed results documented. The test purpose 
discusses the specific purpose and meaning of the test.  The expected results 
section discusses the expected outcome of the test based on the feature being 
tested or the information available about the particular test.  The procedures 
section provides specific instructions for performing the test. This information 
includes commands run or data input in order to execute the test.  Finally, the 
outcome of the test is documented in the observed results section.   Following 
the description of all of the tests performed on a  particular service, findings 
are provided which summarize and draw conclusions based on the combined results 
of the tests.<p>

	<a href="sec4.html">Section IV</a> describes in detail the additional tests that the team was 
able to perform on the Gauntlet firewall.   <p>

	<a href="sec5.html">Section V</a> of the document summarizes the findings of the Gauntlet test 
team and makes recommendations based on these findings.<p>

