<head>
<title>NSA Test Report on Gauntlet - Sec V</title>
</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222"
ALink="#B22222">


<center>
<a href="http://www.tis.com/docs/index.html">
<IMG 
SRC="http://www.tis.com/docs/images/gtop.gif" border=0
ALT="gauntlet"></A>
<HR  size=2>
<IMG SRC="/docs/images/testrep.gif"
border=0 ALT="press"></a>
</center>
<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
<h3>V. Summary and Conclusions</h3><p>

     The goal of the Trusted Information Systems, Inc. Gauntlet V3.0 analysis and testing effort was twofold:
     1) to examine the firewall in light of the vendor claimed capabilities and attempt to verify that the
     firewall does the things that the vendor claims it does and 2) to check the firewall for known
     vulnerabilities such as those things found in the Cert advisories and other open sources. 
<P>
     The following are the basic findings: 
<P>
     Installation and training: The Gauntlet firewall installation was assisted by a Trusted Information
     Systems, Inc. installer and went very smoothly. TIS, Inc. had wisely gathered the information necessary
     beforehand to ensure as quick and organized installation as possible. Throughout the testing effort TIS,
     Inc. provided telephone support and was responsive to our questions and concerns.
<P>
     Vendor claims: The features of the Gauntlet firewall described in ``Running the Gauntlet''
     Administrator's Guide were validated in the X31 testing effort. Because of time constraints we were
     unable take an in-depth look at the operating system installed on the Gauntlet firewall. One of our
     concerns was that the syslogd on the Gauntlet had not been replaced with the patched version issued
     through a CERT advisory dating October 19. 1995. However, we discovered that Gauntlet firewall
     products sold after October 19, 1995 have the syslogd patch installed. 
<P>
     Vulnerabilities: The Gauntlet test team found the Gauntlet firewall vulnerable to flooding attacks using
     both the http and the SMTP protocols. In both cases, the firewall began rebooting itself after multiple
     simultaneous connections using either of these protocols. It appears that this problem may be related to
     the filling of the message buffer. Other vulnerabilities of the SMTP protocol were also exploited by the
     test team. For example, the team was able to successfully send a trojan horse embedded in an e-mail
     message and a postscript document containing an executable file through the firewall. It should be
     emphasized that the success of these attacks is NOT unique to the Gauntlet and would be successful
     against many commercial firewalls. Mail spoofing falls into this category as well in that while it was
     successful against the Gauntlet firewall, simply by allowing mail to pass into the internal network
     attacks such as these become possible. 
<P>
     The testing also revealed that the Gauntlet allows service to continue through the firewall when log
     failures are introduced. For example, the message buffer was filled and the Gauntlet allowed continued
     use of the http and ftp proxies without the capability to provide auditing. In addition, the team
     discovered that the deletion of the log file does not cause any disruption in service and that the
     machine must be rebooted when the log file is restored. 
<P>
     In general, the Gauntlet firewall has a very solid set of proxies with numerous options for specific
     configurations to be added. The bulk of the vulnerabilities discovered by the testing team represent
     vulnerabilities that exist in most firewalls available today.

<P>
	
