<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>INFOSEC Architecture for Advanced Real-Time Networking</title>
<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:holly@la.tis.com">
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=230 height=33  SRC="/docs/images/tisc.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Consulting"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=172 height=15 SRC="/docs/images/govtcon.gif" border=0 ALT="Consulting for Government">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 6>INFOSEC Architecture for Advanced Real-Time Networking</font>
<BR>
<Blockquote>

This Web page contains information on the INFOSEC Architecture for Advanced
Real-Time Networking task of the INFOSEC for Networked Systems project funded by DARPA/ITO.<P>
View the <a href="/docs/images/arpa/stow97-quad2.gif">quad chart</a> graphic for additional information about STOW-97.
<HR>

<H2>PROJECT SUMMARY</H2>

<H3>ARPA Order Number:</H3>


8685


<H3>CONTRACTOR:</H3>

Trusted Information Systems, Inc.
<BR>
3060 Washington Road
<BR>
Glenwood, Maryland  21738
<BR>
Phone: (301) 854-6889
<BR>
FAX:   (301) 854-5363

<H3>PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATORS:</H3>

Herman Lubbes
<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:lubbes@tis.com"><I>lubbes@tis.com</I></A>
<P>

Robert Paczynski<br>
<A HREF="mailto:bob@tis.com"><I>bob@tis.com</I></A>

<H3>TITLE OF EFFORT:</H3>
INFOSEC For Networked Systems

<H3>SUBTASK:</H3>

INFOSEC Architecture for Advanced Real-Time Networking


<!--<RELATED_INFORMATION>
http://www.tis.com/docs/Research/arparesearch.html
</RELATED_INFORMATION>-->

<H3>OBJECTIVE:</H3>

The Synthetic Theater of War-97 (STOW-97) project is an Advanced 
Concept 
Technology Demonstration, within the Real-Time Information 
Transfer and 
Networking (RITN) effort, to advance the current state of 
mulitcasting and 
networking technology.  
<P>
Trusted Information Systems, Inc. (TIS) was tasked by DARPA to 
support the 
NRL efforts to develop a distributed simulation system, based on 
state-of-
the-art technologies which will support the full operational 
capability of 
the United States Atlantic Command (USACOM) Joint Training 
Analysis and 
Simulation Center and improve the capabilities of Service 
simulations.
Specifically, TIS has been tasked to determine the information 
security 
requirements for STOW-97.  This tasking includes assessing 
currently 
developing technologies and analyzing which are sufficiently 
mature to 
support STOW-97 security requirements.


<H3>APPROACH:</H3>

This task provides ongoing security engineering support for the 
STOW-97 
by: assessing prototype network architecture security 
requirements; 
developing a security architecture for the prototype STOW-97 
network; and 
analyzing evolving technologies, such as multicast techniques 
over 
Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) networks, to determine which 
evolving 
technologies are both sufficiently mature and are capable of 
supporting 
STOW-97 security requirements.  New multicast technologies are 
also being 
investigated to satisfy the high-bandwidth demands of STOW-97, as 
well as new 
high-speed security products such as FASTLANE (a high-speed 
encryption device 
well-suited for ATM-based networks).

<H3>RECENT 1996 ACCOMPLISHMENTS:</H3>

<UL>
<LI>

Developed a briefing presentation entitled "Distributed 
Interactive 
Simulation (DIS) Security Architectures" for NRL that presented 
and assessed
the various alternative security architectures for supporting the 
STOW-97
real-time networking security requirements.

<BR><LI>
Wrote a technical white paper that addressed the various 
alternatives and 
recommended architectures for using multicast technology over a 
commercial 
ATM backbone to move information from an Internet Protocol 
(IP)-based Local 
Area Network (LAN) subnet at a particular classification to 
another IP-based 
LAN subnet operating at a different classification level.

<BR><LI>
Investigated and determined the minimal physical, environmental, 
and 
procedural security requirements required for FASTLANE Release 1 
(FR1) test 
sites (NRL, NRaD, SEID/SAIC, TEC, and IDA) for handling, testing, 
and storing
FR1 devices and other associated equipment and COMSEC materials. 
 Since 
STOW-97 will need to transmit information securely between 
networks of 
differing security classifications over a public Wide Area 
Network (WAN), the 
FASTLANE (KG-75) device was selected to handle this requirement. 
 FASTLANE is 
a high-speed encryption device that provides network security 
services for 
ATM networks.  Along with contacting each of the initial test 
site security 
points of contact (POCs) to ensure they were ready to receive 
their 
equipment, other associated devices (e.g., Data Transfer Device), 
and keying 
materials (i.e., they complied with the minimum security 
requirements 
established by NSA doctrine), a checklist was also developed 
(currently in 
draft form) that outlines these requirements in greater detail.
</UL>

<H3>TECHNOLOGY TRANSITION:</H3>

The STOW-97 prototype efforts in the areas of distributed 
simulation systems 
and associated operating environments (e.g., advances made in the 
current 
state of multicasting and network technologies, such as ATM and 
SONET) have 
lead to the migration of these technologies to support the fully 
operational 
capabilities of the USACOM Joint Training Analysis and Simulation 
Center 
(e.g., sharing classified and unclassified information within a 
distributed 
simulation environment over a common communication backbone).

<P>

<ADDRESS>
Last modified: 12 August 1996
</ADDRESS>




</BLOCKQUOTE>
