<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>TRIAD Design - Conclusions</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG SRC="/docs/images/triadhead.gif" border=0 ALT="Triad System">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<h2>
Conclusion
</h2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
The Triad project has produced a prototype operating system that
provides security, distribution, and real-time support.  Based on
Trusted Mach, Triad incorporates the security design of this
high-assurance system. Triad utilizes the extensibility inherent in the
TMach design to provide real-time and distribution functionality 
while demonstrating that security has been maintained.
The design of the system displays a number of important traits:
extensibility, reusability, adaptability, modularity, and scalability.
<p>

Extensibility and reusability are closely related.  The reusability of
many system server subsystems allows application development to reuse
software and leverage off of existing server functionality.  As a
result, application development can concentrate on
application-specific functionality rather than type-independent
functionality of distributed object servers in general.  Application
server real-time support can be achieved in a straightforward manner,
as can the transparent distribution of access to application objects.
Replication of application objects can be largely achieved by reuse,
but some application-specific development is required.
<p>

The adaptability of the system stems from the modularity of the design and
implementation. Specific distribution features are each isolated in
a distinct module, which hides the specifics of the feature's implementation.
As a result, the implementation can be adapted for future systems
with different requirements for features, by substituting or augmenting
the algorithms of the current implementation.
For example, the version voting consistency policy could be augmented by 
embedding it in a hierarchical consistency policy, which has better
scalability properties in some cases.
As another example, the specific network topology of a system could be used
to make the best choice in determining which hosts to choose for service
for a replicated object.
Similar extensions and/or customizations could be made in a variety of areas.
The use of the $x$-kernel for protocol implementation leads to a similar
flexibility in adding new protocols to support new network media or
to provide network security.
The use of the scheduler framework in the kernel permits substitution
or addition of real-time scheduling policies.
<p>

In all of these areas, adaptability is necessary for real-time,
distribution, and security. For real-time, individual real-time
systems often have particular requirements for scheduling or
for performance of network media. One system cannot fulfill
the requirements of every real-time system, but the Triad system
is flexible enough to provide adaptability in support of the
real-time requirements of various different systems.
For distribution, scalability is critical because systems of 
differing size will be best served by different algorithms
for many distribution functions. Therefore, the system must
be adaptable enough so that additional approaches to a given
distribution function can be added without perturbing the design of the system.
For security, the flexibility of the network protocol subsystems
is critical to evolving the system to incorporate the cryptographic
mechanisms needed to provide security for distributed computing
in open environments.
<p>
      
Because of all these design features, the Triad system is
able to support a range of systems with distribution, real-time,
and security requirements.
The current system supports the types of embedded command/control systems
that were the target of current work.
The current system can also support some kinds of more general-purpose
distributed systems, at small to intermediate scales.
Greater scaling can be achieved in the future by adapting specific
functional areas of the current system.
As a result, the same distributed operating system can be the base
for a significant class of current real-time systems with security
requirements, while also providing a high-leverage development
platform for a wider range of distributed systems.
<p>

<HR>
<h4>
Acknowledgements
</h4>
We would like to acknowledge the contributions of Mary M. Bernstein,
Jeffrey Jones, Jonathan King, and Jeffrey Graham to the Triad project.
Triad is supported by Rome Laboratory, under U.S. Government contract
number F30602-93-C-0235.
<p>
