<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>TRIAD Design Capabilities</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG SRC="/docs/images/triadhead.gif" border=0 ALT="Triad System">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<h2>
System Capabilities
</h2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
The three primary capabilities of Triad are distributed system
service, support for real-time applications, and the uniform
enforcement of a security policy throughout a Triad distributed
system.  A key part of Triad's architecture (described in
<a href="references.html#TriadArch">[TriadArch]</a>) is its basis on Trusted Mach (TMach)
<a href="footnotes.html#TMach">[1]</a>
  <a href="references.html#TMach">[TMach]</a>,
a high-assurance system base designed to meet B3 requirements for
security functionality and assurance.
<a href="footnotes.html#Eval">[2]</a>
Triad's security capabilities
derive in large part from this trusted system base.  Triad extends the
TMach system so that its security functionality is uniformly and
consistently performed throughout a group of hosts composing a Triad
system.  
<p>

This approach-- to start with a high-assurance trusted system base and add
distributed real-time functionality-- was motivated by our belief that
it would be more likely to yield a high-assurance system than would an
alternative strategy of over-laying trust on an untrusted system
with distributed real-time functionality.
This approach applies particularly well to TMach,
which was designed to be extensible, as a result of its multi-server
architecture and Mach~
<a href="references.html#Mach">[Mach]</a>
microkernel base.
<p>

Triad's real-time design relies on the real-time notion of
<em>
timeliness,
</em>
i.e., the restriction that some computations complete
within a finite time window.
The base of Triad's real-time capabilities is its scheduling subsystem,
which allows threads of execution to set deadlines and which uses
deadlines to determine which threads to schedule.
Such time-bound processing
is ensured by deadline-based scheduling that is
uniformly applied throughout distributed client/server computations.
Triad's deadline-based approach to real-time is indicative of changes
in the real-time system world from as-fast-as-possible processing
to on-time processing.
<p>

Triad's distribution capabilities are enabled by an extension of Mach's
inter-process communication (IPC) service to span multiple networked hosts.
Given this basis, Triad system server software provides a global name
space for distributed, location-transparent access to files and
other objects. Name and file services permit data replication for
high availability and provide automatic failover for fault tolerance.
Because these distribution capabilities are implemented by the O/S,
the Triad system is based on a distributed O/S rather than on
"middleware'' software, which provides some amount of distribution
functionality between networked hosts.
The result is a distributed system in which the existence of separate
hosts is transparent to normal operation.
<p>

Triad's security capabilities are provided by the base TMach system
and by the use of distributed IPC to propagate security data between hosts.
Triad's real-time and distribution capabilities are provided by extensions
both at the level of the Mach microkernel and of the TMach servers.
These four functional areas are described below.
<p>

<b>
Real-time Microkernel:
</b><br>
The Triad microkernel capabilities in support of real-time processing are
real-time scheduling and scheduling coherence.  Real-time scheduling
is required by real-time systems so that the scheduler can take into
account real-time properties such as execution deadlines.  Triad
provides real-time scheduling using the Best Effort scheduling policy
<a href="references.html#BenefitsAccrual">[BenefitsAccrual]</a>
of the Alpha 
<a href="references.html#Alpha">[Alpha]</a>
distributed real-time
system.  However, many real-time systems have different scheduling
requirements, and as a consequence one real-time scheduler cannot
support a wide range of real-time systems.   Triad therefore
incorporates a 
<em>
reusable scheduler framework,
</em>
a modularization
of the Mach microkernel scheduling subsystem.  The framework provides a
clean interface and modular separation between the microkernel scheduling
mechanisms and the scheduling policy.  Scheduling policy modules can
easily be replaced at build time; as a result, Triad is potentially
supportive of a range of real-time requirements, with a small impact
on architectural assurance.
The assurance benefit is a result of the small amount of trusted code
modification required by the replacement of a scheduling policy module.
This assurance benefit is particularly great when compared to the
significant impact on assurance that results from the modifications to microkernel
code required to implement a new scheduler for each new real-time system.
<p>

<em>
Scheduling coherence
</em>
is the property of a real-time system requiring that
a real-time computation be scheduled with uniform scheduling parameters.
Coherence applies to all cases, including those where the computation
includes multiple threads of execution, multiple address spaces,
and is distributed across multiple hosts.
In Triad's client/server architecture, scheduling coherence is
closely linked to the remote procedure call (RPC) paradigm in which
a client requests an operation by contacting a server via Mach
inter-process communication (IPC) and waits for the server's
response via IPC.
Scheduling coherence is provided as a result of 
<em>
thread migration,
</em>
a Mach IPC optimization pioneered at the University of Utah 
<a href="references.html#MigrThread">[MigrThread]</a>.
The Open Software Foundation (OSF) Research Institute has implemented
thread migration in the RPC feature of its real-time
Mach microkernel 
<a href="references.html#OSFrpc">[OSFrpc]</a>,
which is the microkernel base for Triad.
When a client uses Mach RPC to contact a server, the RPC is processed
without a complete context switch and without a change of scheduling parameters.
As a result, local RPCs are coherently scheduled.
Triad also extends this microkernel mechanism to provide distributed
scheduling coherence between hosts.
<p>

<b>
Real-time Servers:
</b><br>
The real-time capabilities of Triad servers are provided by extensions
to TMach servers that permit the servers to process RPCs in a manner
that preserves scheduling coherence.
These extensions required minor localized changes, affecting only the
IPC data packing code and the IPC initialization code that is
common to all TMach servers.
As a result, Triad servers support real-time processing
(by preserving the time-bound scheduling of clients)
in a manner that has no impact on the structure of the TMach servers.
As a result of the small impact of the existing TMach server code base,
the Triad real-time server extensions thus have minimal
impact on the level of architectural assurance provided by the system.
<p>

<b>
Microkernel Distribution:
</b><br>
Distribution of Mach microkernel services is accomplished by a
new component that runs in a separate address space.
As a result, distribution extensions require no modification to 
microkernel software and thus has a much smaller impact
on architectural assurance than would such modifications.
This new component supports a distributed IPC (dIPC) service
that provides to group of hosts the same IPC service that
Mach provides for a single host.
Because Mach uses IPC for access to other microkernel services, dIPC
also provides distribution for other microkernel services.
The role of each host's dIPC server is to forward to other hosts' dIPC
servers any local messages destined for the remote host, to accept
such forwarded messages from remote dIPC servers, and to deliver
such messages to the local recipient.
<p>

The dIPC implementation is based on the <I>x</I>-kernel network protocol
framework 
<a href="references.html#xkernel">[xkernel]</a>
and its implementation of networked Mach IPC 
<a href="references.html#MachNetIPC">[MachNetIPC]</a>.
This implementation is augmented to transport
security data and real-time scheduling data in support of distributed
security mechanisms and distributed scheduling coherence.
These extensions are greatly facilitated by the modular structure
of the <I>x</I>-kernel framework in which is embedded the set of
microprotocols that implement networked Mach IPC.
The extensions consist of adding either new microprotocols or 
new fields to existing microprotocols.
<p>

<b>
Distributed Servers:
</b><br>
Distribution of TMach services is accomplished by the servers' use of
dIPC for communication with remote clients and with remote peer servers.
As a result, remote clients can 
<em>
transparently
</em>
use distributed services;
i.e., they can remain unaware of the location of the servers providing the service.
Remote peer server communication takes place between servers that reside on
different hosts but that implement the same service.
Remote peer server communication allows peers to coordinate their actions
and provide distributed services to clients.
Each Triad host's Name Server cooperates with remote peers
in implementing a uniform distributed name space and uniform application
of security mechanisms to the access of named objects.
Both Name Server and the File Server allow objects to be replicated
for high availability and fault tolerance.
For replicated objects, the servers maintain copies on multiple hosts
and maintain consistency of the copies using a flexible mechanism that
allows different degrees of consistency to different applications.
<p>

This distribution functionality is the core of the Triad additions to
the TMach server TCB. Because distribution functionality is orthogonal to the
original TMach functionality of servers, distribution can be implemented
by additions to the server code base which cause minimal perturbation
on the server code base. As result, the architectural assurance impact
of these additions is minimized.
<p>
<HR>
