<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>TRIAD Design - Footnotes</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG SRC="/docs/images/triadhead.gif" border=0 ALT="Triad Sytems">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<Font size= 4>Footnotes</FONT>
<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<a name="TMach"</a>
[1] Trusted Mach and TMach are Registered Trademarks of Trusted
    Information Systems, Incorporated.

<p>
<a name="Eval"></a>
[2] TMach is currently under evaluation for a B3 TCSEC
    rating and an E5/F-B3 ITSEC rating.

<p>
<a name="Extend"></a>
[3] <a href="references.html#TMextend">[TMextend]</a>
    provides a more detailed discussion of the Name Server
    and the reference monitor of TMach, including its function of
    partitioning all subjects into communicating groups of a single level,
    thus preventing communication between security levels.

<p>
<a name="Dipc"></a>
[4] Further details of this distributed IPC functionality are given in 
    <a href="references.html#MachNetIPC">[MachNetIPC]</a>.

<p>
<a name="Shuttle"></a>
[5] Note that the primary purpose of
    shuttle migration is not to transfer the scheduling context.
    The primary purpose is to perform synchronous IPC without
    a scheduling context switch. In other words, scheduling coherence
    is a beneficial side-effect of a significant performance improvement
    of Mach IPC.

<p>
<a name="POP"></a>
[6] <a href="references.html#TriadPOP">[TriadPOP]</a>
    describes the integrity of security IDs and the unbypassability of
    both the kernel's security ID mechanism and also the servers' use of it.

<p>
<a name="Tagging"></a>
[7] This ability of the dIPC (tagging messages and RPCs with a security
    ID) derives from its being the sole holder of a kernel privilege for
    precisely this purpose. Ordinarily, the kernel tags messages and RPCs
    with the security ID of the sender.  dIPC's use of this privilege is
    the only exception to this rule.

<p>
<a name="Meta"></a>
[8] The scheduling parameter meta-data is obtained from the scheduling
    parameters of the dIPC thread which receives the client's RPC.
    Because of scheduling coherence, this thread's scheduling attributes
    are the same as those of the client's thread.

<p>
<a name="Possible"></a>
[9] In this example, all name space items are either
    directories or files. However, it is possible to have other types
    of item, either objects of system types (e.g., links) or objects of
    application-defined types.

<p>
<a name="NSmore"</a>
[10] Further information about the basic TMach functionality
     of the Name Server is given in 
     <a href="references.html#TMextend">[TMextend]</a>.
     Both 
     <a href="references.html#TMextend">[TMextend]</a> and 
     <a href="references.html#TriadPOP">[TriadPOP]</a> describe the security
     characteristics of the Name Server and File Server in TMach.
     The security behavior of the TMach Name Server and File Server 
     is not changed by Triad, but only extended to operate in a
     distributed environment by means of distributed IPC.
 
<p>
<a name="Policy"</a>
[11] Note that this policy prevents replicated
     name objects from being updated when any replica's host is
     unavailable.  This is a tradeoff between security and continued
     operation in abnormal conditions that is appropriate for the embedded
     systems environment that the current Triad system addresses.
     However, for systems where update during partial downtime is desired,
     the Triad design supports a slightly weaker consistency policy: all
     <em>
     available
     </em>
     replicas must be involved, and the number of replicas
     must be greater than half the total replicas. This prevents irreconcilable
     divergence yet permits an isolated host to operate with
     "out-of-date'' object data that is reconciled when the host rejoins
     the entire system.
  
<p>
<a name="FSmore"</a>
[12] Further information about the basic TMach functionality
     of the File Server is given in 
     <a href="references.html#TMextend">[TMextend]</a>.
<HR>
