<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>TRIAD Design</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG SRC="/docs/images/triadhead.gif" border=0 ALT="Triad System">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<h2>
Design Overview
</h2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Subsequent sections describe the design of the Triad system in
terms of a subsystem-by-subsystem breakdown of each of the
TMach components affected by Triad extensions.
This section provides a high-level overview of Triad in terms
of those components and their interactions.
<p>

<h4>
Triad Design Impact
</h4>

The design of Triad decomposes the system into kernel-level components
and server-level components as illustrated in Figure 1.
Only certain selected portions of each level are affected by Triad,
while the remainder of each level remains in its original state as
in TMach.
<p>

<br>
<a href="/docs/images/components.gif">Figure 1: Triad System Components and Services</a>
<p>

At the kernel level there are two separate components: the OSF RT Mach
microkernel, and the Distributed IPC (dIPC) subsystem, which is implemented
as a separate server task to avoid modification to the microkernel.
As a result of this separation, there are no microkernel changes for
distribution.
Triad changes to the microkernel are limited to real-time changes:
addition of the replaceable scheduling framework, the insertion into
the framework of the Best Effort real-time scheduler. The other critical
real-time aspect of the microkernel, migrating threads and RPC, is a
feature of the OSF RT Mach microkernel.
<p>

At the server level, only two components are affected by the design
of Triad: the Name Server and the File Server.
In addition to these two servers, there are a number of other TMach
servers that are used in Triad with little or no modification and which
have no additional design in the Triad system.
As described in 
<a href="references.html#TMach">[TMach]</a>
and 
<a href="references.html#TriadArch">[TriadArch]</a>,
these other servers provide system functionality for system initialization,
user login, authentication, terminal I/O, trusted path, audit,
and system administration.
<p>

As a result of the limited impact of the Triad design, there
are only four components of the overall system that are affected:
the Mach microkernel, the dIPC server, the Name Server, and the File Server. 
Before moving on to to discussion of each of these, however,
we first describe the overall communication among these
components and how this communication is used to implement
the client requests that are, as a result of Triad's distributed
client/server architecture, the focus of system functionality.
<p>
<a name="Scommarch">
<h4>
Communication Architecture
</h4>

The initial state of Triad communication consists of two basic parts,
both of which involve the Name Server.
On each host the local Name Server is the only component that any other
component can contact. This central feature is essential to the Name Server's
role as mediator and core of the Triad reference monitor.
<a href="footnotes.html#Extend">[3]</a>
<p>

Clients and other servers initially have only a communication
connection to the local Name Server.  This connection is the
capability to send Mach IPC (either messages or RPCs) to a Mach port
held by the Name Server.  With this initial capability clients can use
the Mach kernel's local IPC service to communicate with local Name
Server in order to request access to objects (such as files) and to
obtain further communication capabilities in the form of port rights
for ports held by other servers (such as the File Server).
This first aspect of the initial state is a fundamental aspect
of TMach that is not affected by Triad.
<p>

A second aspect of the initial state is added by the Triad design.
The Name Server is initially the only local component that can
communicate with the local dIPC server; the dIPC server can
communicate with each peer dIPC server via the network.  During
initialization each Name Server uses its privileged communication with
the local dIPC server to request connections to the Name Servers of
other hosts.  Each such connection is in the form of a send right to a
port held by the dIPC server.  With this port right, the
Name Server can communicate with a remote Name Server by sending a
message (or performing an RPC) over this port, using the Mach kernel's
local IPC service.  The message (or RPC) arrives at the local dIPC
Server, which forwards it over the network to the dIPC server
of the host associated with the particular port
used by the sending Name Server.  The remote dIPC server receives the
network communication and delivers the message (or RPC) to its local
Name Server via local IPC.  In the case of RPCs, the second Name
Server's RPC return data follows the reverse path back to the
originating Name Server.
<p>

Given this initial architecture, we can see how distributed
communication is used to implement the distributed file service shown
in Figure 1.  First, a client obtains access to some file by
sending a request to its local Name Server. In the case of a local
file, the Name Server replies to the client with a port right for a
port held by the local File Server; subsequently the client could send
file read and write requests to the File Server directly, using local
IPC. In processing the request, however, the Name Server may determine
that the specific file is not located on the local host, but rather
some other host.  In that case, the Name Server forwards the request
to the remote Name Server using the distributed IPC mechanism
described above; this forwarding is part of the distributed name
service shown in Figure 1.  The remote Name Server
replies with a port right for a port held by
the File Server on that remote host.  While being passed back to the client's
host, the remote-host port right is converted into a port right on the
client's host.  Subsequently, the client makes its request of the
remote File Server in the following manner: the client's request is
sent via local IPC on the local port right and received by the local
dIPC server, which forwards it to the dIPC of the host associated with
that port right.  The remote dIPC server then delivers the message to
its local File Server using local IPC over the port held by the File
Server.
<a href="footnotes.html#Dipc">[4]</a>
As a result of this
arrangement, the distributed IPC is
<em>
transparent,
</em>
i.e., the
client need not be aware of the location of the file or its server,
because in both local and remote cases it simply sends requests via
local IPC. In distributed cases, the local IPC is forwarded to another
host via the dIPC server, but the client is not aware of this.
<p>

Two essential new requirements for the Triad design emerge from
this communication architecture:
first, distributed IPC data must include the same security data
that is present in local IPC, so that remote IPC recipients
can perform security checks in the same manner, regardless
of whether the IPC originated from a local or a remote sender;
second, distributed IPC data must include real-time scheduling data
associated with the sender, so that this data can be used on the recipient's
host to ensure scheduling coherence.
<p>

Given this overall picture of distributed communication, we can
now describe the various design areas of each of Triad's main
components and how these components work together.
<p>

<HR>
<a href="/docs/research/distributed/acsac95/kdesign.html">
<B>Next...</B></A><BR>
