<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>TRIAD Design - Kernal Level Design</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG SRC="/docs/images/triadhead.gif" border=0 ALT="Triad System">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<h2>
Kernel Level Design
</h2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
The design of the system at the kernel level breaks down into two
components, the Mach microkernel (including a new real-time scheduler)
and the new distributed IPC subsystem.
After describing the design of each of these, we summarize the
various dataflows among the kernel, the distributed IPC subsystem,
and upper-level components.
<p>

<h4>
Microkernel
</h4>

The microkernel component can be decomposed into four
major subsystems: process management, device management,
virtual memory (VM) management and inter-process communication (IPC).
Device and VM management are not affected by Triad.
The process management subsystem is the only one of the four
microkernel subsystems which is affected by the design of Triad--
in this case, the scheduling framework.
The IPC subsystem is not affected, although Triad relies on two aspects
of it: the scheduling coherence provided the RPC mechanism,
and the security mechanisms of IPC.
Therefore sketches of these functional areas are provided below,
along with description of the scheduling framework.
<p>

<b>
RPC:
</b>
The overall approach for the RPC mechanism is the implementation
of the Mach thread abstraction in terms of two separate but
related implementation constructs: the thread execution state
and the thread scheduling state, also referred to as a
<em>
shuttle.
</em>
To be ready to receive RPCs, real-time servers allocate
<em>
empty threads,
</em>
i.e., threads with a dormant execution state and an
undefined shuttle.
When a real-time client makes an RPC, a client thread is suspended
and the RPC request data is copied to the server address space.
The client thread, which invoked the RPC, temporarily loses it shuttle
as the kernel migrates the shuttle to an empty thread of the server.
The server thread then begins executing to act on the client's
RPC request data.
<a href="footnotes.html#Shuttle">[5]</a>
Because the server thread uses the client's shuttle, it executes
in the same scheduling context.
When the server thread has completed its computation, it returns from
the RPC: the kernel copies the RPC return data to to client address
space and returns the shuttle to the client thread.
The client then resumes execution in the same scheduling context.
<p>

The resulting scheduling coherence of RPCs allows Triad to avoid
the class of real-time problems known as priority inversion.
For example,
one kind of priority inversion occurs when a high-priority client
relies on a server that executes at a lower priority.
As a result, the server may take longer to complete the client's RPC
and take up an unnecessary amount of a real-time client's deadline.
With scheduling coherence, the server executes in the same scheduling
context as the client it is servicing, so no priority mismatches can occur.
<p>

<b>
Security ID:
</b>
Triad's security mechanisms rest on a simple ID tag implemented by
OSF Mach++ kernel 
<a href="references.html#HLD">[HLD]</a>
and applied to the RT kernel 
<a href="references.html#OSFrpc">[OSFrpc]</a>.
The security functionality of the kernel is provided by the Mach
kernel's security ID feature.  Each Mach task is assigned a security
ID upon creation, and all IPC (both messages and RPCs) are tagged with
the security ID of the sending task.  The Mach kernel does not
interpret security IDs. Rather it simply makes them available to
higher-level components via three means: security ID tagging of IPC;
security ID inheritance during ordinary task creation; and privileged
task creation in which the security ID may be specified by the
creator. In Triad, the right of privileged task creation is retained
by the TCB, assigned to a single component that creates new tasks
with security IDs corresponding to user identity established during
authentication.  In all other task creation, a new task inherits its
security ID from the creating task.  The mediation component of Triad
uses IPC security ID tags to determine the identity of tasks that
request object access via IPC.
<a href="footnotes.html#POP">[6]</a>
<p>

<b>
Scheduling Framework:
</b>
Within the scheduling subsystem, the scheduling framework provides a
separation among the various mechanisms of the scheduler-- e.g.,
queue management, interfacing with the I/O subsystem to
determine when I/O-blocked threads become ready, getting a new thread
to run, loading up registers with the new thread's state-- from the
actual policy of scheduling, i.e., surveying the available threads and
deciding on the basis of their scheduling attributes that one should
run next.  The design of the scheduling framework simply
consists of an interface between the scheduling mechanisms of the
framework and the scheduling policy module.  The interface specifies
various interactions, such as getting the next thread to run (queue
management), dispatching threads (policy execution), getting and
setting of thread scheduling attributes (attribute management), and
assignment of a thread to a particular scheduling policy
(initialization).  The latter interface permits the kernel to support
multiple scheduling policies, so that all threads do not have to be
scheduled according to the same policy.
<p>

<b>
Scheduler:
</b>
The scheduler component is a scheduling policy module that implements
the Best Effort scheduling policy within the scheduling framework of
the kernel.  The implementation of the scheduler component uses an
existing Best Effort scheduler implementation, and therefore there is
no Triad-specific design.  The Best Effort scheduler implements a
policy of shortest deadline first and highest priority first.  In
addition to deadline and priority attributes, there are additional
attributes (used to describe the value of the computation being
scheduled) that are used during overload conditions that eliminate the
overload by dropping low-value computations.
<p>

<h4>
Distributed IPC Subsystem
</h4>

Triad's distributed IPC (dIPC) implementation is based on an
existing <I>x</I>-kernel implementation of networked Mach IPC.
Therefore, the design for dIPC is a decomposition into
separate micro-protocol modules bound together within the <I>x</I>-kernel
protocol framework.
Before describing this decomposition, however, we describe the
two main ways in which the Triad implementation extends the
functionality of the original networked Mach IPC implementation:
security ID tagging of distributed IPC and support for
distributed scheduling coherence.
<p>

Security ID tagging is a feature of the local IPC implemented by the
Mach kernel for both the message and RPC forms of IPC.
The dIPC subsystem extension of this critical security mechanism
is the
<em>
primary security property
</em>
of the Triad design.
Because of the fundamental way that TMach is based on microkernel
mechanisms-- including the security ID-- and because of the
modular architecture of TMach, this distribution extension
of security ID functionality is the
<em>
only
</em>
extension of
kernel mechanisms that is required for distributed security
of TMach operations spanning multiple hosts.
<p>

The dIPC
subsystem uses local IPC and networking to operate in an intermediary
role between IPC senders and receivers on different hosts.  dIPC
forwards messages and RPCs destined for remote hosts, and receives
messages and RPCs from other hosts.  When a dIPC server receives a
local message or RPC destined for another host, the dIPC server
extracts the security ID tag from the message or RPC. It then uses
the network to send the security ID, along with the message or RPC
data, to the dIPC server on the destination host.  When a dIPC server
receives such network data, it performs the following series of steps:
it extracts the security ID and IPC data; it delivers the IPC data via
local IPC to the local recipient; and it tags the delivered data with the
extracted security ID.
<a href="footnotes.html#Tagging">[7]</a>
As a result, each message or RPC delivered by dIPC appears to the
recipient as if it came from a local sender and includes a security ID
tag with the security ID of the sender, just as in local IPC.
<p>

Support for distributed scheduling coherence is accomplished in
a similar manner.
Scheduling coherence is a feature of the RPC form of local IPC implemented
by the Mach kernel. The dIPC server plays a similar role with scheduling
attributes as it does with security IDs. That is, whenever the dIPC
server receives a local RPC, it obtains the relevant scheduling attributes, adds
these as meta-data to the client's RPC, and sends the complete RPC
data and meta-data to the dIPC server on the destination host.
<a href="footnotes.html#Meta">[8]</a>
When the dIPC server receives an RPC, it extracts the
scheduling parameter meta-data from the RPC and uses these values to
set the scheduling parameters of the thread handling the RPC.
As a result, RPC processing on the receiving host is scheduled coherently
with the RPC processing on the sending host.
<p>

Because the dIPC subsystem is implemented as a set of <I>x</I>-kernel
protocols, each of its sub-components is a protocol embedded in the overall
<I>x</I>-kernel framework 
<a href="references.html#xkernel">[xkernel]</a>.
As is usual with the <I>x</I>-kernel, these protocols are arranged in a
hierarchical graph that is more flexible than a linearly hierarchical stack.
Data moves through the graph in two passes.
The first pass is on the sending host, where data moves
from the top, where clients perform IPC with the dIPC server,
down to the bottom, where data traverses the network.
The second pass is on the receiving hosts, where data arrives
over the network and moves up to the top and then to the
receiver via local IPC.
<p>

The dIPC protocol graph is based on that of the <I>x</I>-kernel
MachNetIPC implementation. Each protocol is either reused as is,
reused with modifications, or, in one case, added.  The following
sequence of steps describes the transmission of an RPC down through
this graph on the sending host and back up through the graph on the
receiving host.  The basic function of some protocols is described in
these steps, and the following text notes particularly important functions
of each new or modified protocol.
<p>

When a remote RPC call is performed, the calling thread enters the dIPC
at the MachRIPC protocol layer.  The security ID of the calling task is
added to the message, which is converted into a "network format'' message.
The message is then passed to the SCHED protocol where the complete
scheduling attributes of the calling thread are attached.
The message next passes through various lower-level protocols that
perform such functions as reliable delivery, connection caching,
host failure identification, message fragmentation, and device management.
After the message has been transmitted, the calling thread waits in the
<I>x</I>-kernel for a reply from the destination host.
Meanwhile, on the destination host, the message is re-assembled from
the network data and passed up through the lower-level protocols to
the SCHED protocol. Here, the scheduling attributes are extracted and
assigned to the thread processing the message.
Finally, the message reaches MachRIPC, which extracts the security identity
of the client from the message and sends the message to the receiver.
When the receiver is finished its message processing, it returns from the RPC,
providing RPC return data.
This return results in a message that makes the same traversal down the
protocol graph, over the network, up the graph, and finally to the
waiting thread that originally called the RPC.
At this point the dIPC returns from the caller's RPC and provides the
RPC return data that it obtained from the destination host.
<p>

<h4>
Kernel-level Component Dataflows
</h4>

Having described the high-level design of the kernel-level components,
we can now review the data flow between the components and how that data
flow follows from client requests-- see Figure 2.
<p>


<br><center>
<IMG SRC="/docs/images/diflow.gif"><br>Figure 2: Triad Kernel-Level Data Flow
<p></center>


The upper part of the figure illustrates the chain of data flow
that occurs when a message is sent on a port that the dIPC server
holds in the place of a real recipient on another host.
The IPC data flows from the sender to kernel (which adds the security
ID) and then to the dIPC subsystem and then over the network to the
destination host's dIPC.
In addition, the sending dIPC server obtains the client's scheduling
attributes to attach to the network message as a whole.
The upper part of the figure also shows the reverse chain of events when an
RPC arrives in the form of a network message from another host's dIPC.
The message is reassembled from the network data, and the RPC data,
security ID, and scheduling attributes are extracted.
The dIPC server performs a kernel call to apply those scheduling
attributes to the RPC's processing.
Finally, the dIPC makes a kernel call to deliver the RPC data and
tag it with the security ID.
<p>

The lower part of the figure shows the associated data flow 
between the scheduler and the rest of kernel, via the interfaces
provided by the scheduler framework.
Scheduling attributes flow from the kernel to
the scheduler when the dIPC (or other components) sets these attributes.
Scheduling attributes flow to the kernel from
the scheduler when the dIPC (or other components) gets these attributes.
Queue operations and thread selections flow from the scheduler to
the framework, and thread initialization data flows from the framework to
the scheduler.
<p>

<HR>
<a href="/docs/research/distributed/acsac95/serdesign.html">
<B>Next...</B></A><BR>
<FORM METHOD="GET" ACTION="http://www.tis.com/docs/cgi-bin/AnyURL.cgi">
<select name="level">
<option value="/docs/research/distributed/acsac95/index.html">Introduction
<option value="/docs/research/distributed/acsac95/scapa.html">System Capabilities
