<IMG SRC="/docs/images/triadhead.gif" border=0 ALT="Triad System">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->
<h2>
Server Level Design
</h2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
The design of the system at the server level focuses on the
Name Server and the File Server, the two servers that were
extended from the TMach system base for Triad.
In addition, the server design also allows for some amount
of reuse of type-independent software for application development.
Before describing the design of these two components and
the reusable features, we introduce the functionality of the
two servers by describing how they work together to
provide distributed access to named objects, including files.
<p>

<h4>
Distributed Name Space
</h4>

Figure 3 illustrates the overall functionality of the
Name and File Servers. The figure shows a small name space that
consists of a root directory, a top-level directory for both
users and projects, a user directory for each of users Lee and Pat,
and a project directory for the Triad project.
In each of these leaf directories is a single file.
<p>
<center>
<img width=460 height=582 src="/docs/images/nspace.gif"><br>
Figure 3: Triad Distributed Name and File System
</center>
<p>

An important aspect of the Triad name space is that it is
a global name space.
This entire sample name space is visible in exactly the same way
on all of the three hosts in the example.
Any client on any host can make a request on any object.
However, the name space is also a distributed name space; i.e.,
not every item in the name space is present on every host.
In fact, only a few items are present on every host, that is, fully
<em>
replicated.
</em>
(Typically, the root and a few top-level directories are fully replicated,
to provide a common point of reference for clients on all hosts.)
This approach minimizes the replication overhead of maintaining consistent
copies of named items on every host.
<p>

Figure 3 illustrates the distributed aspect of the sample
Triad name space, by showing for each host which name space items
<a href="footnotes.html#Possible">[9]</a>
are resident on that host, either as a single copy, or as a replica.
The benefits of both replication and non-replication can be seen on
each host in the figure, by examining the parenthesized notation
after the name of each item.
This notation represents the number of replicas and the hosts on which
those replicas reside.
<p>


The figure shows, for example, that Lee's personal files can be accessed
locally only from Host A but that requests on Host A for Pat's personal
file are forwarded to the Name Server on Host B.
A similar situation applies to requests on Host A for files in the
project directory. Such requests are also forwarded, but because the
files are replicated on two hosts, each request may be forwarded to either
of these hosts.
If such a replicated file is modified, the changes are written to
disk not only by the file server on the host of the server that
received the request (possibly forwarded), but also on the other
host that has a replica.
<p>

The role of the File Server is indicated by the relationship between
two aspects of a file's representation: name space information about a file,
and the file contents stored on disk by the File Server.
The relation between them is via a file ID.
the Name Server associates each file ID with a file.
The File Server associates each file ID with disk location data.
The replication of a file is indicated by a vertical arrow
linking a file entry in one File Server, and file entry in another
File Server for the exact same file; the file ID and file data are
the same, but the disk location data is a local matter.
<p>

<h4>
Name Server
</h4>

The Name Server design is based on a high-level decomposition
into several subsystems: a resolver subsystem, a mediator subsystem,
a number of item manager subsystems, a communication subsystem,
a disk access subsystem,
and a distribution/replication subsystem.
The Triad design describes only the last subsystem, while the other
subsystems were developed for the TMach system.
We first give a brief overview of each of these subsystems and their
inter-relationships and then proceed to a more detailed description
of the design for distribution and replication.
<a href="footnotes.html#NSmore">[10]</a>
<p>

<h5>
Basic Subsystems
</h5>

The primary function of the Name Server is to process client requests
to resolve names.  Name resolution is the means by which clients gain
access to named objects, which are referred to as 
<em>
items
</em>
in the name space.  Names refer to a tree-structured name space in which
internal nodes are directories.  As a result, a name is a sequence of
directory names, ending with the name of an item, which may be a
directory or some other kind of item.  Each instance of name
resolution is relative to a specific directory, either to the root
directory or some other directory that the client has previously
resolved.  Therefore, name resolution is an iterative process of
resolving the initial part of the full name to obtain a directory, and
then resolving the rest of the full name relative to the initial
directory.
<p>

At each iteration in a name resolution the mediator subsystem and an
item manager subsystem are involved. The mediator subsystem is called
on to rule on whether the requested access is permitted to the
requesting client, where the permission is based on comparison of the
security attributes of the object and the subject.  For the Triad
system, the security attributes enable mandatory, discretionary, and
integrity checks.  If the mediator rules that access is
permitted-- e.g., the client has lookup permission for the directory
and can proceed to resolve the next element in the full name-- then
the item's manager is involved.  In many cases, this is the Name
Server directory manager subsystem, which accesses the data associated
with the directory item and finds the desired item within that
directory.  This item is returned to the resolver, which then
iterates.  Alternatively the resolver may have reached the last element
of the full name, and the item named is not a directory.  In most such
cases, the named item is managed by another component, e.g., the File
Server.  However, for a few types of items (e.g., symbolic links), a
subsystem of the Name Server itself serves as the item manager. In all
such cases, the subsystem interacts with the resolver in the same manner
as separate item manager components.
<p>

The disk access subsystem handles the stable storage of all object
data for the types of objects managed by the Name Server.  Included in
this data is the data of directory objects, which includes the
security attributes of all objects contained by the directory.  For
types of objects not managed by the Name Server (e.g., files) the type
manager maintains the object data itself.  The disk access subsystem
obtains exclusive access to a disk device and provides an interface
to unnamed files with familiar abstractions such as i-nodes, blocks,
super-blocks, and random access.
<p>

The communication subsystem deals with the use of Mach IPC to receive
requests from clients and to send responses to them. Mach messages
are received, the message contents are unpacked to determine which kind of
Name Server request the client has made, and processing is dispatched
to the subroutine that handles that kind of request.
For the Triad system we have added similar reception and dispatch
processing for the remote procedure call (RPC) form of Mach
inter-process communication (IPC) in addition to the message-passing
form of IPC.
The communication subsystem handles replies to clients, packing the
results into a reply message, and sending the message via Mach IPC.
For the Triad system, we have added similar reply mechanism for
requests that arrive via RPC.
This minor addition is the only change to the TMach-developed subsystems
of the Name Server.
<p>

<h5>
Distribution/Replication Subsystem
</h5>

The distribution/replication subsystem implements all of the 
distribution functionality added by Triad.
This subsystem deals with name 
resolution and directory management in a distributed environment.  The
primary areas of functionality are peer communication, replication,
request forwarding and consistency.
<p>

Peer communication uses a facility provided by dIPC uniquely
to the Name Server, as described in the section on
<a href="sdesign.html#Scommarch">Communication Architecture</a>.
Using a privileged communication port to dIPC, each host's Name Server
can send messages to the Name Servers of other hosts.
In addition, each Name Server uses its dIPC communication with remote
Name Servers to implement a service to other local servers which manage
objects, e.g., the File Server.
This service allows a server for a particular type of object to
request a communication port to the server for the same type on a
remote host. Thus, the peer communication subsystem sets up not
only Name Server peer communication but enables other servers
to set up peer communication.
<p>

The replication subsystem allows for replication of objects managed
by the Name Server, primarily directories. Replication means that
more than one Name Server, each on a different host, maintains a
copy of the replicated directory's data, and each can service
requests for that directory.
When a request updates the directory, there must be co-ordination
with the Name Servers that have  replicas of the directory.
Such co-ordination is performed by the consistency subsystem,
described below.
<p>

The request forwarding subsystem provides a mechanism for a client
to gain access to an object not locally maintained.
When a client requests access to an object not replicated
on its host, the client's local Name Server must forward the request
to a remote Name Server that does maintain a copy.  If the object is
replicated there are multiple candidates for forwarding, and the
request forwarder subsystem must choose one.  Likewise, each Name
Server must also be prepared to receive forwarded requests from peer
Name Servers.
<p>

The consistency subsystem maintains consistency among the various
replicas of each replicated object managed by the Name Server.
Consistency processing is required whenever a client makes an object
request that updates the object.  The Name Server's consistency
policy is simple: available replica must be updated if any replica is
to be updated.  A two-phase locking commit protocol ensures that
every available replica's manager is prepared to receive the updated
value before the updating manager commits the new value.  The purpose
of the consistency policy is to ensure that replicated object data
remains strictly consistent.  The strict consistency requirement is
necessary because Name Server objects contain security-critical data, i.e.,
object security attributes.  When the attributes are changeable (e.g.,
access control lists (ACLs)), a looser consistency policy would allow
two hosts to each have different ACLs for the same object and to
enforce different access controls on it.  It might even be possible
for independent sets of replicas to "diverge'' in different
directions to arrive at irreconcilable replica differences that would
require manual intervention to restore uniform enforcement of the
security policy.
<a href="footnotes.html#Policy">[11]</a>
<p>

Note that real-time functionality, though potentially related, does not
affect the security-critical aspect of the strict consistency policy of
the Name Server. For example, if a deadline expires during an update operation
that is governed by strict consistency, then the operation
is aborted, and strict consistency is maintained.
<p>

<h4>
File Server
</h4>

The File Server design is based on a high-level decomposition into
several subsystems: an item manager subsystem, a communication
subsystem, a disk access subsystem, and a distribution/replication
subsystem.  The Triad design describes only the last subsystem, while the
other subsystems were developed for the TMach system.
<a href="footnotes.html#FSmore">[12]</a>
<p>

As with the Name Server, scheduling coherence results from the
communication subsystem's use of real-time RPC.
With the exception of addition of RPC, the File Server communication
subsystem is unchanged from TMach. It serves the same purpose as does
in the Name Server communication subsystem, although specific
interfaces are different.
<p>

Also unchanged from TMach is the File Server item manager and
disk access subsystems.
The item manager subsystem is similar to the item manager subsystems
of the Name Server. That is, the subsystem provides the implementation
of the operations defined for a particular type-- in this case, files.
Each file operation (e.g., read a block of file data of a given length
starting from a given offset) is implemented in terms of a very
similar operation of the disk access subsystem.
The disk access subsystem is exactly the same as in the Name Server.
<p>

The File Server distribution/replication subsystem has a similar
decomposition to that of the Name Server in that there subsystems
for peer communication, replication, and consistency.  The peer
communication subsystem of the File Server uses the service provided
to type managers by the Name Server's peer communication subsystem, as
described above.  The replication subsystem of the File Server works
with the replication subsystem of the Name Server to perform
replicated object creation and deletion, e.g., to set up replication
attributes and store initial object data.  The consistency subsystem
of the File Server plays the same general role as that of the Name
Server, but the consistency policy (described below) is different.
In contrast to the Name Server's consistency policy, which is restricted
to the strict consistency requirements of Name Server objects, the
File Server's consistency policy is more flexible and is general enough
to support the needs of many kinds of replicated objects.
<p>

In each of these areas of functionality, the distribution/replication
subsystem functionality is generic in the sense that it is not tied to
the specific type of object being implemented: the file.
The only type-specific functionality is the part of the peer-to-peer protocol
used by the consistency subsystem to exchange updated object data.
<p>

The consistency policy implemented by the File Server utilizes the
version voting approach derived from the Cronus system 
<a href="#Cronus">[Cronus]</a>.
Each time a replicated object is written, the manager of that replica
must confer with managers of other replicas to ensure that it has
the most up-to-date version.
However, only a subset of the replicas must be consulted.
The precise number of replicas in existence (the replication factor)
and the number that must be consulted during an update (the write quorum)
may be specified on a per-object basis or inherited during object creation.
A read quorum may also be used to specify the amount of checking that
a manager must do to ensure that its implementation of a read operation is
based on up-to-date object data.
Thus Triad offers a flexible mechanism
that allows dynamic specification of the degree of consistency
desired and also allows tradeoffs between the amount of consistency
processing done during read operations versus write operations.
<p>


<a name="Sfmwk">
<h4>
Application Framework
</h4>

Triad provides an extensible framework that enables the development
of applications utilizing the same real-time and distribution
capabilities provided to the trusted servers.  Much of the
extensibility of the system derives from the Name Server's
implementation of an
<em> 
tem management
</em> 
interface.  This interface is used by all other servers that manage their own
types of object, so an item manager's interaction with the name server is
generic with respect to the type of object managed.  As an example,
the Name Server's service to type managers of peer communication
initialization is a service that could be used by application item
managers as well as the trusted File Server.
<p>

Much of the distribution and real-time software of the File Server is
not specific to files.  As a result this software can be reused for
the development of applications on Triad.  With such reuse,
application software can not only use the distributed real-time
services of Triad, but also provide application service that is itself
implemented with real-time and distribution properties.
<p>

Another application reuse feature of the system is the nature of the
server communication subsystem as a library of reusable code.  Just as
the File Server uses the same communication subsystem as the Name
Server, any application server can reuse the code so long as the
server has a well-defined procedural interface to clients.  As a
result, application server development is isolated from specific
usages of Mach IPC. The real-time aspect of servers is also
implemented in this reusable subsystem, so that any application server
can also preserve the scheduling coherence of any of its clients.
<p>

The replication and consistency subsystems of the File Server also
constitute a body of reusable code for application servers.  For the
most part, the replication and consistency processing (e.g.,
inheritance of replication attributes, and implementation of the version
voting consistency mechanism) is independent of the representation of
the object managed by the server.  However, for the part of the
replication/consistency subsystem that actually sends and receives
object data and/or operation data, type-specific code must be
developed for each application.  Hence, the replication/consistency
subsystem provides a framework for development of distributed servers,
together with most of the functionality required by the framework.
<p>

