<!-- Main Body -->
<a name="Sexample">
<h2>
Sample Scenario
</h2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
This section summarizes the functionality of the system by
providing a detailed example of each component's processing
of one client operation on an object.
Because the operation is on a remotely managed replicated file,
most of the system's components come into play.
In many other cases, of course, locality would reduce the
complexity of the processing.
<p>

Our example begins with a client opening a file.  The client's thread
first sets a deadline for the execution of the function.  To do so,
the client makes a kernel interface function call that results in
kernel execution branching to the scheduler framework, which passes
the deadline to the scheduling policy module.  The policy module
maintains the deadline as an attribute of the thread that made the
deadline-set call.  The policy module sets a timer so that it can tell
if the deadline has expired, entailing that the thread be aborted.
<p>

After performing this bit of real-time responsibility, the client thread
calls the Name Server interface function to open a file.
This function makes an RPC call to the local Name Server.
The RPC is via a kernel call that copies the RPC data from the
client to the server, picks an available server thread, assigns
the client thread's scheduling attributes (including deadline)
to the server thread, and starts the server thread.
Once the server thread executes, it resolves the name and determines
that the designated file is not managed locally but has replicas
on three other hosts. It picks one host and forwards the open operation
to it via a distributed RPC to the Name Server on the other host.
<p>

This RPC transfers control to the dIPC, which sends the RPC data,
including the deadline set by the original client thread, to its peer
on the remote host.  At this point, the client thread, the server
thread, and the dIPC thread are all blocked in a chain, waiting for a
reply over the network.
<p>

On the other host, the dIPC reassembles the RPC from the network data,
using a thread from a pool of worker threads.  When the message is
ready to be delivered, the worker thread makes an RPC to the local
Name Server to complete the forwarding of the open operation.  The
worker thread also blocks.  The Name Server completes the operation
and returns the appropriate return data using the kernel interface for
returning from an RPC.  At this point, the kernel transfers control
back to the dIPC worker thread, which unblocks, receives the RPC
return data from the Name Server, and sends the data over the network
to the dIPC on the client's host.
<p>

On the client's host, the dIPC reassembles the RPC return from the
network data and hands off the RPC return data to the waiting dIPC
thread. That thread also uses the kernel interface to return from an
RPC, and this wakes up the Name Server thread that forwarded the
client's operation. This thread in turn returns to the client, which
now has a running thread with the return data from the RPC for opening
a file.  The deadline has not yet expired, so the client thread lifts
the deadline via the kernel call that causes the scheduling policy
module to cancel the timer it had previously set.
<p>

Now that the client has a descriptor to an open file, it can call file
interface functions to read and write the file.  This is performed in
the same manner that the client's Name Server used to forward the open
operation.  If the client's file operation is for reading, then the
File Server simply gets the required data on disk and returns it to
the client.  If the client's file operation is for writing, then the
File Server first performs consistency processing with the manager of
the other replicas.  Because the file has a write quorum of two
(rather than the total of three replicas), only one other replica must
be consulted.  This consultation involves obtaining a lock from the
other replica's manager.  Also involved is a check that the File
Server has the most up-to-date version before applying the requested
writes.  The lock and version acquisition uses distributed IPC via
peer connections previously obtained from the Name Server.  Once these
prerequisites have been taken care of, the File Server makes the
write requested by the client and then sends the new file data to the
other replica and releases its lock.  Once the other replica has
acknowledged, the File Server finally returns to the client.
<p>

