<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>TRIAD Design</title>
<!-- Copyright 1996 Trusted Information Systems -->
<!-- Design and programming: The James Gang (jgang@jamesgang.com) -->
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" Link="#191970" VLink="#B22222" ALink="#B22222">

<center>
<a href="/docs/research/index.html">
<IMG width=216 height=28  SRC="/docs/images/tisr.gif" border=0 ALT="TIS Research"></A>
<HR  size=2 >
<IMG width=191 height=16 SRC="/docs/images/dissys.gif" border=0 ALT="Distributed Systems Security">
</center>

<HR  size=2 >

<!-- Main Body -->

<a name="TMach"</a>
[1] Trusted Mach and TMach are Registered Trademarks of Trusted
    Information Systems, Incorporated.
<P>
<a name="Band"</a>
[2] Note, we do not consider increased bandwidth due to increased
    processing capacity as an increase in covert channels due to distribution;
    if all the nodes involved were stand-alone nodes, their combined covert
    channel bandwidth would also increase in the same proportion.
    Therefore, the increase has nothing to do with distribution per se,
    but is simply a function of increased processing capacity.
<P>
<a name="Local"</a>
[3] Note that local services can be accessed by remote clients,
    in that each named object can be accessed throughout the
    distributed system, due to the distributed service of the RNS,
    and using distributed IPC for communication.
    However, servers implementing local services need no additional
    functionality, because of the very location-independent transparency
    of Triad's communication and object access functionality.
<P>
<a name="Host"</a>
[4] Note that each host may be running an instance of a non-replicated
    server as well; but for these servers, there is no requirement
    for distributed communication and cooperation with instances
    on other host.
<P>
