<DOCNO>WT08-B05-258</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA002-000014-B012-258</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.rain-tree.com:80/ 204.216.104.96 19970101092046 text/html 9599
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 01 Jan 1997 09:36:20 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5.1
Last-modified: Tue, 10 Dec 1996 00:57:08 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 9416
</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Raintree Marketing Home Page</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bg_home.jpg" bgcolor=#ffffff>

<ul><blockquote>
<img src="hd_home2.jpg" alt="Welcome to the Wealth of the Rainforest - Pharmacy to the World" width=474 height=145>

<p><img src="falls.gif" width=116 height=277 align=right hspace=10 border=1>
<p><b><font size=+2>T</font>he Amazon Rainforest, the world's greatest natural resource,  is the most powerful and bio-actively diverse natural phenomenon on the planet. Since the dawn of man this foreboding  and sometimes frightening frontier has been the source of countless intoxicating  legends, myths and mysteries.  Both Western and European cultures have been drawn to its door in the hopes of finding riches beyond comprehension and artifacts from civilizations that have long since expired with the passage of time. Indigenous inhabitants of the Rainforest often bore the brunt of marauding explorers and conquistadors. Intoxicated by dreams and fantasies of wealth and endless youth, they left behind decimated cultures in their ravenous wake. Although the fabled Fountain of Youth was never  discovered many treasures in gold and gems were spirited away by the more successful invaders of the day.  Little did they know that the true wealth of this priceless resource remained. . . the untold wealth of the indigenous plants. Rich in beneficial nutrients, phytochemicals and active constituents,  the Rainforest Indians and Indigenous People have used them for centuries for  their survival, health and well-being.

<p>

<center>
<script language="javascript">
	if(navigator.userAgent.indexOf("MSIE") != -1)
   document.writeln ('<bgsound src="rain_2.AU" loop=20>');
	else
   document.writeln ('<font  size=2> Control Sound Here <br></font><embed src="rain_2.AU" autostart=true controls=smallconsole loop=true height=15 width=144>');
</script>
</center>

<p><img src="rain2.jpg" alt="Rainforest falls" width=156 height=239 align=right vspace=5>

<p>Thousands of years ago, the native peoples of the Rainforest had developed great centers of learning, including medical schools that taught the role of medicinal plants in healthcare. Given the Age, archaeologists and historians alike have long since documented the high level of sophistication in their knowledge and teachings. With the natural decline of these civilizations, sometimes encouraged by the invaders of the day, many cultural practices, including the teaching of this information declined or were labeled blasphemous and banned entirely by the inquisition that remained.<p>

Among teachings destroyed were the great writings which contained this wealth of knowledge about the uses of plants in medicine and health care. In addition,  the intergenerational transmission of this information shifted from a written to an oral tradition. This has unfortunately led to the realization that,  as a result of the refining of this information over the generations,  this valuable knowledge is probably in greater danger of extinction than the plants themselves. Sadly, modern times have led to the further loss of a great deal of information about plant use. This is a direct byproduct of the Western and European techno-pharmaceutical complexes which have developed and maintained a synthetic-chemical model for the treatment of illness and disease.  Ironically many of the patented chemical pharmaceutical compounds available and marketed today are in fact based on or derived from the active ingredients found naturally occurring in plant sources found in the Rainforest. <p>

<img src="rain4a.jpg" alt="Rainforest pic 2" width=239 height=165 align=right><p>

Many secrets and untold treasures await discovery with the medicinal plants used by shamans, healers and the indigenous people of the Rainforest Tribes. So alluring are the mysteries of indigenous medical knowledge that over 100 pharmaceutical companies and even the US government  are currently funding projects studying the  indigenous plant knowledge. This has fueled a ground swell of demand for ethnobotanists from around the world.  Their work in the Rainforest has resulted in the rediscovery of this long thought lost information. It is the invaluable work of the ethnobotanist to chronicle this information, to document the remains of what once existed, and make it freely available for all to benefit, including future generations.<p>

Extracting these secrets from the jungles is no easy task and sadly, this state of affairs may not last long enough into the future for man to unlock all their secrets. Tragically,  Rainforests once covered  14% of the earth's land surface; now they cover a mere 6% and experts estimate that the last remaining rainforests could be consumed in less than 40 years. Experts agree that by  leaving the Rainforests intact and harvesting it's wealth of  nuts, fruits, oil-producing plants, and medicinal plants, the Rainforest has more economic value than if they were cut down to make grazing land for cattle as so much of it is being lost to.<p> 

<img src="rain5a.jpg" alt="Rainforest pic 3" width=240 height=164 align=right><p>

The Raintree Group of companies advocates the preservation of the Rainforests by promoting the use of sustainable and renewable botanical sources like these important medicinal plants and herbal products found on the following pages. Raintree has assured that all Rainforest products featured here have been ecologically harvested using the assistance of  the Indigenous People, to support their local economy to ensure the plant regeneration for future use.  Please do not support Rainforest products that are not provided in this manner.  In addition, a portion of the sales from the products featured are sequestered and donated to nonprofit  organizations and associations specifically administered for the ongoing study and preservation of the Rainforest and its valuable reserves.<p>

Raintree is proud to a part of this growing awareness and education of the Rainforest and its undeniably documented wealth of medicinal herbs and plants. By creating a market and income from Rainforest herbs and plants, we are enjoined by many others to provide a morally and ecologically balanced relationship that is not only supportive of  the monetary needs of the indigenous peoples of the Rainforest but also the rest of the world's needs for the life supportive ingredient rich botanicals found in this marvel of nature. We hope that you will join us in our endeavors.<p>

Raintree has been privileged to become  associated with the top professionals in the field of Ethnobotany from around the world, and through them we have come to know individuals from the traditional communities of the Rainforest.  We all share a common thread in this relationship, and that is  the preservation of the Rainforest, and the sustaining and supporting of  present and future research and documentation of the medicinal benefits of  Rainforest plants.  This Web page is an extensive compilation of specific information on these plants; their history of use, benefits and clinical documentation.  <p></b>
</blockquote>


